{"title_page": "Assassination of Jamal Khashoggi", "text_new": "{{Short description|assassination of a Saudi journalist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{outdated|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Assassination of Jamal Khashoggi\n| partof      =\n| image       = Jamal Khashoggi in March 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Jamal Khashoggi in March 2018\n| map         =\n{{Location map|Turkey Istanbul\n| alt     = Location of the Saudi consulate in Istanbul\n| lat_deg = 41.0860\n| lon_deg = 29.0121\n| caption = \n| border  = none\n| float = center\n}}\n| map_size    =\n| map_alt     =\n| map_caption = Location of the Saudi consulate in Istanbul, where the assassination took place<ref name=\"cia\"/>\n| location    = Saudi consulate in [[Istanbul]], Turkey\n| target      = \n| coordinates = {{coord|41.0860|N|29.0121|E|display=inline,title}}\n| date        = {{start date |df=yes|2018|10|02}}\n| time        = Some time after 1 p.m. ([[Time in Turkey|TRT]]), when Khashoggi entered the Saudi consulate<ref name=\"cia\"/><ref name=\"NDTV_Fiancee\">{{cite news |title=\"Where Is Jamal?\": Fiancee Of Missing Saudi Journalist Demands To Know |url=https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/where-is-jamal-fiancee-of-missing-saudi-journalist-demands-to-know-1928951 |accessdate=13 October 2018 |agency=The Washington Post |publisher=NDTV |date=9 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091308/https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/where-is-jamal-fiancee-of-missing-saudi-journalist-demands-to-know-1928951 |archive-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| timezone    =\n| injuries    = \n| victim      = [[Jamal Khashoggi]]\n| assailants = \n| weapons     = \n| numparts    = \n| dfens       = \n| motive      = Allegedly to remove a prominent dissident and critic of the Saudi leadership<ref name=\"cia\"/><ref name=\"Washington Post 6 October 2018\"/>\n| inquiry     = \n| coroner     =\n| accused     =\n| convicted   = For murder:<br>Fahad Shabib Albalawi<br>Turki Muserref Alshehri<br>Waleed Abdullah Alshehri<br>Maher Abdulaziz Mutreb<br>[[Salah Mohammed al-Tubaigy|Salah Mohammed Tubaigy]]\n| verdict     = [[Capital punishment in Saudi Arabia|Death sentence]] for murder: five persons<br>\n                Imprisonment for cover-up of the murder: three other persons\n| convictions = \n| charges     = \n| litigation  =\n| website     = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module      =\n}}\n\nThe '''assassination of Jamal Khashoggi'''\u2014a [[Saudi people|Saudi]] [[dissident]], journalist for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', and former general manager and editor-in-chief of the [[Al-Arab News Channel]]\u2014occurred on 2 October 2018 at the [[Saudis|Saudi]] [[Consul (representative)|consulate]] in [[Istanbul]], Turkey, and was perpetrated by agents of the [[Saudi government]].<ref name=\"nytasassination\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/12/world/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-killing-saudi-arabia.html |title='Tell Your Boss': Recording Is Seen to Link Saudi Crown Prince More Strongly to Khashoggi Killing |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=12 November 2018 |access-date=13 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112233122/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/12/world/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-killing-saudi-arabia.html |archive-date=12 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bbcsaudi\">{{cite news |title=Jamal Khashoggi: An unauthorized Turkey source says journalist was murdered in Saudi consulate |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45775819 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 October 2018 |access-date=12 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009004244/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45775819 |archive-date=9 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lured to the consulate building on the pretext of providing him papers for his upcoming wedding, [[Jamal Khashoggi|Khashoggi]] was ambushed, suffocated, and dismembered<ref name=Sakelaris/><ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce>David D. Kirkpatrick & Nick Cumming-Bruce, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/19/world/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-Mohammed-bin-Salman.html Saudis Called Khashoggi 'Sacrificial Animal' as They Waited to Kill Him], ''New York Times'' (19 June 2019).</ref> by a 15-member squad of Saudi assassins.<ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce/> Khashoggi's final moments are captured in audio recordings, transcripts of which were subsequently made public.<ref name=Sakelaris>Nicholas Sakelaris, [https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2019/09/26/Saudi-Prince-bin-Salman-accepts-responsibility-but-not-blame-for-Khashoggi-death/6231569504880/ Saudi Prince bin Salman accepts responsibility but not blame for Khashoggi death], United Press International (26 September 2019).</ref><ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/09/audio-jamal-khashoggi-gruesome-murder-revealed-190909163642769.html Audio transcripts of Jamal Khashoggi's murder revealed], Al Jazeera (10 September 2019).</ref> The Turkish investigation concluded that Khashoggi had been strangled as soon as he entered the consulate building, and that his body was dismembered and disposed of.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/khashoggi-choked-death-dismembered-turkey-prosecutor-181031145816813.html|title=Turkey: Khashoggi strangled immediately after entering consulate|website=Al Jazeera|first=Umut|last=Uras|date=31 October 2018|access-date=31 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031231027/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/khashoggi-choked-death-dismembered-turkey-prosecutor-181031145816813.html|archive-date=31 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>The team had traveled to Istanbul specifically to commit the murder.<ref name=Hubbard>Ben Hubbard, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/03/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-khashoggi-death-penalty.html Saudi Arabia Seeks Death Penalty for 5 Suspects in Khashoggi Killing], ''New York Times'' (3 January 2019).</ref>\n\nThe Saudi government engaged in an extensive effort to [[cover-up]] the killing, including [[Destruction of evidence|destroying evidence]].<ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce/> After repeatedly shifting its account of what happened to Khashoggi in the days following the killing, the Saudi government admitted that Khashoggi had been killed in a [[premeditated murder]],<ref name=\"admission\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/saudi-arabia-now-admits-khashoggi-killing-was-premeditated-n924286|title=Saudis change Khashoggi story again, admit killing was 'premeditated'|website=NBC News|last=Smith|first=Saphora|date=25 October 2018|access-date=25 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025155511/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/saudi-arabia-now-admits-khashoggi-killing-was-premeditated-n924286|archive-date=25 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC_murder_fox\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45935823|title=Saudis now admit journalist was murdered|last=|first=|date=22 October 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=22 October 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021230750/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45935823|archive-date=21 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> but denied that the killing took place on the orders of bin Salman,<ref name=\"admission\"/><ref name=\"fivedeathsentence\"/><ref name=\"fiveexecute\"/> who said he accepted responsibility for the killing \"because it happened under my watch\" but asserted that he did not order it.<ref name=Sakelaris/> Turkish officials released an audio recording of Khashoggi's killing that they alleged contained evidence that Khashoggi had been assassinated on the orders of  Mohammed bin Salman.<ref name=\"nytasassination\"/> By November 2018, the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]], based on multiple sources of intelligence, had concluded that bin Salman had ordered Khashoggi's assassination.<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite news |title=CIA concludes Saudi crown prince ordered Jamal Khashoggi's assassination |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-concludes-saudi-crown-prince-ordered-jamal-khashoggis-assassination/2018/11/16/98c89fe6-e9b2-11e8-a939-9469f1166f9d_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=16 November 2018 |access-date=17 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203145827/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-concludes-saudi-crown-prince-ordered-jamal-khashoggis-assassination/2018/11/16/98c89fe6-e9b2-11e8-a939-9469f1166f9d_story.html |archive-date=3 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same month, the United States sanctioned 17 Saudi individuals under the [[Magnitsky Act]] over the Khashoggi murder, including former bin Salman advisor [[Saud Al-Qahtani]], but did not sanction bin Salman himself.<ref>Kim Hjelmgaard, [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2018/11/15/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-seek-death-penalty-writers-murder/2009827002/ US sanctions 17 Saudi nationals over Jamal Khashoggi's killing], ''USA Today'' (15 November 2018).</ref> U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] disputed the CIA assessment, expressed support for bin Salman, and stated that the investigation into Khashoggi's death had to continue.<ref name=\"nov20\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/unusual-statement-disputing-cia-filled-exclamation-points-trump-backs-saudi-n938526 |title=In unusual statement disputing the CIA and filled with exclamation points, Trump backs Saudi ruler after Khashoggi killing |website=NBC News |date= |access-date=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121024654/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/unusual-statement-disputing-cia-filled-exclamation-points-trump-backs-saudi-n938526 |archive-date=21 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe murder prompted intense global scrutiny and criticism of the Saudi government.<ref name=RashadHosenball>Marwa Rashad & Mark Hosenball, [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi/saudi-sentences-five-to-death-three-to-jail-over-khashoggi-murder-idUSKBN1YR0SY Saudi Arabia sentences five to death over Khashoggi murder, U.N. official decries 'mockery'], Reuters (23 December 2019).</ref> A June 2019 report issued by the [[United Nations special rapporteur]] on [[extrajudicial executions]] [[Agn\u00e8s Callamard]] concluded that Khashoggi's murder was \"a brutal and premeditated killing, planned and perpetrated.\"<ref name=RashadHosenball/> Callamard determined that responsibility for Khashoggi's killing, and the elaborate campaign to cover it up, rests with the highest officials of the [[House of Saud|Saudi royal court]] and that \"credible evidence\" called for the \"investigation of high-level Saudi officials' individual liability, including the crown prince's.\"<ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce/> Callamard's report also detailed the role of the Saudi consul general in Istanbul in coordinating the killing, undercutting the claim that the murder was an unauthorized act by rogue operatives.<ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce/> The special rapporteur called for a criminal investigation to be undertaken by the UN and, because Khashoggi was a resident of the United States, the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]].<ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce/>\n\nIn January 2019, the Saudi government began trials against 11 Saudis accused of involvement in Khashoggi's murder.<ref>Donna Abdulaziz, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-begins-trial-in-khashoggi-murder-11546533394 Saudi Arabia Begins Trial in Khashoggi Murder], ''Wall Street Journal'' (January 3, 2019).</ref><ref name=RashadHosenball/> In December 2019, following proceedings shrouded in secrecy, a Saudi court acquitted three defendants; sentenced five defendants to [[Capital punishment in Saudi Arabia|death]]; and sentenced three defendants to prison terms.<ref name=RashadHosenball/> The acquitted defendants, [[Saud al-Qahtani]] and [[Ahmad Asiri (general)|Ahmed al-Asiri]], were high-level Saudi security officials, while the five men sentenced to death were \"essentially foot soldiers in the killing.\"<ref name=RashadHosenball/> Saudi prosecutors rejected the findings of the UN investigation and asserted that the killing \"was not premeditated\" but was instead  \"taken at the spur of the moment.\"<ref name=RashadHosenball/> UN special rapporteur Callamard said the Saudi verdict was a \"mockery\" because \"the masterminds not only walk free, they have barely been touched by the investigation and the trial.\"<ref name=RashadHosenball/> Human rights group [[Amnesty International]] called the verdict a \"whitewash\" and the Turkish government said that the trials had fallen far short of \"justice being served and accountability.\"<ref name=RashadHosenball/>\n\n==Victim==\n{{main|Jamal Khashoggi}}\n[[File:P06409PS-0571 (3594694537).jpg|4 June 2009 \u2212 after his speech ''[[A New Beginning]]'' at [[Cairo University]], U.S. President [[Barack Obama|Obama]]  participates in a roundtable interview with, among others, Jamal Khashoggi, [[Bambang Harymurti]], and [[Nahum Barnea]].|thumb|right]]  \t \t\n\nKhashoggi was a Saudi journalist,<ref name=\"bbcsaudi\"/> author, and a former general manager and editor-in-chief of [[Al-Arab News Channel]].<ref name=\"speakers\">{{cite web|title=Speakers|url=http://www.prwcdubai.com/english/speaker_article.php?idsp=11|publisher=International Public Relations Association \u2013 Gulf Chapter (IPRA-GC)|accessdate=10 May 2012|year=2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511210004/http://www.prwcdubai.com/english/speaker_article.php?idsp=11|archive-date=11 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He also served as editor for the Saudi newspaper ''[[Al-Watan (Saudi Arabia)|Al Watan]]'', turning it into a platform for Saudi progressives.<ref name=\"afb\">{{cite news |last= Hendley |first= Paul |title= Saudi newspaper head resigns after run-in with conservatives |url= https://en.hdhod.com/Saudi-newspaper-head-resigns-after-run-in-with-conservatives_a3996.html |accessdate= 11 October 2018 |newspaper= Al Hdhod |date= 17 May 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181116112423/https://en.hdhod.com/Saudi-newspaper-head-resigns-after-run-in-with-conservatives_a3996.html |archive-date= 16 November 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nKhashoggi fled Saudi Arabia in June 2017 and went into self-imposed exile in the US. He became a frequent contributor to publications like the ''Washington Post''{{'}}s global opinions section and continued to criticize the Saudi government from afar. He had been sharply critical of Saudi Arabia's [[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia|crown prince]], [[Mohammad bin Salman]], and the country's [[King of Saudi Arabia|king]], [[Salman of Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"bbcsaudi\"/> He also opposed the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey says journalist Khashoggi 'killed at Saudi consulate' |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20181007-turkish-police-journalist-jamal-khashoggi-killed-saudi-consulate-mbs-washington-post |work=France 24 |date=7 October 2018 |access-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009002148/https://www.france24.com/en/20181007-turkish-police-journalist-jamal-khashoggi-killed-saudi-consulate-mbs-washington-post |archive-date=9 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe said, \"The government banned me from Twitter when I cautioned against an overly enthusiastic embrace of then-President-elect [[Donald Trump]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2017/09/18/saudi-arabia-wasnt-always-this-repressive-now-its-unbearable/|title=Saudi Arabia wasn't always this repressive. Now it's unbearable|last=Khashoggi|first=Jamal|date=|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=7 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006173627/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2017/09/18/saudi-arabia-wasnt-always-this-repressive-now-its-unbearable/|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2017, the ''Washington Post'' published its first column by Khashoggi, in which he criticized the prince and the kingdom's direction and advocated for reform in his country. Once Khashoggi's collaboration with the ''Washington Post'' started, he was [[harassment|harassed]] via Twitter from pro-regime bot accounts commonly known as \"the electronic flies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/23/jamal-khashoggi-a-victim-of-saudi-internet-trolls|title=Khashoggi was victim of Saudi internet trolls, friend tells Euronews|date=23 October 2018|publisher=|access-date=2 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103210221/https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/23/jamal-khashoggi-a-victim-of-saudi-internet-trolls|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The \"lord of the flies\", the man who ran social media for crown prince Mohammed, was [[Saud al-Qahtani]]. The crown prince Mohammed ordered a zero-tolerance campaign against dissents, spearheaded by Qahtani, who is implicated in the murder of Khashoggi.<ref name=\"reut22Oct\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-adviser-insight/how-the-man-behind-khashoggi-murder-ran-the-killing-via-skype-idUSKCN1MW2HA |title=How the man behind Khashoggi murder ran the killing via Skype |agency=Reuters |date=22 October 2018 |access-date=22 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115040933/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-adviser-insight/how-the-man-behind-khashoggi-murder-ran-the-killing-via-skype-idUSKCN1MW2HA |archive-date=15 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"nyt20Oct\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/20/us/politics/saudi-image-campaign-twitter.html |title=Saudis' Image Makers: A Troll Army and a Twitter Insider |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Katie |last=Benner |first2=Mark |last2=Mazzetti |first3=Ben |last3=Hubbard |first4=Mike |last4=Isaac |date=20 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115201738/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/20/us/politics/saudi-image-campaign-twitter.html |archive-date=15 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nJust before his assassination, Khashoggi was launching projects to combat online abuse in an attempt to consolidate the [[Opposition (politics)|opposition]] and accuse crown prince Mohammed of mismanaging the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia (KSA). Khashoggi collaborated with Omar Abdelaziz, one of most visible public critics of the Saudi regime abroad who had received asylum in Canada, on a range of projects. One project was named Geish al-Nahl \u062c\u064a\u0634 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u062d\u0644 (Army of the Bees or The Bees Army). They wanted to create a counterpoint to the regime's propaganda machine{{snd}} \"a network of pro-democracy activists who would post and amplify one another's messages about Saudi political issues\".<ref name=\"FoPo19Oct\" /> Abdulaziz said they wanted \"to talk about the dissidents, the political prisoners, freedom of speech, human rights\" and \"make people aware of what's really happening\".<ref name=\"FoPo19Oct\">{{cite web |last1=Elias Groll |title=The Kingdom's Hackers and Bots Saudi Arabia is using cutting-edge technology to track dissidents and stifle dissent. |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/10/19/the-kingdoms-hackers-and-bots-saudi-dissident-khashoggi/ |website=foreignpolicy.com |accessdate=19 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020015413/https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/10/19/the-kingdoms-hackers-and-bots-saudi-dissident-khashoggi/ |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> And the Bee Movement should also provide [[cybersecurity]] to \"people living in Saudi Arabia and other oppressive regimes in the Middle East\" in need of a safe way to express themselves.<ref name=\"Ind20Oct\">{{cite news |last1=Bel Trew |title=Bee stung: Was Jamal Khashoggi the first casualty in a Saudi cyberwar? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-cyberwar-trolls-bee-army-missing-journalist-turkey-us-a8591051.html |work=The Independent |date=20 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107064614/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-cyberwar-trolls-bee-army-missing-journalist-turkey-us-a8591051.html |archive-date=7 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> As Khashoggi wrote in his last, posthumously published, column, he was of the opinion that \"What the Arab world needs most is [[free expression]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jamal Khashoggi |title=What the Arab world needs most is free expression |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/global-opinions/jamal-khashoggi-what-the-arab-world-needs-most-is-free-expression/2018/10/17/adfc8c44-d21d-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html |website=The Washington Post |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020001008/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/global-opinions/jamal-khashoggi-what-the-arab-world-needs-most-is-free-expression/2018/10/17/adfc8c44-d21d-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-saudi-princes-crackdown-was-confidant-tied-to-khashoggi-killing-1541178150|title=Behind Saudi Prince's Crackdown Was Confidant Tied to Khashoggi Killing|first1=Margherita|last1=Stancati|first2=Summer|last2=Said|date=2 November 2018|publisher=|accessdate=7 February 2019|via=wsj.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190205161652/https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-saudi-princes-crackdown-was-confidant-tied-to-khashoggi-killing-1541178150|archive-date=5 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKhashoggi and Abdelaziz were also working on a short film, showing how the Saudi leadership was dividing the country, a website tracking human rights and the new [[Foundation (nonprofit)|foundation]] \"Democracy for the Arab World Now\" (DAWN) Khashoggi was forming. They tried to keep their work secret from Saudi persecution. In late September 2018, Khashoggi met with friends in London to discuss his various plans.<ref>{{cite web |last1=[[Joby Warrick]], Loveday Morris, [[Souad Mekhennet]] |title=In death, Saudi writer's mild calls for reform grew into a defiant shout |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-death-saudi-writers-mild-calls-for-reform-grew-into-a-defiant-shout/2018/10/20/8fa185cc-d48b-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=20 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107232542/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-death-saudi-writers-mild-calls-for-reform-grew-into-a-defiant-shout/2018/10/20/8fa185cc-d48b-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html |archive-date=7 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn summer 2018, Abdulaziz's [[cellphone]] was infected with a [[surveillance]] tool. This was first revealed on 1 October 2018 in a detailed forensic report by [[Citizen Lab]],<ref name=\"CiLab1Oct\">{{cite web |last1=By Bill Marczak, John Scott-Railton, Adam Senft, Bahr Abdul Razzak, Ron Deibert |title=The Kingdom Came to Canada How Saudi-Linked Digital Espionage Reached Canadian Soil |url=https://citizenlab.ca/2018/10/the-kingdom-came-to-canada-how-saudi-linked-digital-espionage-reached-canadian-soil/ |publisher=Citizen Lab |date=1 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108025746/https://citizenlab.ca/2018/10/the-kingdom-came-to-canada-how-saudi-linked-digital-espionage-reached-canadian-soil/ |archive-date=8 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> a [[University of Toronto]] project that investigates digital espionage against [[civil society]]. Citizen Lab concluded with a \"high degree of confidence\" that his cellphone was successfully targeted with [[NSO Group]]'s [[Pegasus (spyware)|Pegasus spyware]] and attributed this infection to an operator linked to \"Saudi Arabia's government and security services\".<ref name=\"CiLab1Oct\" /> NSO's Pegasus, of which KSA has emerged as one of its biggest operators, is one of the most advanced spyware tools available. It is designed to infect cell phones without being detected. Among other known cases, KSA is believed to have used NSO software to target London-based Saudi dissident [[Yahya Assiri]], a former Royal Saudi Air Force officer and founder the [[human rights organisation]] [[ALQST]] and an [[Amnesty International]] researcher.<ref>{{cite web |title=Amnesty International Among Targets of NSO-powered Campaign |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/research/2018/08/amnesty-international-among-targets-of-nso-powered-campaign/ |website=amnesty.org |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001225006/https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/research/2018/08/amnesty-international-among-targets-of-nso-powered-campaign/ |archive-date=1 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Loveday Morris and Zakaria Zakaria |title=Secret recordings give insight into Saudi attempt to silence critics |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/secret-recordings-give-insight-into-saudi-attempt-to-silence-critics/2018/10/17/fb333378-ce49-11e8-ad0a-0e01efba3cc1_story.html |website=The Washington Post |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107232559/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/secret-recordings-give-insight-into-saudi-attempt-to-silence-critics/2018/10/17/fb333378-ce49-11e8-ad0a-0e01efba3cc1_story.html |archive-date=7 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThrough their sophisticated spyware attack on Abdulaziz's phone, the Saudi regime would have had a direct line into Khashoggi's private thoughts, and access to hours of conversations between the two men. Abdulaziz recalled: \"Jamal was very polite in public, but in private, he spoke more freely{{snd}} he was very very critical of the crown prince.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Avi Asher-Schapiro |title=How the Saudis may have spied on Jamal Khashoggi |url=https://cpj.org/blog/2018/10/how-the-saudis-may-have-spied-on-jamal-khashoggi.php |website=[[Committee to Protect Journalists]] |date=31 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108030351/https://cpj.org/blog/2018/10/how-the-saudis-may-have-spied-on-jamal-khashoggi.php |archive-date=8 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 September, just eleven days before Khashoggi was murdered in the Saudi consulate, he made a declaration of support for the Bees Movement. Using the Bee Army's first [[hashtag]] \"what do you know about bees\" he tweeted \"They love their home country and defend it with truth and rights\".<ref name=\"Ind20Oct\" />\n\nOn 9 October, one week after his disappearance, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' published an article in which Hatice Cengiz, Khashoggi's fianc\u00e9, claimed that he had applied for [[U.S. citizenship]].<ref name=\"WaPoCengiz9-10-2018\">{{cite web |last1=Hatice Cengiz |title=Please, President Trump, shed light on my fiance's disappearance |website=The Washington Post |date=9 October 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/10/09/please-president-trump-shed-light-on-my-fiances-disappearance |access-date=29 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030035528/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/10/09/please-president-trump-shed-light-on-my-fiances-disappearance/ |archive-date=30 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 October, The [[Wilson Center]] issued a statement saying that they had offered him a [[fellow]]ship at the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]] (or Wilson Center), located in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/article/statement-jamal-khashoggi |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223223759/https://www.wilsoncenter.org/article/statement-jamal-khashoggi |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Yah15102018\">{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Nazaryan |title=Think tanks reconsider Saudi support amid Khashoggi controversy |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/think-tanks-reconsider-saudi-support-amid-khashoggi-controversy-193104698.html |publisher=Yahoo News |date=15 October 2018 |access-date=28 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028073900/https://www.yahoo.com/news/think-tanks-reconsider-saudi-support-amid-khashoggi-controversy-193104698.html |archive-date=28 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 October, Marc Owen Jones, an assistant professor at [[Hamad Bin Khalifa University]] in Doha who researched Arab propaganda and has monitored Saudi Twitter bots for two years, said he has seen a massive surge in pro-regime Twitter activity, and in the creation of troll accounts, since Khashoggi went missing: \"There was such a huge spike in October in bot accounts and the use of the hashtags praising the crown prince, it's absurd\".<ref name=\"Ind20Oct\" />\n\nAfter Khashoggi's assassination, the Saudi cyber-operations were the focus of global scrutiny. The [[Government of Canada]] started an investigation in to those malicious cyberattacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2018/11/21/exclusive-saudi-dissidents-hit-with-stealth-iphone-spyware-before-khashoggis-murder/|title=Exclusive: Saudi Dissidents Hit With Stealth iPhone Spyware Before Khashoggi's Murder|first=Thomas|last=Brewster|website=Forbes|accessdate=7 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128002753/https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2018/11/21/exclusive-saudi-dissidents-hit-with-stealth-iphone-spyware-before-khashoggis-murder/|archive-date=28 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018 Omar Abdulaziz granted [[CNN]] access to his text messages with Jamal Khashoggi, where the two discussed their sharp criticism and political opposition to Mohammed bin Salman.<ref>{{cite web |title=Khashoggi messages reveal sharp criticism of MBS |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A03r8oGCe3M |website=Youtube |publisher=CNN |date=2 December 2018 |access-date=3 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203120739/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A03r8oGCe3M |archive-date=3 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Nina dos Santos and Michael Kaplan |title=Jamal Khashoggi's private WhatsApp messages may offer new clues to killing |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/12/02/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-whatsapp-messages-intl/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=3 December 2018 |access-date=3 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203074511/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/12/02/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-whatsapp-messages-intl/index.html |archive-date=3 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Abdulaziz filed a lawsuit against an Israeli company [[NSO Group|NSO Group Technologies]] that allowed his smartphone to be taken over and his communications to be spied on by the Saudi regime.<ref>{{cite web |last1=David D. Kirkpatrick |title=Israeli Software Helped Saudis Spy on Khashoggi, Lawsuit Says |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/02/world/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-spyware-israel.html |publisher=NYT |date=2 December 2018 |access-date=3 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203034630/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/02/world/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-spyware-israel.html |archive-date=3 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===US intelligence reports===\n''The Washington Post'' reported on 10 October 2018 that [[United States Intelligence Community|U.S. intelligence]] intercepted communications of Saudi officials discussing a plan ordered by the Crown Prince Bin Salman, to capture Khashoggi from his home in Virginia.<ref name=\"WaPo 10-10-2018\">{{cite web |title=Crown prince sought to lure Khashoggi back to Saudi Arabia and detain him, U.S. intercepts show |website=The Washington Post |date=10 October 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/crown-prince-sought-to-lure-khashoggi-back-to-saudi-arabia-and-detain-him-us-intercepts-show/2018/10/10/57bd7948-cc9a-11e8-920f-dd52e1ae4570_story.html |access-date=10 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011020534/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/crown-prince-sought-to-lure-khashoggi-back-to-saudi-arabia-and-detain-him-us-intercepts-show/2018/10/10/57bd7948-cc9a-11e8-920f-dd52e1ae4570_story.html |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"WaPo 2018\">{{cite web |title=Saudis are said to have lain in wait for Jamal Khashoggi |website=The Washington Post |date=10 October 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/saudis-lay-in-wait-for-jamal-khashoggi-and-left-turkey-quickly-sources-say/2018/10/09/0e283e2e-cbc5-11e8-ad0a-0e01efba3cc1_story.html |access-date=9 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010013836/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/saudis-lay-in-wait-for-jamal-khashoggi-and-left-turkey-quickly-sources-say/2018/10/09/0e283e2e-cbc5-11e8-ad0a-0e01efba3cc1_story.html |archive-date=10 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The intercepted communications were regarded as significant because Khashoggi had bought a home in [[McLean, Virginia]],<ref>{{cite news |title=For Khashoggi, a Tangled Mix of Royal Service and Islamist Sympathies |website=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/14/world/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia.html |date=14 October 2018 |access-date=23 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017155108/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/14/world/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia.html |archive-date=17 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> where he lived after fleeing the [[KSA]]. Khashoggi had obtained an [[O visa]]{{snd}} also known as the \"genius\" visa, that offers individuals of \"extraordinary ability and achievement\" in the sciences, arts, education, and other fields and are recognized internationally{{snd}} he had applied for permanent residency status, and three of his children were US citizens.<ref>{{cite news |title=Friends of Saudi dissident say he failed to return after visit to Istanbul consulate |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/03/saudi-dissident-jamal-khashoggi-worry-after-his-absence-in.html |accessdate=25 October 2018 |work=CNBC |agency=Reuters |date=2 October 2018 |quote=Khashoggi was in the United States on an O-visa |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025150231/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/03/saudi-dissident-jamal-khashoggi-worry-after-his-absence-in.html |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"qz25102018\">{{cite news |last1=Heather Timmons |title=What does the US owe Jamal Khashoggi? |url=https://qz.com/1428499/jamal-khashoggi-what-trump-owes-khashoggi-under-us-law-and-constitution/ |accessdate=25 October 2018 |work=Quartz |date=19 October 2018 |quote=Khashoggi was living in the United States on an 'O' visa ... Three of Khashoggi's children are US citizens. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025185924/https://qz.com/1428499/jamal-khashoggi-what-trump-owes-khashoggi-under-us-law-and-constitution/ |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> As a [[Resident of the united states|legal resident of the United States]] Khashoggi was entitled to protection. Under a directive adopted in 2015, the US intelligence community has a \"duty to warn\" people{{snd}} including those who are not US citizens{{snd}} who are at risk of being kidnapped or killed. This directive was a central aspect of the conversation about the US's response to Khashoggi's disappearance.\n\nAccording to the [[National Security Agency]] (NSA) officials, the [[White House]] was warned of this threat through official intelligence channels.<ref name=\"Obs\">{{cite web| title=NSA: White House Knew Jamal Khashoggi Was In Danger| website=Observer| url=https://observer.com/2018/10/nsa-source-white-house-knew-jamal-khashoggi-danger| date=10 October 2018| access-date=20 October 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013053921/https://observer.com/2018/10/nsa-source-white-house-knew-jamal-khashoggi-danger/| archive-date=13 October 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> The Office of the [[Director of National Intelligence]] (DNI) of [[Dan Coats]] declined to comment on why Khashoggi was not warned.<ref name=\"qz25102018\" /> 55 members of Congress demanded in a letter clarity from DNI Dan Coats on what the intelligence community knew about the risk Khashoggi faced before his disappearance and whether American officials attempted to notify him that his life was in danger. In the letter, they sought insight into everything the NSA knows about phone calls and emails from Saudi officials on the Khashoggi case.<ref>{{cite web |title=Au\u00dfenminister Saudi-Arabiens sieht T\u00f6tung Khashoggis als Fehler |website=Der Standard |date=21 October 2018 |url=https://derstandard.at/2000089809286/US-Praesident-Trump-in-Fall-Khashoggi-unter-Druck |language=de |access-date=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025193735/https://derstandard.at/2000089809286/US-Praesident-Trump-in-Fall-Khashoggi-unter-Druck |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Knight First Amendment Institute at [[Columbia University]] filed a lawsuit against five US intelligence services \"seeking immediate release of records concerning U.S. intelligence agencies' compliance or non-compliance with their 'duty to warn' reporter Jamal Khashoggi of threats to his life or liberty\". The [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] joined the legal effort.<ref>{{cite web |title=US intelligence being sued for failing to warn Khashoggi of threat |url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20181121-us-intelligence-being-sued-for-failing-to-warn-khashoggi-of-threat/ |publisher=The Middle East Monitor |date=21 November 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123004610/https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20181121-us-intelligence-being-sued-for-failing-to-warn-khashoggi-of-threat/ |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Knight Institute Sues to Learn Whether U.S. Intelligence Agencies Complied With \"Duty to Warn\" Reporter Jamal Khashoggi of Threats to His Life |url=https://knightcolumbia.org/news/knight-institute-sues-learn-whether-us-intelligence-agencies-complied-duty-warn-reporter-jamal |publisher=Knight First Amendment Institute |date=20 November 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716083047/https://knightcolumbia.org/news/knight-institute-sues-learn-whether-us-intelligence-agencies-complied-duty-warn-reporter-jamal |archive-date=16 July 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 November, [[Central Intelligence Agency]] members who internally analyzed multiple sources of intelligence concluded that Mohammed bin Salman ordered Khashoggi's assassination.<ref name=\"cia\"/> On 20 November, US President [[Donald Trump]] disputed the CIA assessment and stated that the investigation into Khashoggi's death had to continue.<ref name=\"nov20\"/>\n\n==Disappearance==\n[[File:Ghanem al-Dosari.jpg|Saudi Arabian activist [[Ghanem al-Dosari]] at a protest outside the [[Natural History Museum, London]], 11 October 2018, after the disappearance of Jamal Kashoggi. The Saudi embassy was holding a Saudi National Day celebration at the museum.|thumb|right]]\n[[File:Consulate General of Saudi Arabia in Istanbul.jpg|The Saudi consulate in Istanbul, 16 October 2018,  after Khashoggi's disappearance.|thumb|right]]\nOver the year 2017, the House of Saud appealed to Khashoggi to return to Riyadh and resume his services as a media advisor to the royal court. But he declined in fear that it was a ruse and that upon returning he would be imprisoned or worse. Khashoggi met with crown prince Mohammed's brother [[Khalid bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Khalid]] at the [[Embassy of Saudi Arabia in Washington, D.C.|Saudi embassy in Washington]], in \"early 2018 or late 2017.\"<ref name=\"LedermanOct22\">{{cite web |last1=Josh Lederman |title=Khashoggi met with crown prince's brother amid efforts to return him to Saudi Arabia |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/mideast/khashoggi-met-crown-prince-s-brother-amid-efforts-return-him-n923031 |date=22 October 2018 |access-date=2 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102080709/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/mideast/khashoggi-met-crown-prince-s-brother-amid-efforts-return-him-n923031 |archive-date=2 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2018 Khashoggi visited the Washington embassy again, to retrieve paperwork for his pending marriage to his Turkish fianc\u00e9e, Hatice Cengiz. He tried to complete everything in the U.S. but was instead lured to the Saudi Arabian consulate in Turkey, where his fianc\u00e9e lived.<ref>{{cite news |title=Did Embassy in DC send Khashoggi to Istanbul? |url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/09/did-embassy-in-dc-send-khashoggi-to-istanbul |agency=Reuters and NBC |publisher=Euronews |date=9 October 2018 |access-date=2 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010060724/https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/09/did-embassy-in-dc-send-khashoggi-to-istanbul |archive-date=10 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=[[Boris Johnson]] |title=The murder of Jamal Khashoggi was a barbaric act. We mustn't let Saudi Arabia off the hook |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/21/murder-jamal-khashoggi-barbaric-act-mustnt-let-saudi-arabia/ |quote=First there was the transparent ruse by which the Saudi-born Washington Post columnist was tricked into endangering himself by leaving the United States. |work=The Telegraph |date=21 October 2018 |access-date=2 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102123432/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/21/murder-jamal-khashoggi-barbaric-act-mustnt-let-saudi-arabia/ |archive-date=2 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKhashoggi's first visit to the Saudi consulate in Istanbul was on 28 September 2018{{snd}} where he showed up unannounced. Having divorced his wife, who had remained in Saudi Arabia, he went to the consulate to obtain a document certifying that he was no longer married so he could marry his Turkish fianc\u00e9e. Before that visit he \"sought assurances about his safety from friends in the US\" and instructed his fianc\u00e9e to contact Turkish authorities if he failed to emerge.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/08/jamal-khashoggi-turkey-search-black-van-carried-body-saudi-arabia|title=Jamal Khashoggi: Turkey hunts black van it believes carried body|first1=Martin|last1=Chulov|first2=Patrick|last2=Wintour|date=9 October 2018|website=the Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215220703/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/08/jamal-khashoggi-turkey-search-black-van-carried-body-saudi-arabia|archive-date=15 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He received a warm welcome from officials, and was told to return to the consulate on 2 October. \"He was very pleased with their nice treatment and hospitality\", she later said.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/khashoggi-lured-back-saudi-consulate-warm-greeting-time/story?id=58857344|title=Though Khashoggi didn't suspect he may be in danger, he was still apprehensive|first=A. B. C.|last=News|date=30 October 2018|website=ABC News|access-date=2 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102062814/https://abcnews.go.com/International/khashoggi-lured-back-saudi-consulate-warm-greeting-time/story?id=58857344|archive-date=2 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 September Khashoggi traveled to London and spoke at a conference. On 1 October Khashoggi returned to Istanbul, and he told a friend that he was worried about being kidnapped and sent back to KSA.<ref name=\"TNYT30102018\" />\n\nMeanwhile, at around 16:30, a three-person Saudi team arrived in Istanbul on a scheduled flight, checked in to their hotels then visited the consulate, according to President Erdogan. Another group of officials from the consulate traveled to a forest in Istanbul's outskirts and to the nearby city of Yalova on a \"reconnaissance\" trip. Erdogan said a \"road map\" to kill Khashoggi was devised in Saudi Arabia during this time. In the night of 2 October, a 15-member group arrived from Riyadh on two private Gulfstream jets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/10/23/world/europe/ap-saudi-arabia-writer-killed-timeline.html|title=Key Moments Surrounding the Killing of Jamal Khashoggi|publisher=|access-date=2 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103210118/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/10/23/world/europe/ap-saudi-arabia-writer-killed-timeline.html|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 October 2018 CCTV showed the suspected agents entering the consulate around noon. Khashoggi arrived about an hour later, accompanied by his fianc\u00e9e Cengiz, whom he entrusted with two [[cell phone]]s while she waited outside for him.<ref name=\"TNYT30102018\">{{cite news |title=What Happened to Jamal Khashoggi? |website=The New York Times |date=3 October 2018 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/03/world/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-journalist-istanbul.html |access-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020052554/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/03/world/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-journalist-istanbul.html |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"AlJa8Oct2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/erdogan-closely-case-saudi-critic-jamal-khashoggi-181007143237024.html|title=Erdogan on Khashoggi vanishing: Upsetting this happens in Turkey|date=8 October 2018|access-date=19 October 2018|website=Al Jazeera|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019041311/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/erdogan-closely-case-saudi-critic-jamal-khashoggi-181007143237024.html|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC_8Oct2018\">{{cite news |title= Saudi journalist Jamal Khashoggi disappears after entering Saudi Arabia's consulate in Istanbul |url= http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-07/turkish-authorities-investigate-disappearance-of-jamal-khashoggi/10348304 |agency= [[Reuters]] |publisher= [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date= 7 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181017115417/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-07/turkish-authorities-investigate-disappearance-of-jamal-khashoggi/10348304 |archive-date= 17 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> He entered the consulate, through main entrance, at around 1 pm.<ref name=\"NDTV_Fiancee\"/> As he had not come out by 4 pm, even though the working hours of the consulate were until 3:30 pm,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://time.com/5416396/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-journalist-missing/ |title=A Columnist Walked Into Saudi Arabia's Consulate. Then He Went Missing |access-date=11 October 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011020839/http://time.com/5416396/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-journalist-missing/ |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cengiz contacted the authorities, phoning Khashoggi's friend, Yasin Aktay, an adviser to President Erdogan,<ref>{{cite web | title=Seine Verlobte im Interview: Aus diesem Grund ging Khashoggi beim zweiten Mal unbesorgt in das Konsulat | website=[[Die Welt]] | date=26 October 2018 | url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article182794750/Seine-Verlobte-im-Interview-Aus-diesem-Grund-ging-Khashoggi-beim-zweiten-Mal-unbesorgt-in-das-Konsulat.html | language=de | access-date=30 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208163013/https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article182794750/Seine-Verlobte-im-Interview-Aus-diesem-Grund-ging-Khashoggi-beim-zweiten-Mal-unbesorgt-in-das-Konsulat.html | archive-date=8 December 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> reported him missing and the police then started an investigation.\n\nThe Saudi government said that he had left the consulate<ref name=\"SPA1\">{{cite news |url= https://www.spa.gov.sa/1822222 |title= News snippet |publisher= [[Saudi Press Agency]] |date= 4 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181006075206/https://www.spa.gov.sa/1822222 |archive-date= 6 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC1\">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45758096 |title= Jamal Khashoggi: Washington Post blanks out missing Saudi writer's column |publisher= BBC |date= 5 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181019093042/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45758096 |archive-date= 19 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\"NPR1\">{{cite news |first= Sasha |last= Ingber |url= https://www.npr.org/2018/10/04/654591662/saudi-critic-vanishes-after-visiting-consulate-prompting-fear-and-confusion |title= Saudi Critic Vanishes After Visiting Consulate, Prompting Fear And Confusion |publisher= [[NPR]] |date= 4 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181019010138/https://www.npr.org/2018/10/04/654591662/saudi-critic-vanishes-after-visiting-consulate-prompting-fear-and-confusion |archive-date= 19 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> via a back entrance.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/10/alleged-saudi-hit-squad-linked-to-jamal-khashoggi-disappearance |title=Jamal Khashoggi: details of alleged Saudi hit squad emerge |last=Chulov |first=Martin |date=10 October 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=11 October 2018 |last2=McKernan |first2=Bethan |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011021035/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/10/alleged-saudi-hit-squad-linked-to-jamal-khashoggi-disappearance |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Cabinet Erdo\u011fan IV|Turkish government]] first said that he was still inside, and his fianc\u00e9e and friends said that he was missing.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/03/world/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-journalist-istanbul.html |title= What Happened to Jamal Khashoggi? Conflicting Reports Deepen a Mystery |first= Carlotta |last= Gall |date= 3 October 2018 |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181020052554/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/03/world/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-journalist-istanbul.html |archive-date= 20 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nTurkish authorities have claimed that security camera footage of the day of the incident was removed from the consulate and that Turkish consulate staff were abruptly told to take a holiday on the day Khashoggi disappeared while inside the building.<ref name=\"guardian2\">{{cite news|date=9 October 2018|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/09/khashoggi-case-cctv-disappears-from-saudi-consulate-in-turkey|title=Khashoggi case: CCTV disappears from Saudi consulate in Turkey|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020131856/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/09/khashoggi-case-cctv-disappears-from-saudi-consulate-in-turkey|archive-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[General Directorate of Security (Turkey)|Turkish police]] investigators told the media that the recordings from the security cameras did not show any evidence of Khashoggi leaving the consulate.<ref name=\"NH_Thriller\"/> A security camera was located outside the consulate's front which showed him entering but not leaving, while another camera installed at a preschool opposite the rear entrance of the consulate also did not show him leaving.<ref name=\"NH_Thriller\">{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Joan |title=Jamal Khashoggi Case: A contemporary thriller |url=https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/opinion/jamal-khashoggi-case-a-contemporary-thriller |accessdate=14 October 2018 |publisher=National Herald |date=13 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014053123/https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/opinion/jamal-khashoggi-case-a-contemporary-thriller |archive-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe disappearance presented Turkish officials with a sharp diplomatic challenge. [[Jamal Elshayyal]] reported Turkish authorities were trying to walk a fine line so as not to damage the Turkish-Saudi relationship: \"There is an attempt by the Turkish government to try to find a way out of this whereby there isn't a full collapse of diplomatic relations, at least a temporary freeze between Saudi Arabia and Turkey. Because, if indeed, Turkish authorities can prove unequivocally that Saudi agents essentially murdered a journalist inside the consulate in Istanbul, it would require some sort of strong reaction.\"<ref name=\"AlJa8Oct2018\" /> Analysts have suggested that Khashoggi may have been considered especially dangerous by the Saudi leadership not because he was a long-time dissident, but rather, a pillar of the Saudi establishment who had been close to its ruling circles for decades, had worked as an editor at Saudi news outlets and had been an adviser to a former Saudi intelligence chief [[Turki bin Faisal Al Saud]].<ref name=\"Washington Post 6 October 2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkey-concludes-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-killed-by-murder-team-sources-say/2018/10/06/31ee4f86-c8d9-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html|title=Saudi forensic expert is among 15 named by Turkey in disappearance of journalist Jamal Khashoggi|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=14 October 2018|date=6 October 2018|first=Kareem|last=Fahim|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007000044/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkey-concludes-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-killed-by-murder-team-sources-say/2018/10/06/31ee4f86-c8d9-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html|archive-date=7 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Assassination==\nAccording to numerous anonymous police sources, the Turkish police believe that Khashoggi was tortured and killed inside the Saudi consulate in Istanbul<ref name=\"reuters\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident/exclusive-turkish-police-believe-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-was-killed-in-consulate-sources-idUSKCN1MG0HU |title= Exclusive: Turkish police believe Saudi journalist Khashoggi was killed in consulate \u2013 sources |last= Coskun |first= Orhan |agency= [[Reuters]] |date= 6 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181014224621/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident/exclusive-turkish-police-believe-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-was-killed-in-consulate-sources-idUSKCN1MG0HU |archive-date= 14 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\"MEE\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/turkish-police-suspect-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-was-killed-consulate-report-1250529206 |title= Turkish police suspect Saudi journalist Khashoggi was killed at consulate |work= [[Middle East Eye]] |date= 6 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181007073811/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/turkish-police-suspect-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-was-killed-consulate-report-1250529206 |archive-date= 7 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> by a 15-member team brought in from Saudi Arabia for the operation.<ref name=\"Fahim 2018\">{{cite web |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkey-concludes-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-killed-by-murder-team-sources-say/2018/10/06/31ee4f86-c8d9-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html |title= Turkey concludes Saudi journalist Jamal Khashoggi killed by 'murder' team, sources say |first= Kareem |last= Fahim |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |date= 6 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181007000044/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkey-concludes-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-killed-by-murder-team-sources-say/2018/10/06/31ee4f86-c8d9-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html |archive-date= 7 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\"guardian1\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/06/saudi-journalist-killed-inside-consulate-turkish-sources |title= Saudi journalist 'killed inside consulate' \u2013 Turkish sources |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 6 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181020223151/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/06/saudi-journalist-killed-inside-consulate-turkish-sources |archive-date= 20 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> One anonymous police source claimed that the dead body was \"[[Dismemberment|cut into pieces]]\" and quietly moved out of the consulate, and that all of this was \"videotaped to prove the mission had been accomplished and the tape was taken out of the country\".<ref name=MEE/> ''[[Middle East Eye]]'' cited an anonymous Saudi who said the [[Tiger Squad]] brought Khashoggi's fingers to Mohammad bin Salman in Riyadh as other evidence that the mission was successful.<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\">{{cite news | last1= Abu Sneineh | first1= Mustafa | title= REVEALED: The Saudi death squad MBS uses to silence dissent | date= 22 October 2018 | website= Middle East Eye | url= https://www.middleeasteye.net/tiger-squad-saudi-hitmen-khashoggi-mbs | accessdate= 22 October 2018 | archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/73MnJ9BcG?url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/tiger-squad-saudi-hitmen-khashoggi-mbs | archivedate= 22 October 2018 | url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 7 October, Turkish officials pledged to release evidence showing that Khashoggi was killed.<ref name=guardian1/> Aktay initially said he believed Khashoggi had been killed in the consulate,<ref name=MEE/> but on 10 October he claimed that \"the Saudi state is not blamed here\", something that a journalist for ''[[The Guardian]]'' saw as Turkey trying not to harm lucrative trade ties and a delicate regional relationship with Saudi Arabia.<ref name = guardian2/> Turkey then claimed to have audio and video evidence of the killing occurring inside the consulate.<ref name=\"WaPo1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/turks-tell-us-officials-they-have-audio-and-video-recordings-that-support-conclusion-khashoggi-was-killed/2018/10/11/119a119e-cd88-11e8-920f-dd52e1ae4570_story.html |title=Turks tell U.S. officials they have audio and video recordings that support conclusion Khashoggi was killed |first1=Shane |last1=Harris |first2=Souad |last2=Mekhennet |first3=John |last3=Hudson |first4=Anne |last4=Gearan |date=11 October 2018 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020074357/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/turks-tell-us-officials-they-have-audio-and-video-recordings-that-support-conclusion-khashoggi-was-killed/2018/10/11/119a119e-cd88-11e8-920f-dd52e1ae4570_story.html |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> U.S. President Donald Trump said the United States had asked Turkey for the recordings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-europe-45893993/jamal-khashoggi-we-ve-asked-for-tape-evidence-trump|title=We've asked for Khashoggi tape evidence \u2013 Trump|website=BBC News|access-date=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019224754/https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-europe-45893993/jamal-khashoggi-we-ve-asked-for-tape-evidence-trump|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> According to \"people familiar with the matter\", the audio was shared with [[Central Intelligence Agency]] agents; a CIA spokeswoman declined to comment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/saudi-claims-that-khashoggi-died-in-a-brawl-draw-immediate-skepticism/2018/10/19/e10d4186-d3ef-11e8-83d6-291fcead2ab1_story.html|title=Saudi claims that Khashoggi died in a 'brawl' draw immediate skepticism|last=|first=|date=|website=The Washington Post|language=en|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022232500/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/saudi-claims-that-khashoggi-died-in-a-brawl-draw-immediate-skepticism/2018/10/19/e10d4186-d3ef-11e8-83d6-291fcead2ab1_story.html|archive-date=22 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[CNN]] reported on 15 October that Saudi Arabia was about to admit to the killing, but would claim that it was an \"interrogation gone bad\", as opposed to a targeted death squad killing.<ref name=prepadmit>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/15/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-death-turkey/index.html|title=Saudis preparing to admit Jamal Khashoggi died during interrogation, sources say|website=CNN|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015201630/https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/15/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-death-turkey/index.html|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"prepadmit\"/> This claim drew criticism from some, considering that Khashoggi was reportedly dismembered and that his killing was allegedly premeditated, and the circumstances, including the arrival and departure of a team of 15, included forensic specialists presumed to have been present to hide evidence of the crime, on the same day.<ref name=prepadmit/>\n\nThe next day, ''[[Middle East Eye]]'' reported that, according to an anonymous Turkish source, the killing took about seven minutes and forensic specialist [[Salah Muhammed al-Tubaigy]], who had brought along a [[bone cutter|bone saw]],<ref name=\"MEE_7minutes\" /> cut Khashoggi's body into pieces while Khashoggi was still alive, as he and his colleagues listened to music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inquisitr.com/5119410/jamal-khashoggi-dismembered-alive-saudi/|title=Jamal Khashoggi Dismembered Alive, Saudi Killer Listened To Music During Murder|website=Inquisitr|accessdate=16 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017033937/https://www.inquisitr.com/5119410/jamal-khashoggi-dismembered-alive-saudi/|archive-date=17 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The source further claimed that \"Khashoggi was dragged from consul general [[Mohammad al-Otaibi]]'s office at the Saudi consulate ... Tubaigy began to cut Khashoggi's body up on a table in the study while he was still alive,\" and \"There was no attempt to interrogate him. They had come to kill him.\"<ref name=\"MEE_7minutes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/exclusive-khashoggi-829291552|title=Jamal Khashoggi's killing took seven minutes, Turkish source tells MEE|website=Middle East Eye|accessdate=16 October 2018}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Turkish pro-government newspaper ''[[Daily Sabah]]'' reported on 18 October that neighbours to the consul's residence had observed an unusual barbecue party, which the paper suggested might have been to mask the smell from the incineration of the dismembered corpse: \"We have been living here for twelve years but I have never seen them having a barbecue party. That day, they had a barbecue party in the garden.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/columns/merve-sebnem-oruc/2018/10/18/a-rogue-state-behind-khashoggis-disappearance-not-rogue-killers|title=A 'rogue state' behind Khashoggi's disappearance, not 'rogue killers'|accessdate=19 October 2018|work=Daily Sabah|author=Merve \u015eebnem Oru\u00e7|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019122015/https://www.dailysabah.com/columns/merve-sebnem-oruc/2018/10/18/a-rogue-state-behind-khashoggis-disappearance-not-rogue-killers|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' published reports from anonymous sources that Khashoggi was tortured in front of top Saudi diplomat Mohammad al-Otaibi, Saudi Arabia's consul general.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/pompeo-seeks-answers-amid-crisis-over-missing-saudi-journalist-1539690270?mod=trending_now_3|title=Turkey Details Alleged Killing of Saudi Journalist|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017091557/https://www.wsj.com/articles/pompeo-seeks-answers-amid-crisis-over-missing-saudi-journalist-1539690270?mod=trending_now_3|archive-date=17 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/jamal-khashoggi-tortured-saudi-diplomat-reports_us_5bc736d8e4b0d38b5873dc98|title=Jamal Khashoggi Tortured In Front Of Top Saudi Diplomat: Reports|website=Huffington Post|accessdate=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018043214/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/jamal-khashoggi-tortured-saudi-diplomat-reports_us_5bc736d8e4b0d38b5873dc98|archive-date=18 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Reuters reported that al-Otaibi left Istanbul for [[Riyadh]] on 16 October. His departure came hours before his home was expected to be searched in relation to the journalist's disappearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident-consul/saudi-consul-general-leaves-turkey-for-riyadh-turkish-broadcasters-idUSKCN1MQ23T|title=Saudi consul general leaves Turkey for Riyadh: Turkish broadcasters|agency=Reuters|accessdate=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018044649/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident-consul/saudi-consul-general-leaves-turkey-for-riyadh-turkish-broadcasters-idUSKCN1MQ23T|archive-date=18 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 October, the Saudi Foreign Ministry reported that a preliminary investigation showed that Khashoggi had died at the consulate while engaged in a fight, the first Saudi acknowledgement of Khashoggi's death.<ref name=\"WaPoArrest19\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/world/wp/2018/10/19/saudi-government-acknowledges-journalist-jamal-khashaoggi-died-while-in-that-countrys-consulate-in-istanbul/ |title=Saudi Arabia fires 5 top officials, arrests 18 Saudis, saying Khashoggi was killed in fight at consulate |last=Sullivan |first=Kevin |date=19 October 2018 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=20 October 2018 |last2=Morris |first2=Loveday |language=en |last3=El-Ghobashy |first3=Tamer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020015713/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/world/wp/2018/10/19/saudi-government-acknowledges-journalist-jamal-khashaoggi-died-while-in-that-countrys-consulate-in-istanbul/ |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 20 October [[Saud al-Qahtani]] and [[Ahmad Asiri (general)|Ahmad Asiri]] were announced fired by Saudi Arabia for involvement in Khashoggi's killing according to the BBC.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Jamal Khashoggi case: Saudi Arabia says journalist killed in fight |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45923217 |work=BBC |date=20 October 2018 |access-date=23 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120201646/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45923217 |archive-date=20 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 October, an anonymous Saudi official said Khashoggi had been threatened with drugging and kidnapping by Maher Mutreb, had resisted and was restrained with a chokehold, which killed him.<ref name=\"Rashad\">{{cite news |agency=Reuters |last1=Rashad |first1=Marwa |title=Amid skepticism, Saudi official provides another version of... |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-official/amid-skepticism-saudi-official-provides-another-version-of-khashoggi-death-idUSKCN1MV04V |accessdate=21 October 2018 |date=21 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021091541/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-official/amid-skepticism-saudi-official-provides-another-version-of-khashoggi-death-idUSKCN1MV04V |archive-date=21 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 October, [[Reuters]] cited a Turkish intelligence source and a high-ranking Arab with access to intelligence and links to members of Saudi's royal court and reported that Saud al-Qahtani, the then-top aide for Mohammed bin Salman, had made a [[Skype]] call to the consulate while Khashoggi was held in the room. Qahtani reportedly insulted Khashoggi, who responded in kind. According to the Turkish source, Qahtani then asked the team to kill Khashoggi. Qahtani instructed: \"Bring me the head of the dog\". According to both sources, the audio of the Skype call is currently with Erdogan.<ref name=\"ReutersSkype\">{{cite news |title=How the man behind Khashoggi murder ran the killing via Skype |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-adviser-insight/how-the-man-behind-khashoggi-murder-ran-the-killing-via-skype-idUSKCN1MW2HA |accessdate=22 October 2018 |agency=Reuters |date=22 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115040933/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-adviser-insight/how-the-man-behind-khashoggi-murder-ran-the-killing-via-skype-idUSKCN1MW2HA |archive-date=15 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Nazif Karaman of the ''[[Daily Sabah]]'', the audio recording from inside the consulate revealed that Khashoggi's last words were: \"I'm suffocating... take this bag off my head, I'm claustrophobic.\"<ref name=\"DailySabah_Khashoggi_lastwords\">{{cite news | title= 'I'm suffocating': Khashoggi's last words, says Turkish reporter | publisher= [[Al Jazeera English]] | url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/suffocating-khashoggi-words-turkish-reporter-181111085534099.html |accessdate= 11 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111185950/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/suffocating-khashoggi-words-turkish-reporter-181111085534099.html  |archivedate= 11 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 December, the details of the transcript of the audio were described to [[CNN]] by an anonymous source.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/12/09/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-last-words-intl/index.html |title='I can't breathe.' Jamal Khashoggi's last words disclosed in transcript, source says |first=Nick |last=Robertson |date=9 December 2018 |work=[[CNN]] |access-date=12 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212045056/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/12/09/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-last-words-intl/index.html |archive-date=12 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 November, a ''H\u00fcrriyet'' columnist reported that Turkey has more evidence, including a second audio recording from the consulate, where the Saudi team reviews the plans on how to execute Khashoggi. He also reported that: \"Turkish officials also did not confirm [Saudi prosecutor's claim] that Khashoggi was killed after they gave him a fatal dose of drug. They say that he was strangulated with a rope or something like a plastic bag.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-has-second-audio-recording-on-khashoggi-killing-columnist-138915 |title=Turkey has second audio recording on Khashoggi killing: Columnist \u2013 Turkey News |publisher=Hurriyetdailynews.com |date=16 November 2018 |accessdate=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121230813/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-has-second-audio-recording-on-khashoggi-killing-columnist-138915 |archive-date=21 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Front of the Consulate General of Saudi Arabia in Istanbul.jpg|Police cordon, in front of the Saudi consulate in Istanbul, after Khashoggi's disappearance.|thumb|right]]\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Meets With King Salman (45309197352).jpg|thumb|right|U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] meets with King Salman on 16 October 2018.]]\nHatice Cengiz begged the US government to take action in helping to find her fianc\u00e9. In her ''Washington Post'' op-ed on 9 October, Cengiz wrote, \"At this time, I implore President [[Donald Trump|Trump]] and [[Melania Trump|first lady Melania Trump]] to help shed light on Jamal's disappearance. I also urge Saudi Arabia, especially King Salman and Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman, to show the same level of sensitivity and release CCTV footage from the consulate.\"<ref name=\"WaPoCengiz9-10-2018\"/>\n\n''[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]]'' reported on 11 October that Turkish officials were investigating whether Khashoggi's [[Apple Watch]] would reveal clues as to what happened to him inside the Saudi consulate, examining whether data from the smartwatch could have been transmitted to the [[Cloud computing|cloud]], or his personal phone, which was with Cengiz.<ref name=\"shockingevide\">{{cite news | last=Wilkinson | first=Bard | last2=Robertson | first2=Nic | last3=Smith-Spark | first3=Laura | title=Turkey has 'shocking' evidence of Saudi journalist's murder | website=CNN | date=12 October 2018 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/12/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-turkey-recordings-intl/index.html | access-date=12 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012074432/https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/12/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-turkey-recordings-intl/index.html | archive-date=12 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of 14 October, President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Erdo\u011fan]] and King Salman announced that a deal had been made for a \"jointing working group\" to examine the case.<ref name=\"wintour\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/15/turkey-jamal-khashoggi-granted-permission-search-saudi-arabia-consulate-istanbul|title=Donald Trump says 'rogue killers' may have murdered Khashoggi|first1=Patrick|last1=Wintour|first2=Martin|last2=Chulov|date=15 October 2018|website=The Guardian|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015113944/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/15/turkey-jamal-khashoggi-granted-permission-search-saudi-arabia-consulate-istanbul|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 15 October the Turkish Foreign Ministry announced that an \"inspection\" of the consulate, by both Turkish and Saudi officials, would take place that afternoon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/jamal-khashoggi-team-enters-saudi-consulate-ahead-of-joint-search-11526611|title=Jamal Khashoggi: Joint search team enters Saudi consulate|publisher=|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015231627/https://news.sky.com/story/jamal-khashoggi-team-enters-saudi-consulate-ahead-of-joint-search-11526611|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/jamal-khashoggi-latest-saudi-arabia-turkey-search-istanbul-death-missing-a8584361.html|title=Turkish authorities to search Saudi consulate two weeks after journalist vanished|publisher=news.sky.com|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015170040/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/jamal-khashoggi-latest-saudi-arabia-turkey-search-istanbul-death-missing-a8584361.html|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> According to an anonymous source from the Attorney General's office, Turkish officials found evidence of \"tampering\" during the inspection, and evidence that supports the belief Khashoggi was killed.<ref name=\"SearchEvidence\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/turkish-prosecutors-find-evidence-jamal-khashoggi-killing-181015205254636.html|title=Turkish prosecutors 'find evidence of Jamal Khashoggi killing'|website=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=15 October 2018|accessdate=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016203320/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/turkish-prosecutors-find-evidence-jamal-khashoggi-killing-181015205254636.html|archive-date=16 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> President Erdo\u011fan said that \"investigation is looking into many things such as toxic materials and those materials being removed by painting them over\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident-erdogan/turkeys-erdogan-says-some-material-at-saudi-consulate-painted-over-idUSKCN1MQ1CT|title=Turkey's Erdogan says some material at Saudi consulate painted over|agency=Reuters|accessdate=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016224604/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident-erdogan/turkeys-erdogan-says-some-material-at-saudi-consulate-painted-over-idUSKCN1MQ1CT|archive-date=16 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to anonymous sources, Turkish police have expanded the search, as Khashoggi's body may have been disposed of in nearby [[Belgrad Forest]] or on farmland in [[Yalova Province]], as indicated by the movement of the Saudi vehicles,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/18/search-for-khashoggis-remains-extends-to-saudi-consul-generals-residence|title=Search for Khashoggi's remains focuses on consul general's house|first1=Bethan|last1=McKernan|first2=Julian|last2=Borger|date=18 October 2018|website=the Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228180559/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/18/search-for-khashoggis-remains-extends-to-saudi-consul-generals-residence|archive-date=28 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[DNA profiling|DNA tests]] of samples from the Saudi consulate and the consul's residence are being conducted;<ref name=\"BBCJK\">{{cite web |title=Jamal Khashoggi case: Turkish police 'search forest' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45909732 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=19 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019015214/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45909732 |archive-date=19 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Al Jazeera'' reported that according to anonymous sources, fingerprints of one of the alleged perpetrators, Salah Muhammad al-Tubaigy, were found in the consulate.<ref name=\"AJ\">{{cite web |title=Jamal Khashoggi case: All the latest updates |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/jamal-khashoggi-case-latest-updates-181010133542286.html |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=19 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018230957/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/jamal-khashoggi-case-latest-updates-181010133542286.html |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Confirmation of death===\n\nOn 20 October, the Saudi Foreign Ministry reported that a preliminary investigation showed that Khashoggi had died at the consulate while engaged in a fight, the first Saudi acknowledgement of Khashoggi's death.<ref name=\"WaPoArrest19\"/>\n\nOn 22 October, six US and Western officials<ref name=\"haaretz2018-10-23\">{{cite web | title=CIA director Gina Haspel travels to Turkey for Khashoggi probe, sources say | website=haaretz.com | date=23 October 2018 | url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/cia-director-gina-haspel-travels-to-turkey-for-khashoggi-probe-source-says-1.6588337 | access-date=24 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023234114/https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/cia-director-gina-haspel-travels-to-turkey-for-khashoggi-probe-source-says-1.6588337 | archive-date=23 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> stated they believed that the crown prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]], because of his role overseeing the Saudi security apparatus, was ultimately responsible for Khashoggi's disappearance, and the [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA), [[Gina Haspel]], departed for Turkey to work on the investigation<ref>{{cite web | agency=Reuters | title=CIA director Haspel travels to Turkey for Khashoggi case: source | date=22 October 2018 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-cia/cia-director-haspel-travels-to-turkey-for-khashoggi-case-source-idUSKCN1MW2WN | access-date=24 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024112921/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-cia/cia-director-haspel-travels-to-turkey-for-khashoggi-case-source-idUSKCN1MW2WN | archive-date=24 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> \"amid a growing international uproar over Saudi's explanation of the killing\".<ref name=\"WaP20181022\">{{cite web |title=CIA director flies to Turkey amid growing controversy over Jamal Khashoggi killing |website=The Washington Post |date=22 October 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-director-flies-to-turkey-amid-growing-controversy-over-jamal-khashoggi-killing/2018/10/22/47d406d9-9f36-49fc-a187-a9a495b70a62_story.html |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024073637/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-director-flies-to-turkey-amid-growing-controversy-over-jamal-khashoggi-killing/2018/10/22/47d406d9-9f36-49fc-a187-a9a495b70a62_story.html |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Governor of \u0130stanbul]]'s office said that Khashoggi's fianc\u00e9e, Hatice Cengiz, had been given 24-hour [[police protection]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamal Khashoggi: Erdogan vows to reveal all that happened 'in all its nakedness' |website=Sky News |date=21 October 2018 |url=https://news.sky.com/story/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-vows-to-bring-journalists-killers-to-justice-11531766 |accessdate=22 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022002900/https://news.sky.com/story/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-vows-to-bring-journalists-killers-to-justice-11531766 |archive-date=22 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlso on 22 October, [[CNN]] aired [[CCTV]] law enforcement footage from the Turkish authorities, showing the Saudi agent Mustafa al-Madani, a member of the 15-man team, leaving the consulate by the back door.<ref name=\"body double\"/> He was dressed up in Khashoggi's clothes, except for the shoes. Madani had also put on a fake beard that resembled Khashoggi's facial hair, his glasses and his Apple Watch.<ref name=\"Tuysuz\" /><ref name=Rashad /><ref name=\"TheGMcKernan\" /> Madani, who was of similar age, height, and build to Khashoggi, left the consulate from its back door.<ref name=\"body double\"/> He was later seen at Istanbul's [[Blue Mosque (Istanbul)|Blue Mosque]], where he went to a public bathroom and changed back to his own clothes and discarded Khashoggi's clothes.<ref name=\"body double\"/> Later he was seen dining with another Saudi agent, and the footage shows him smiling and laughing.<ref name=\"ClarissaWard\" /> An anonymous Turkish official believes that Madani was brought to Istanbul to act as a [[body double]] and that \"You don't need a body double for a [[Extraordinary rendition|rendition]] or an interrogation. Our assessment has not changed since October 6. This was a [[premeditated]] murder, and the body was moved out of the consulate.\"<ref name=\"body double\">{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/22/middleeast/saudi-operative-jamal-khashoggi-clothes/index.html |title=Mustafa al-Madani identified as Saudi 'body double' in Khashoggi's clothes, Turkish source says |work=CNN |date=23 October 2018 |accessdate=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025145625/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/22/middleeast/saudi-operative-jamal-khashoggi-clothes/index.html |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The use of the body double might have been an attempt to lend credence to the Saudi government's first version of events: that Khashoggi walked out through the back not long after he arrived. But \"it was a flawed body double, so it never became an official part of the Saudi government's narrative\", a Turkish diplomat told ''The Washington Post''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/saudi-consulate-employees-talking-to-turkish-prosecutors-in-khashoggi-inquiry/2018/10/22/ba5980da-d3d2-11e8-a4db-184311d27129_story.html |title=Video appears to show Saudi body double in Jamal Khashoggi's clothes |work=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025032054/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/saudi-consulate-employees-talking-to-turkish-prosecutors-in-khashoggi-inquiry/2018/10/22/ba5980da-d3d2-11e8-a4db-184311d27129_story.html |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe body double footage bolstered Turkish claims that the Saudis always intended either to kill Khashoggi or move him back to Saudi Arabia. [[\u00d6mer \u00c7elik]], a spokesman for Turkey's ruling [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AKP]], stated: \"We are facing a situation that has been monstrously planned and later tried to be covered up. It is a complicated murder.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=The Khashoggi Body Double \u2013 and Mounting Evidence of a Premeditated Murder |website=The New Yorker |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-khashoggi-body-doubleand-mounting-evidence-of-a-premeditated-murder |date=22 October 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025031303/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-khashoggi-body-doubleand-mounting-evidence-of-a-premeditated-murder |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia has vowed it will conduct a thorough criminal investigation and deliver justice for Khashoggi, Turkish investigators have been faced with several delays from their Saudi counterparts. On 22 October, BBC reported that Turkish police had found a car with diplomatic number plates, abandoned in an underground car park in Istanbul. The car belonged to the Saudi consulate and permission was sought from the Saudi diplomats to search the car.<ref name=\"BBC_murder_fox\"/> Turkish media published a video from 3 October (day after the disappearance) that apparently showed the staff of the consulate burning documents.<ref name=BBC_murder_fox/>\n\n===Search of Saudi consul's residence===\nOn Sunday 7 October, the Turkish Ministry of Foreign Affairs summoned Saudi Arabian Ambassador [[Waleed A. M. Elkhereiji]] to demand for the second time permission to search the consulate building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/diplomacy/2018/10/08/turkey-demands-permission-to-search-saudi-consulate-after-journalist-khashoggis-disappearance|title=Turkey demands permission to search Saudi consulate after journalist Khashoggi's disappearance|work=[[Daily Sabah]]|quote=The Ministry of Foreign Affairs on Sunday summoned Saudi Arabian Ambassador [[Waleed A. M. Elkhereiji]] for the second time after journalist Jamal Khashoggi's disappearance and demanded permission to search the consulate building in Istanbul, October 8.|access-date=2 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119051646/https://www.dailysabah.com/diplomacy/2018/10/08/turkey-demands-permission-to-search-saudi-consulate-after-journalist-khashoggis-disappearance|archive-date=19 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Saudi officials continued to refuse that Turkish police could search the well in the Saudi consul's garden,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/todays-headlines/-saudis-did-not-let-turkey-search-well-at-consulate-/1291897 |title=Saudis did not let Turkey search well at consulate |work=[[Anadolu Agency]] |date=24 October 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024121708/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/todays-headlines/-saudis-did-not-let-turkey-search-well-at-consulate-/1291897 |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/saudi-khashoggi-consulate/saudi-officials-refuse-turkish-police-search-at-well-in-istanbul-consulate-anadolu-idUSA4N1UT02E |title=Saudi officials refuse Turkish police search at well in Istanbul consulate \u2013 Anadolu |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=24 October 2018 }}</ref> but granted permission on 24 October (22 days after the assassination).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ntv.com.tr/turkiye/konsolosluk-bahcesindeki-kuyuda-arama-yapilacak,9UXbI7aPaEWUk1k-7i9QPg |title=Konsolosluk bah\u00e7esindeki kuyuda arama yap\u0131lacak |language=Turkish |work=[[NTV (Turkey)]] |date=24 October 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-consulate/turkish-police-receive-permission-to-search-well-at-saudi-consulate-ntv-idUSKCN1MY1HF |title=Turkish police receive permission to search well at Saudi consulate: NTV |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=24 October 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024142119/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-consulate/turkish-police-receive-permission-to-search-well-at-saudi-consulate-ntv-idUSKCN1MY1HF |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"WaPoPreMeditated\">{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia again changes its story on Khashoggi killing |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/turkish-probe-of-khashoggi-killing-turns-to-garden-well/2018/10/25/a3aabb88-d837-11e8-8384-bcc5492fef49_story.html |accessdate=26 October 2018 |work=The Washington Post |date=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025115811/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/turkish-probe-of-khashoggi-killing-turns-to-garden-well/2018/10/25/a3aabb88-d837-11e8-8384-bcc5492fef49_story.html |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Turkish newspaper ''[[H\u00fcrriyet]]'' reported on 26 October that police had found no DNA traces of Khashoggi in water samples taken from the well.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/incelemeden-once-araclara-oto-kuafor-40998828 |title=\u0130ncelemeden \u00f6nce ara\u00e7lara oto kuaf\u00f6r |language=Turkish |work=H\u00fcrriyet |date=26 October 2018 |quote=Yap\u0131lan kriminal incelemede, suda herhangi bir DNA \u00f6rne\u011fine rastlanmad\u0131 |access-date=26 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026182249/http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/incelemeden-once-araclara-oto-kuafor-40998828 |archive-date=26 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"SBS_NoDNA\">{{cite news |title=No Khashoggi DNA in Saudi consulate well |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/no-khashoggi-dna-in-saudi-consulate-well |accessdate=26 October 2018 |publisher=SBS News |date=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026143440/https://www.sbs.com.au/news/no-khashoggi-dna-in-saudi-consulate-well |archive-date=26 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCalling for an international investigation, at the [[Headquarters of the United Nations]] in [[New York City]] on 25 October, [[Agnes Callamard]], UN Special Rapporteur on Extrajudicial, Summary or Arbitrary Executions, explained the Saudi officials implicated in the death of Khashoggi \"are high enough to represent the state\".<ref name=\"NZZOct31\">{{cite web | title=Fall Khashoggi: Menschenrechtsexpertin fordert Uno-Untersuchung | website=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung | date=26 October 2018 | url=https://www.nzz.ch/international/fall-khashoggi-menschenrechtsexpertin-fordert-uno-untersuchung-ld.1431312 | language=de | access-date=31 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031174120/https://www.nzz.ch/international/fall-khashoggi-menschenrechtsexpertin-fordert-uno-untersuchung-ld.1431312 | archive-date=31 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> \"Even Saudi Arabia has admitted that the crime was premeditated ... From where I sit, this bears all the hallmarks of [[extrajudicial execution]]s. Until I am proven otherwise I must assume that this was the case. It is up to the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia to prove that it was not.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Khashoggi Killing Likely an Extrajudicial Execution \u2013 Press Conference (25 October 2018) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H5UGTUc06yU |website=Youtube |publisher=United Nations |date=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Saudi public prosecutors visit===\nSaudi public prosecutor Saud al-Mojeb arrived in Istanbul on 28 October, days after he contradicted weeks of official Saudi statements by saying that Khashoggi's murder was premeditated. His trip came amid Turkish suggestions of \"a lack of cooperation by the Saudi side\" and alleged \"attempts to spoil evidence\".<ref name=\"AlJ31Oct\">{{cite web | last=Koseoglu | first=Sinem | title=Turkey to present probe findings to Saudi, request new search | website=Al Jazeera | date=28 October 2018 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/turkey-present-saudi-probe-findings-request-consulate-search-181028145716739.html | access-date=31 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031133038/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/turkey-present-saudi-probe-findings-request-consulate-search-181028145716739.html | archive-date=31 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> Mojeb held talks on 29 October with Istanbul's chief prosecutor Irfan Fidan at the [[Istanbul \u00c7a\u011flayan Justice Palace|\u00c7a\u011flayan courthouse]]. During the meeting Saudi officials asked for the complete investigation folder, including evidence, statements and footage. The Turkish investigators presented the probe findings in a 150-page dossier, but refused to share all the evidence they have compiled in the murder. And they repeated the request for the extradition of the 18 suspects to Turkey, although the Saudi foreign minister [[Adel al-Jubeir]] insisted on 27 October that the men would be tried on Saudi soil. They also repeated requests for confirmation on the whereabouts of Khashoggi's body, the identity of the \"local cooperator\" that the Saudis claim disposed of the body, and an update on the progress of a Saudi investigation of the 15 Saudi operatives who visited the Istanbul consulate at the time of the murder. Due the lack of trust between the two countries the meeting lasted only 75 minutes. Turkish foreign minister [[Mevlut Cavusoglu]] stated that \"The whole truth must be revealed\" and the visit will help in that direction. He also asked Saudis to complete the investigation sooner.<ref name=\"Reuters_29Prosecutor\">{{cite news |title=Turkey demands truth over Khashoggi killing as Saudi prosecutor visits |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey-prosecutor/turkey-demands-truth-over-khashoggi-killing-as-saudi-prosecutor-visits-idUSKCN1N30K2 |accessdate=29 October 2018 |agency=Reuters |date=29 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029141615/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey-prosecutor/turkey-demands-truth-over-khashoggi-killing-as-saudi-prosecutor-visits-idUSKCN1N30K2 |archive-date=29 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"TheG_29Oct\">{{cite web | last=Wintour | first=Patrick | last2=McKernan | first2=Bethan | title=Turkey refuses to share all Khashoggi evidence with Saudis | website=the Guardian | date=29 October 2018 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/29/saudi-prosecutor-saud-al-mojeb-arrives-in-turkey-to-assist-with-jamal-khashoggi-inquiry | access-date=27 January 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204163743/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/29/saudi-prosecutor-saud-al-mojeb-arrives-in-turkey-to-assist-with-jamal-khashoggi-inquiry | archive-date=4 February 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMojeb held a second round of talks with Fidan on 30 October, before inspecting the Saudi consulate in the [[Levent]] neighbourhood, where he left after spending a little over an hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/saudi-prosecutor-visits-istanbul-court-house-in-khashoggi-probe-138396|title=Saudi prosecutor joins probe at Saudi consulate in Istanbul for Khashoggi investigation \u2013 Turkey News|website=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|accessdate=31 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030115127/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/saudi-prosecutor-visits-istanbul-court-house-in-khashoggi-probe-138396|archive-date=30 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"WaPo31Oct\" /> According to a source at the prosecutor's office, Fidan asked Mojeb to conduct another joint search at the consul-general's residence, because when Turkish investigators first entered the building in mid-October they were not allowed to search three locked rooms and were also not allowed to search a {{convert|20|m|adj=on}}-deep well. The Saudis did not let firefighters descend into the well, and the search ended with police only able to obtain some water samples.<ref name=\"AlJ31Oct\" />\n\nPresident Erdo\u011fan said the investigation needs to be completed swiftly: \"This needs to be solved now; there is no point in excuses\", and wants an extradition request for 18 suspects detained in KSA to be put on trial in Istanbul. High Commissioner for Human Rights, [[Michelle Bachelet]], also urged Saudi Arabia to reveal the location of Khashoggi's body: \"I urge the Saudi authorities to reveal the whereabouts of his body without further delay or prevarication.\"<ref name=\"WaPo31Oct\">{{cite web |title=Khashoggi's fiancee calls on Trump to prevent 'cover-up' |website=The Washington Post |date=31 October 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/khashoggis-fiancee-calls-on-trump-to-prevent-cover-up/2018/10/30/96cce4e0-dcb0-11e8-8bac-bfe01fcdc3a6_story.html |access-date=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031050424/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/khashoggis-fiancee-calls-on-trump-to-prevent-cover-up/2018/10/30/96cce4e0-dcb0-11e8-8bac-bfe01fcdc3a6_story.html |archive-date=31 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mojeb was accused by Erdo\u011fan of refusal to cooperate during his visit to discuss the investigation. Erdo\u011fan stated that, \"The prosecutor came to Turkey to make excuses, make things difficult.\" Mojeb had not shared any information to the Turkish investigators but wanted to take Khashoggi's mobile phone that was left outside the consulate with his fianc\u00e9e when he entered.<ref name=\"Reuters_Tapes_given\"/>\n\n===Disposing of the body===\nOn 31 October a senior Turkish official told ''The Washington Post'' that Turkish authorities were investigating the theory that Khashoggi's body was destroyed in acid on the grounds of the consulate or at the nearby residence of the Saudi consul general. The \"biological evidence\" discovered in the consulate garden supported the theory.<ref name=\"WaPo31Octacid\">{{cite web |title=Prosecutor says Khashoggi was strangled and dismembered, but fate of body still a mystery |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/saudi-arabia-not-fully-cooperating-with-khashoggi-investigation-turkish-official-says/2018/10/31/804bfc2a-dc78-11e8-8bac-bfe01fcdc3a6_story.html |website=The Washington Post |date=31 October 2018 |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103092637/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/saudi-arabia-not-fully-cooperating-with-khashoggi-investigation-turkish-official-says/2018/10/31/804bfc2a-dc78-11e8-8bac-bfe01fcdc3a6_story.html |archive-date=3 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Echoing the claim, Yasin Aktay, an adviser to Erdo\u011fan in his ruling [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]] and a friend of Khashoggi, hinted in an article in the Turkish newspaper ''H\u00fcrriyet'', published on 2 November, that the body was destroyed by dismembering and dissolving in acid: \"We now see that it wasn't just cut up, they got rid of the body by dissolving it\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/11/02/world/europe/02reuters-saudi-khashoggi-turkey.html|title=Turkey's Erdogan-Khashoggi Killing Ordered at Saudi 'Highest Levels'|publisher=|access-date=3 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103105151/https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/11/02/world/europe/02reuters-saudi-khashoggi-turkey.html|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trtworld.com/turkey/khashoggi-s-body-was-dissolved-after-murder-erdogan-advisor-21325|title=Khashoggi's body was 'dissolved' after murder \u2013 Erdogan advisor|website=Khashoggi's body was 'dissolved' after murder \u2013 Erdogan advisor|access-date=3 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103170538/https://www.trtworld.com/turkey/khashoggi-s-body-was-dissolved-after-murder-erdogan-advisor-21325|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey/erdogan-adviser-said-khashoggis-body-was-dismembered-and-dissolved-newspaper-idUSKCN1N7179|title=Erdogan adviser said Khashoggi's body was dismembered and...|agency=Reuters|access-date=3 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103123749/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey/erdogan-adviser-said-khashoggis-body-was-dismembered-and-dissolved-newspaper-idUSKCN1N7179|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March 2019, Al Jazeera Arabic released a documentary on the investigation of Khashoggi's murder and the subsequent coverup.  In its coverage, the network states that the body was likely disposed of by being burnt in an oven at the Saudi consulate general's residence.<ref name=\"burned-oven\">{{cite news |title=Jamal Khashoggi's body likely burned in large oven at Saudi home |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/jamal-khashoggi-body-burned-large-oven-saudi-home-190304011823218.html |website=Al Jazeera News |date=4 March 2019 |access-date=5 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305125107/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/jamal-khashoggi-body-burned-large-oven-saudi-home-190304011823218.html |archive-date=5 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  An interview with the oven's builder revealed that it was designed to be \"deep\", and capable of withstanding temperatures over {{convert|1000|C|F}}. The burning took three days and happened in parts.  Afterwards, a large quantity of [[barbecue]] meat was prepared to cover the evidence of cremation.\n\nIn a ''Washington Post'' op-ed Erdo\u011fan described the murder as \"inexplicable\" and as a \"clear violation and a blatant abuse of the [[Vienna Convention on Consular Relations]]\", arguing that not punishing the perpetrators \"could set a very dangerous precedent.\" He criticised Saudi inaction against the consul general [[Mohammad al-Otaibi]], who had misled the media and had fled the country shortly afterwards. He warned that no-one should dare commit \"such acts on the soil of a [[NATO]] ally again\" and wrote: \"As responsible members of the international community, we must reveal the identities of the puppet masters behind Khashoggi's killing and discover those in whom Saudi officials{{snd}} still trying to cover up the murder{{snd}} have placed their trust... We know that the order to kill Khashoggi came from the highest levels of the Saudi government.\" He urged the international community to uncover the whole truth.<ref name=\"Erdogan\">{{cite news |last1=Recep Tayyip Erdogan |title=Saudi Arabia still has many questions to answer about Jamal Khashoggi's killing |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/11/02/recep-tayyip-erdogan-saudi-arabia-still-has-many-questions-to-answer-about-jamal-khashoggis-killing |website=The Washington Post |date=2 November 2018 |access-date=15 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115152537/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/11/02/recep-tayyip-erdogan-saudi-arabia-still-has-many-questions-to-answer-about-jamal-khashoggis-killing/ |archive-date=15 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Tampering with evidence===\nOn 5 November, ''Daily Sabah'' quoted a Turkish official that an 11-member \"investigative team\" had been sent by Saudi Arabia to Istanbul on 11 October.<ref name=\"MEE_Compensation\">{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia to pay compensation to Khashoggi family, fiancee: Turkish official |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-arabia-pay-compensation-khashoggi-family-and-fiancee-says-turkish-official-2016567611 |accessdate=10 November 2018 |website=Middle East Eye |date=6 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111043945/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-arabia-pay-compensation-khashoggi-family-and-fiancee-says-turkish-official-2016567611 |archive-date=11 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Chemist Ahmad Abdulaziz Aljanobi and toxicology expert Khaled Yahya al-Zahrani were sent as a part of the investigative team to erase the evidence and cover up.<ref name=\"MEE_Saudi_CoverTeam\"/> This was mentioned by the Turkish official as a sign of awareness about the crime among the top Saudi officials.<ref name=\"Reuters_Tapes_given\"/> The Saudi team had visited the consulate everyday between 11 and 17 October.<ref name=\"MEE_Saudi_CoverTeam\"/> On 15 October, Turkish police were allowed for the first time to enter the consulate.<ref name=\"MEE_Saudi_CoverTeam\">{{cite news |title=audi team sent to Istanbul to 'cover up' Khashoggi murder: Turkish official |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/two-saudis-sent-istanbul-cover-khashoggi-murder-turkish-official-1558214130 |accessdate=10 November 2018 |website=Middle East Eye |date=5 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111044012/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/two-saudis-sent-istanbul-cover-khashoggi-murder-turkish-official-1558214130 |archive-date=11 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Audio tapes===\nSpeaking before his departure for Paris to attend the [[Armistice of 11 November 1918|World War I armistice]] centenary, Erdo\u011fan acknowledged the existence of audio recordings in a televised speech on 10 November to maintain the pressure from the international community on Saudi Arabia to reveal who ordered the murder of Khashoggi. He said: \"We gave the tapes. We gave them to Saudi Arabia, to the United States, Germans, French and British, all of them.\" It was the first time that he disclosed that the three European Union states had heard the recordings. [[Reuters]] reported that Turkey had multiple audio recordings of the Khashoggi incident.<ref name=\"Reuters_Tapes_given\" /> These recordings document Khashoggi's torture and death, as well as conversations from the days prior to the incident that Turkey had uncovered during its investigation. Based on these recordings, Turkey had concluded from an early stage that the killing was premeditated. [[Saud al-Qahtani]] was reported as having a major role throughout the recording.<ref name=\"Reuters_Tapes_given\">{{cite news |title=Turkey gave Khashoggi tapes to European nations, Erdogan says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey/turkey-gave-khashoggi-tapes-to-european-nations-erdogan-says-idUSKCN1NF0EQ |accessdate=10 November 2018 |agency=Reuters |date=10 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110171320/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey/turkey-gave-khashoggi-tapes-to-european-nations-erdogan-says-idUSKCN1NF0EQ |archive-date=10 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><!-- <ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/tape-of-khashoggis-killing-has-been-given-to-us-saudi-europeans-erdogan-says/2018/11/10/bb21ab5e-e4e0-11e8-ab2c-b31dcd53ca6b_story.html</ref> -->\n\nWhile attending the [[World War I centennial]] commemorations in France, Erdo\u011fan discussed with President Donald Trump how to further respond to the killing. And a further closed-door meeting with Secretary-General [[Ant\u00f3nio Guterres]] of the [[United Nations]] took place.<ref>{{cite news |title=Erdo\u011fan, Trump meet over dinner in French capital |url=https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/erdogan-trump-meet-over-dinner-in-french-capital-3465965 |date=11 November 2018 |publisher=Yeni Safak |access-date=12 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112101403/https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/erdogan-trump-meet-over-dinner-in-french-capital-3465965 |archive-date=12 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> President Trump and French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] agreed that more details were needed from KSA on Khashoggi's murder. Accordingly, they also agreed that the case should not cause further destabilization in the Middle East; and fallout from the Khashoggi affair could create a way forward to find a resolution to the ongoing [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|War in Yemen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Will Saudi Arabia ever reveal who ordered the killing of Jamal Khashoggi? Luciano Zaccara (Assistant Professor of Gulf Politics at the Gulf Studies Center at Qatar University), Matthew Bryza (Former White House official, now a non-Resident Senior Fellow at the Atlantic Council), Selva Tor (Professor of Political Science and International Relations at Ko\u00e7 University)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uXbJ2RRw2Yk|website=Al Jazeera English|date=11 November 2018|access-date=12 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112183448/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uXbJ2RRw2Yk|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCanadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] gave public confirmation that Turkey had shared audio of the killing with world governments.<ref name=\"LeMon12Nov\">{{cite web |last1=Madjid Zerrouky |title=Le premier ministre canadien confirme l'existence d'enregistrements de l'assassinat du journaliste |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/proche-orient/article/2018/11/12/affaire-khashoggi-le-premier-ministre-canadien-confirme-l-existence-d-enregistrements_5382548_3218.html |quote=S'il y a un probl\u00e8me de communication entre les diff\u00e9rentes institutions au sein du gouvernement fran\u00e7ais, il appartient aux autorit\u00e9s fran\u00e7aises et non \u00e0 la Turquie de r\u00e9gler ce probl\u00e8me. |website=Le Monde |date=12 November 2018 |access-date=12 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112221849/https://www.lemonde.fr/proche-orient/article/2018/11/12/affaire-khashoggi-le-premier-ministre-canadien-confirme-l-existence-d-enregistrements_5382548_3218.html |archive-date=12 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Guard12Nov\">{{cite web |last1=Patrick |first1=Patrick |title=Trudeau says Canada received Turkish tape of Khashoggi murder |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/nov/12/trudeau-says-canada-has-received-turkish-tape-of-khashoggi |website=The Guardian |date=12 November 2018 |access-date=12 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112211149/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/nov/12/trudeau-says-canada-has-received-turkish-tape-of-khashoggi |archive-date=12 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The German government also confirmed it had received information from the Turkish authorities, but declined to elaborate.<ref>{{cite web |title=Geheimdienst-Kooperation Frankreich widerspricht T\u00fcrkei \u2013 offenbar keine Aufnahmen zu Khashoggi-Mord erhalten |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/frankreich-hat-die-aufnahmen-von-jamal-khashoggi-nicht-von-der-tuerkei-erhalten-a-1238012.html |website=Der Spiegel |publisher=dop/Reuters/AP/AFP |date=12 November 2018 |access-date=12 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112153727/http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/frankreich-hat-die-aufnahmen-von-jamal-khashoggi-nicht-von-der-tuerkei-erhalten-a-1238012.html |archive-date=12 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The British Foreign Secretary [[Jeremy Hunt]] paid an official visit to KSA and called for its cooperation with a \"credible\" investigation into Khashoggi's killing.<ref name=\"thetimes1\">{{cite news |last=Spencer |first=Richard |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jeremy-hunt-presses-saudi-arabia-over-yemen-and-khashoggi-t9tq9sjlz |title='Tell your boss' recording could link Saudi prince to Khashoggi's death |newspaper=The Times |date=13 November 2018 |accessdate=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121225415/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jeremy-hunt-presses-saudi-arabia-over-yemen-and-khashoggi-t9tq9sjlz |archive-date=21 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOne of the assassins was heard saying \"I know how to cut\" on the audio tape.<ref name=\"guard14dec\">{{cite news|agency=Reuters|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/dec/14/khashoggi-killer-heard-saying-i-know-how-to-cut-on-audio-erdogan|title=Khashoggi killer heard saying 'I know how to cut' on audio \u2013 Erdo\u011fan|newspaper=The Guardian|date=14 December 2018|accessdate=15 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214234246/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/dec/14/khashoggi-killer-heard-saying-i-know-how-to-cut-on-audio-erdogan|archive-date=14 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Charges===\n\nOn 15 November 2018, the Saudi Prosecutor's Office stated that 11 Saudi nationals had been indicted and charged with murdering Khashoggi and that five of the individuals who were indicted would face the [[Capital punishment in Saudi Arabia|death penalty]], since it had been determined they were directly involved in \"ordering and executing the crime\".  Prosecutors alleged that shortly after Khashoggi entered the Saudi Consulate in Istanbul he was bound and then injected with an overdose of a [[sedative]] that resulted in his death. The prosecutors also alleged that his body had been dismembered and removed from the consulate by five of those charged in the killing and given to a local collaborator for disposal. Saudi officials continued to deny that the Saudi Royal Family was involved in, ordered, or sanctioned the killing.<ref name=\"fivedeathsentence\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/15/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-prosecutor-death-penalty-intl/index.html|title=Saudis seek death penalty, details Khashoggi's death|first1=Sarah|last1=El Sirgany|first2=Nada|last2=Altaher|first3=Bianca|last3=Britton|publisher=CNN|access-date=15 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115215513/https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/15/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-prosecutor-death-penalty-intl/index.html|archive-date=15 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"fiveexecute\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/11/15/668162272/khashoggi-case-update-saudi-prosecutor-says-5-suspects-should-be-executed|title=Khashoggi Case Update: Saudi Prosecutor Says 5 Suspects Should Be Executed|publisher=|access-date=15 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115164655/https://www.npr.org/2018/11/15/668162272/khashoggi-case-update-saudi-prosecutor-says-5-suspects-should-be-executed|archive-date=15 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 November 2018, several news organizations including ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''The Washington Post'' reported that CIA was unequivocal in assessing with \"high confidence\" that the crown prince Mohammad bin Salman ordered Khashoggi's assassination. The agency examined multiple sources of intelligence, including an [[intercepted]] phone call that the crown prince's brother [[Khalid bin Salman]]{{snd}} the then Saudi ambassador to the United States{{snd}} had with Khashoggi. A conclusion that contradicted previous Saudi government claims that the crown prince was not involved. A CIA spokesman and both the White House and the [[US State Department]] declined to comment. The Saudis issued a denial.<ref name=\"cia\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=CIA concludes Saudi prince ordered Khashoggi's killing (Interview with Fawaz A. Gerges, chair of Contemporary Middle East Studies at the LSE) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9zGx-AjbXmU |website=Youtube |publisher=CBC News |date=17 November 2018 |access-date=19 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118083243/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9zGx-AjbXmU |archive-date=18 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 November 2018, Trump issued the statement \"On Standing with Saudi Arabia\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Donald J. Trump|title=On Standing with Saudi Arabia|publisher=whitehouse.gov|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-president-donald-j-trump-standing-saudi-arabia|date=20 November 2018|access-date=24 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124130615/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-president-donald-j-trump-standing-saudi-arabia/|archive-date=24 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and without citing further evidence he denied the CIA's conclusion: \"Our intelligence agencies continue to assess all information, but it could very well be that the Crown Prince had knowledge of this tragic event{{snd}} maybe he did and maybe he didn't!\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=[[Michael Hirsh (journalist)|Michael Hirsh]] |title=What Happened to Trump's Khashoggi Report? |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/11/20/what-happened-to-the-khashoggi-report-trump-talked-about/ |magazine=Foreign Policy |date=20 November 2018 |quote=Indeed, in his extraordinary statement on Tuesday, Trump laid out one of the most naked and amoral declarations of American realpolitik \u2013 the idea that the United States is interested only in material and geopolitical benefit, and no longer cares to promulgate its values \u2013 of any president in U.S. history. |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124220251/https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/11/20/what-happened-to-the-khashoggi-report-trump-talked-about/ |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=nov20 /><ref>{{cite web |title=With Khashoggi decision, Trump places strategic interests above human rights |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZUw9i1qEPgg |website=Youtube |publisher=PBS NewsHour |date=20 November 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122060754/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZUw9i1qEPgg |archive-date=22 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a series of interviews President Trump said the crown prince denies his involvement \"vehemently\" and the CIA only has \"feelings\" and there is \"no smoking gun\" in the death.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trump contradicts CIA assessment on Khashoggi killing |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-contradicts-cia-assessment-on-khashoggi-killing |publisher=FoxNews.com |date=21 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124134126/https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-contradicts-cia-assessment-on-khashoggi-killing |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The next day ''H\u00fcrriyet'' columnist [[Abdulkadir Selvi]] wrote that the \"''CIA holds 'smoking gun phone call' of Saudi Crown Prince on Khashoggi murder''\"<ref>{{cite news |title=CIA holds 'smoking gun phone call' of Saudi Crown Prince on Khashoggi murder |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/cia-holds-smoking-gun-phone-call-of-saudi-crown-prince-on-khashoggi-murder-columnist-139079 |newspaper=H\u00fcrriyet |date=22 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124220121/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/cia-holds-smoking-gun-phone-call-of-saudi-crown-prince-on-khashoggi-murder-columnist-139079 |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and that the [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]] [[Gina Haspel]] has possession of an intercepted phone call in which crown prince [[Mohammad bin Salman|Mohammad]] gives an order to his brother [[Khalid bin Salman|Khalid]] \"''to silence Jamal Khashoggi as soon as possible''\". \"The subsequent murder is the ultimate confirmation of this instruction.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=CIA Has Recording of Saudi Crown Prince Ordering Khashoggi Silenced |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/report-cia-has-tape-of-saudi-crown-prince-giving-instructions-to-silence-khasoggi-1.6677571 |agency=Reuters |work=Haaretz |date=22 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124140644/https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/report-cia-has-tape-of-saudi-crown-prince-giving-instructions-to-silence-khasoggi-1.6677571 |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey says the CIA has a 'smoking gun' tape nailing the Saudi crown prince in the Khashoggi case |url=https://www.sfgate.com/technology/businessinsider/article/Turkey-says-the-CIA-has-a-smoking-gun-tape-13414259.php |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=22 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124162418/https://www.sfgate.com/technology/businessinsider/article/Turkey-says-the-CIA-has-a-smoking-gun-tape-13414259.php |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Turkish media: CIA has recording of MBS ordering Khashoggi murder |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xkZYVjsRRig |website=Youtube |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=22 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123014639/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xkZYVjsRRig |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCiting the leaked CIA assessment, ''The Wall Street Journal'' reported that Mohammed bin Salman sent at least 11 text messages in the hours before and after the assassination on 2 October to his closest adviser [[Saud al-Qahtani]] who supervised the 15-man kill-team that was sent to Istanbul, and that Qahtani was in direct communication with the team's leader in Istanbul. The assessment also noted that Mohammed bin Salman had told his agents back in August 2017 that Khashoggi could be lured to a third country, if he could not be persuaded to return to the KSA.<ref>{{cite web |title=CIA Intercepts Underpin Assessment Saudi Crown Prince Targeted Khashoggi |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/cia-intercepts-underpin-assessment-saudi-crown-prince-targeted-khashoggi-1543640460 |website=The Wall Street Journal |date=1 December 2018 |access-date=2 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202053424/https://www.wsj.com/articles/cia-intercepts-underpin-assessment-saudi-crown-prince-targeted-khashoggi-1543640460 |archive-date=2 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, the message-exchange element of the report was contested by Saudi Arabia based on a confidential Saudi-commissioned investigation conducted by the private security firm [[Kroll Inc.|Kroll]]. The investigation, which focused on a forensic examination of a cellphone belonging to Saud al-Qahtani, found that none of the messages exchanged on the day of the murder between Prince Mohammed and Mr. Qahtani concerned the murder.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-commissioned-report-contests-u-s-finding-about-journalists-killing-11549498605 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=Saudis: Saudi-Commissioned Report Contests U.S. Finding About Khashoggi's Killing |date=7 February 2019 |access-date=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104164833/https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-commissioned-report-contests-u-s-finding-about-journalists-killing-11549498605 |archive-date=4 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman appeared in an interview with the CBS \"''[[60 Minutes]]''\" program that was aired on 29 September 2019, denying that he had ordered the killing of Jamal Khashoggi or that he had prior knowledge about it but said that he bears all responsibility for the killing of Jamal Khashoggi because the incident took place under his watch. He also said that \"once charges are proven against someone, regardless of their rank, it will be taken to court, no exception made.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mohammad-bin-salman-denies-ordering-khashoggi-murder-but-says-he-takes-responsibility-for-it-60-minutes-2019-09-29/|title=Mohammad bin Salman denies ordering Khashoggi murder, but says he takes responsibility for it|website=cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=30 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002062740/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mohammad-bin-salman-denies-ordering-khashoggi-murder-but-says-he-takes-responsibility-for-it-60-minutes-2019-09-29/|archive-date=2 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/29/middleeast/crown-prince-mohammed-bin-salman-interview/index.html|title=Mohammed bin Salman denies personal involvement in Khashoggi killing in '60 Minutes' interview but says it was carried out by Saudi officials|last=Maxouris|first=Christina|website=CNN|access-date=30 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001182811/https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/29/middleeast/crown-prince-mohammed-bin-salman-interview/index.html|archive-date=1 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March 2020, 20 Saudi nationals were reportedly indicted by Turkish prosecutors over the killing of Khashoggi.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/25/turkey-charges-20-saudis-over-jamal-khashoggi |title= Turkey charges 20 Saudis over Jamal Khashoggi murder. |}}</ref> According to the prosecutor's office in Istanbul, a royal court adviser Saud al-Qahtani, and Saudi's former deputy intelligence chief Ahmed al-Assiri were charged with inciting the murder; both had been investigated by Saudis in 2019 but acquitted or not charged.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/turkey-charges-20-saudis-over-khashoggi-murder/|title=Turkey charges 20 Saudis over Khashoggi murder|date=March 25, 2020|newspaper=Times of Israel}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.voanews.com/press-freedom/turkey-charges-20-khashoggi-killing |title= Turkey Charges 20 in Khashoggi Killing. |}}</ref> they were previously The suspects are believed to have fled Turkey, while Saudi Arabia has denied the Turkish claims for all the accused to be taken back to Turkey in order to answer for their crimes.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/turkish-prosecutors-file-indictment-khashoggi-killing-69785875 |title= Turkish prosecutors file indictment over Khashoggi killing. |}}</ref> According to Aljazeera, the charges were filed based on analysis of Khashoggi's accessories, witness testimonies, analysis of the suspects' phone records, including information on their whereabouts within and outside Turkey, as well as the consulate.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/istanbul-prosecutor-indicts-saudi-suspects-khashoggi-killing-200325083658411.html |title= Istanbul prosecutor indicts Saudi suspects for Khashoggi killing. |}}</ref> Even though arrest warrants have already been given out by the Turkish prosecutor for the accused, the office of the prosecutor however, did not disclose a specific date for the trial.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001365657/turkey-charges-20-saudis-over-khashoggi-murder |title= Turkey charges 20 Saudis over Khashoggi murder. |}}</ref>\n\n==Alleged perpetrators==\n[[File:Asiri and MbS.png|thumb|200px|[[Ahmad Asiri (general)|Ahmad Asiri]] (right)  and [[Mohammed bin Salman]] (left) in 2016]]  \nAl-Waqt news quoted informed sources as saying that [[Mohammad bin Salman]] had assigned [[Ahmad Asiri (general)|Ahmad Asiri]], the deputy head of the Saudi intelligence agency [[General Intelligence Presidency|Riasat Al-Mukhabarat Al-A'amah]]<ref name=\"saudigazette2013\">{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Gen. Asiri named deputy head of General Intelligence; Ibrahim Al-Omar is new SAGIA chairman|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/177105/Gen-Asiri-named-deputy-head-of-General-Intelligence-Ibrahim-Al-Omar-is-new-SAGIA-chairman|accessdate=13 October 2017|newspaper=Saudi Gazette|date=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113112753/http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/177105/Gen-Asiri-named-deputy-head-of-General-Intelligence-Ibrahim-Al-Omar-is-new-SAGIA-chairman|archive-date=13 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and the former spokesman for the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition in Yemen]], with the mission to execute Khashoggi inside the Saudi consulate in Istanbul. Another military officer with a great deal of experience in dealing with dissidents was the second candidate for the mission.<ref name=\"perps\">{{cite web|url = http://en.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn=13970718000686|title = Arab Source: Khashoggi Murdered by Ex-Spokesman of Saudi-Led Coalition in War on Yemen|publisher = [[Fars News Agency]]|accessdate = 10 October 2018|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181011053539/http://en.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn=13970718000686|archive-date = 11 October 2018|url-status = live}}</ref> On the same day, Turkish media close to the President published images of what it described as a 15-member \"assassination squad\" allegedly sent to kill Khashoggi, and of a black van later traveling from the Saudi consulate to the consul's home.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/5420263/saudi-arabia-jamal-khashoggi-assassination-squad/|title=Photos Purport to Show Hit Squad Sent to Kill Saudi Writer|website=Time|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014055021/http://time.com/5420263/saudi-arabia-jamal-khashoggi-assassination-squad/|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 October the ''[[Daily Sabah]]'', a news outlet close to the Turkish president, published the names and pictures of the 15-member Saudi team apparently taken at passport control.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish police identify 5 suspects linked to Khashoggi murder: report |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/investigations/2018/10/10/15-member-saudi-intel-squad-sent-to-target-wps-khashoggi-identified |newspaper=Daily Sabah |accessdate=17 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017212018/https://www.dailysabah.com/investigations/2018/10/10/15-member-saudi-intel-squad-sent-to-target-wps-khashoggi-identified |archive-date=17 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Additional details about identities were also reported along with their aliases.<ref>{{cite news |title=15-member Saudi 'intel squad' sent to target WP's Khashoggi identified |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/investigations/2018/10/17/turkish-police-identify-5-suspects-linked-to-khashoggi-murder-report |newspaper=Daily Sabah |accessdate=10 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017092212/https://www.dailysabah.com/investigations/2018/10/17/turkish-police-identify-5-suspects-linked-to-khashoggi-murder-report |archive-date=17 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to one report, seven of the fifteen men suspected of killing Khashoggi are Mohammed bin Salman's personal bodyguards.<ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Hearst |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/khashoggi-mohammed-bin-salman-saudi-arabia-suspects-969185217 |title=Exclusive: Seven of bin Salman's bodyguards among Khashoggi suspects |work=Middle East Eye |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=10 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018003141/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/khashoggi-mohammed-bin-salman-saudi-arabia-suspects-969185217 |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ''Daily Sabah'' outlet named and detailed:\n\n* Maher Abdulaziz Mutreb ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0627\u0647\u0631 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0645\u0637\u0631\u0628|links=no}}) (born 1971): a former diplomat in London, was photographed with [[Mohammad bin Salman]] on trips to [[Madrid]], [[Paris]], [[Houston]], [[Boston]] and [[New York City|New York]].<ref>[https://archive.today/20181016232142/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/16/world/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-prince.html Suspects in Khashoggi Case Had Ties to Saudi Crown Prince], by [[David D. Kirkpatrick]], Malachy Browne, Ben Hubbard and David Botti, 16 October 2018, [[The New York Times]]</ref><ref name=\"straitstimes\">{{cite news |title=Khashoggi case: Report links suspects to Saudi prince |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/middle-east/khashoggi-case-report-links-suspects-to-saudi-prince |work=[[The Straits Times]] |date=18 October 2018 |access-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020011536/https://www.straitstimes.com/world/middle-east/khashoggi-case-report-links-suspects-to-saudi-prince |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=One of the people believed to have been involved in Jamal Khashoggi's disappearance reportedly identified as frequent travel companion of Mohammed bin Salman |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jamal-khashoggi-disappearance-suspect-could-be-colleague-of-mohammed-bin-salman-2018-10 |work=Business Insider |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020053001/https://www.businessinsider.com/jamal-khashoggi-disappearance-suspect-could-be-colleague-of-mohammed-bin-salman-2018-10 |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> (convicted) Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* [[Salah Mohammed Tubaigy|Salah Mohammed al-Tubaigy]] ({{lang-ar|\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0628\u064a\u0642\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1971): the head of the Saudi Scientific Council of Forensics.<ref name=\"straitstimes\"/> (convicted) Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" /> \n* Abdulaziz Mohammed al-Hasawi ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0627\u0648\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1987): works as one of [[Mohammed bin Salman]]'s personal bodyguards.<ref name=\"straitstimes\"/>\n* Thaer Ghaleb al-Harbi ({{lang-ar|\u062b\u0627\u0626\u0631 \u063a\u0627\u0644\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0628\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1979): a member of the [[Saudi Royal Guard Regiment|Saudi Royal Guard]].<ref name=\"straitstimes\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" /> \n* Mohammed Saad al-Zahrani ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0633\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0632\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1988): a member of the [[Saudi Royal Guard Regiment|Saudi Royal Guard]].<ref name=\"straitstimes\"/><ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" /> \n* Meshal Saad al-Bostani ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0634\u0639\u0644 \u0633\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1987, died 2018): according to ''Al Jazeera'', a [[Lieutenant#Air force rank|lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Saudi Air Force|Saudi Air Force]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Matheson |first1=Rob |title=Who are the Saudi suspects in the Khashoggi case |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aGe1INeGhkU |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=17 October 2018}}</ref> According to Turkish media, he died in a car accident in Riyadh on return to Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite news |title=One of the men suspected of killing Jamal Khashoggi reportedly died in a car crash after returning to Saudi Arabia |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/khashoggi-suspect-mashal-saad-al-bostani-reportedly-dead-in-car-crash-2018-10 |accessdate=18 October 2018 |work=Business Insider |date=19 October 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018172317/https://www.businessinsider.com/khashoggi-suspect-mashal-saad-al-bostani-reportedly-dead-in-car-crash-2018-10 |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi who arrived in Turkey day of Khashoggi disappearance dies in 'traffic accident' |url=https://nypost.com/2018/10/18/saudi-who-arrived-in-turkey-day-of-khashoggi-disappearance-dies-in-traffic-accident/ |accessdate=18 October 2018 |work=New York Post |date=18 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018181319/https://nypost.com/2018/10/18/saudi-who-arrived-in-turkey-day-of-khashoggi-disappearance-dies-in-traffic-accident/ |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=One of 15 Saudis that targeted Khashoggi dies in suspicious car accident |url=https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/one-of-15-member-squad-that-targeted-khashoggi-dies-in-suspicious-car-accident-3463852 |accessdate=18 October 2018 |work=Yeni \u015eafak |language=tr-TR |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019040959/https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/one-of-15-member-squad-that-targeted-khashoggi-dies-in-suspicious-car-accident-3463852 |archive-date=19 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Naif Hassan al-Arefe ({{lang-ar|\u0646\u0627\u064a\u0641 \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u064a\u0641\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1986)<ref name=\"aljazeera 15 Saudis\">{{cite news |title=The 15 Saudis who flew to Turkey before Khashoggi's killing |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/15-saudis-flew-turkey-khashoggi-killing-181122144743650.html |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=aljazeera.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223162415/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/15-saudis-flew-turkey-khashoggi-killing-181122144743650.html |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n* Mustafa Mohammed al-Madani ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0635\u0637\u0641\u0649 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0646\u064a|links=no}})  (born 1961): Khashoggi's [[body double]] leaving the Saudi consulate by the back door, dressed in Khashoggi's clothes, a fake beard, and his glasses. The same man was seen at the [[Sultan Ahmed Mosque|Blue Mosque]], in an attempt to show that Khashoggi had left the consulate unharmed.<ref name=\"Tuysuz\">{{cite news |last1= Tuysuz |first1=Gul |last2=Abdelaziz |first2=Salma |last3=Balkiz |first3=Ghazi |last4=Formanek |first4=Ingrid |last5=Ward |first5=Clarissa |date=23 October 2018 |title=Surveillance footage shows Saudi 'body double' in Khashoggi's clothes after he was killed, Turkish source says |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/22/middleeast/saudi-operative-jamal-khashoggi-clothes/index.html |work=CNN |location=Istanbul |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023145023/https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/22/middleeast/saudi-operative-jamal-khashoggi-clothes/index.html |archive-date=23 October 2018 |access-date=23 October 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"ClarissaWard\">{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Clarissa |title=Who are the Saudi suspects in the Khashoggi case |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=41wj-5YKzkQ |publisher=CNN/Youtube |date=22 October 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024171328/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=41wj-5YKzkQ |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"TheGMcKernan\">{{cite web | last=Wintour | first=Patrick | last2=McKernan | first2=Bethan | title=CCTV footage appears to show Khashoggi body double in Istanbul | website=the Guardian | date=22 October 2018 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/22/cctv-footage-appears-to-show-jamal-khashoggi-body-double-in-istanbul | access-date=24 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023224357/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/22/cctv-footage-appears-to-show-jamal-khashoggi-body-double-in-istanbul | archive-date=23 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC23\"/>  Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Mansur Uthman Abahussein ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0646\u0635\u0648\u0631 \u0639\u062b\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0623\u0628\u0627\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646|links=no}}) (born 1972)<ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Waleed Abdullah al-Shehri ({{lang-ar|\u0648\u0644\u064a\u062f \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0647\u0631\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1980) (convicted),<ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Turki Musharraf al-Shehri ({{lang-ar|\u062a\u0631\u0643\u064a \u0645\u0634\u0631\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0647\u0631\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1982) (convicted)<ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Fahad Shabib al-Balawi ({{lang-ar|\u0641\u0647\u062f \u0634\u0628\u064a\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u0648\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1985) (convicted)<ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Saif Saad al-Qahtani ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u064a\u0641 \u0633\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062d\u0637\u0627\u0646\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1973) Not charged and released.<ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Middle 23 Dec\" />\n* Khalid Aedh al-Taibi ({{lang-ar|\u062e\u0627\u0644\u062f \u0639\u0627\u064a\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0628\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1988)<ref name=\"WaPo Oct 2018\" /> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\">{{cite web |title=Treasury Sanctions 17 Individuals for Their Roles in the Killing of Jamal Khashoggi {{!}} U.S. Department of the Treasury |url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm547 |website=home.treasury.gov |publisher=US Government |accessdate=23 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224073010/https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm547 |archive-date=24 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Badir Lafi al-Otaibi ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u062f\u0631 \u0644\u0627\u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062a\u064a\u0628\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1973)<ref name=\"WaPo Oct 2018\">{{cite news |title=What we know about the 15 Saudis said by Turkey to have played a role in Khashoggi's disappearance |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/investigations/khashoggi-saudi-suspects/ |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=The Washington Post |date=19 October 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223162413/https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/investigations/khashoggi-saudi-suspects/ |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* [[Ahmad Asiri (general)|Ahmad Asiri]], the deputy head of the Saudi intelligence agency [[General Intelligence Presidency|Riasat Al-Mukhabarat Al-A'amah]]. Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Middle 23 Dec\" />\n\n== Trial and convictions ==\nThe trial was conducted in secret with diplomats and Khashoggi family members permitted to attend but not speak. The court adhered to the official line that the killing was not premeditated.<ref name=\"Irish 23 Dec 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Jansen |first1=Michael |title=Khashoggi trial was an exercise in scapegoating and not justice |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/middle-east/khashoggi-trial-was-an-exercise-in-scapegoating-and-not-justice-1.4123789 |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=23 December 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223190308/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/middle-east/khashoggi-trial-was-an-exercise-in-scapegoating-and-not-justice-1.4123789 |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to the Saudi prosecutors, ten people were questioned and then released due to lack of evidence against them. A total of 11 people were put on trial by the court.<ref name=\"CNN 23 Dec 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Lister |first1=Tim |title=Saudi death sentence wipes MBS's fingerprints in Khashoggi killing |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/23/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-verdict-analysis-intl/index.html |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=CNN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223185112/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/23/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-verdict-analysis-intl/index.html |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The court conducted ten hearings that were not open to the public. A few foreign diplomats were allowed to attend the hearings after swearing to secrecy. CNN reported that lack of public access made it impossible to understand how the court decided the verdict.<ref name=\"CNN 23 Dec 2019\" />\n\nOn 23 December 2019 five people were sentenced to death for carrying out Khashoggi's killing:\n\n* Fahad Shabib Albalawi\n* Turki Muserref Alshehri\n* Waleed Abdullah Alshehri\n* Maher Abdulaziz Mutreb, intelligence officer\n* Dr [[Salah Mohammed Tubaigy]], a forensic doctor from the Saudi interior ministry<ref name=\"BBC23\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-50890633|title=Jamal Khashoggi: Saudis sentence five to death for journalist's murder|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=23 December 2019|access-date=23 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223094357/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-50890633|archive-date=23 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN 23 Dec 2019\" />\n\nThree other defendants, unnamed {{As of|2019|12|23|lc=y}}, were sentenced to a combined total of 24 years in prison for \"covering up this crime and violating the law\".<ref name=\"BBC23\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/saudi-arabia-sentences-five-people-to-death-over-khashoggi-killing-11893950|title=Saudi Arabia sentences five people to death over Khashoggi killing|website=Sky News|access-date=23 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223114252/https://news.sky.com/story/saudi-arabia-sentences-five-people-to-death-over-khashoggi-killing-11893950|archive-date=23 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe following defendants were released:\n\n* [[Saud al-Qahtani]], released without charge\n* [[Ahmed al-Assiri (general)|Ahmed al-Assiri]], a former deputy intelligence chief, released due to a lack of evidence\n* [[Al-Otaibi|Mohammed al-Otaibi]], Saudi Arabia's consul-general in Istanbul, released due to a lack of evidence<ref name=\"Middle 23 Dec\">{{cite news |title=Khashoggi murder: Saudi Arabia sentences five to death, Qahtani not charged |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-arabia-sentences-five-death-over-jamal-khashoggi-murder |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=Middle East Eye |date=23 December 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223161215/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-arabia-sentences-five-death-over-jamal-khashoggi-murder |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe eight Saudis convicted in the verdict can appeal further. Clemency can be offered by Salah Khashoggi, the eldest son of Khashoggi.<ref name=\"Middle 23 Dec\" />\n\n===Response===\nCNN reported that the verdict was accepted by Khashoggi's sons. According to [[Amnesty International]]'s Middle East Research Director Lynn Maalouf, the verdict was a whitewash and the organisation released a statement saying: \"The verdict fails to address the Saudi authorities' involvement in this devastating crime or clarify the location of Jamal Khashoggi's remains&nbsp;... only an international, independent and impartial investigation can serve justice for Jamal Khashoggi.\"<ref name=\"CNN 23 Dec 2019\" />\n\nThe [[United Nations]] rapporteur on summary executions, [[Agn\u00e8s Callamard]], described the sentence as a \"mockery\" of justice, since, according to her, it was an \"[[extrajudicial killing|extrajudicial execution]] for which the state of Saudi Arabia is responsible\" and its masterminds walk free.<ref name=\"aljaz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/turkey-rights-groups-decry-saudi-verdict-khashoggi-murder-191223171239748.html|title=Turkey, rights groups decry Saudi verdict on Khashoggi murder|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=23 December 2019|access-date=23 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223210119/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/turkey-rights-groups-decry-saudi-verdict-khashoggi-murder-191223171239748.html|archive-date=23 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThree weeks to the day after the death of Khashoggi, on 22 October 2018, his son and brother were summoned to a [[photo op]] with King Salman and the heir to the throne, at the Palace of Yamamah, in Riyadh. Salah bin Jamal Khashoggi and his uncle Sahel were received by the royals. Pictures of the event went viral, amid reports that Salah, who lives in [[Jeddah]], has been banned from leaving the country since 2017. A family friend, [[Yehia Assiri]], described the event as \"a serious assault on the family\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Feis |first=Aaron |url=https://nypost.com/2018/10/23/khashoggis-son-meets-with-saudi-king-and-crown-prince/ |title=Khashoggi's son meets with Saudi king and crown prince |work=Nypost.com |accessdate=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024152548/https://nypost.com/2018/10/23/khashoggis-son-meets-with-saudi-king-and-crown-prince/ |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/twitter-storm-khashoggi-son-meets-saudi-crown-prince-181024011910161.html |title=Twitter storm after Khashoggi's son meets Saudi crown prince |work=Al Jazeera |date=24 October 2018 |accessdate=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024192201/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/twitter-storm-khashoggi-son-meets-saudi-crown-prince-181024011910161.html |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Nick Paton Walsh]], a senior international correspondent, described it as \"a remarkable display of the sustained and catastrophic disconnect between Riyadh and the outside world. As if PR is something you shoot yourself in the foot with.\"<ref name=\"Walsh2018\">{{cite news |last=Walsh |first=Nick Paton |title=Meeting Khashoggi's son could backfire for bin Salman |website=CNN |date=24 October 2018 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/24/opinions/bin-salman-khashoggi-saudi-brand-opinion-intl/index.html |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024203852/https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/24/opinions/bin-salman-khashoggi-saudi-brand-opinion-intl/index.html |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 24 October 2018, Salah Khashoggi, who holds dual Saudi-US citizenship, and his family left Saudi Arabia for the US.<ref>{{cite web |first=Bethan |last=McKernan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/25/jamal-khashoggi-killing-premeditated-says-saudi-prosecutor |title=Khashoggi's son leaves Saudi Arabia as prosecutor says killing was planned |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 October 2018 |accessdate=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121213456/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/25/jamal-khashoggi-killing-premeditated-says-saudi-prosecutor |archive-date=21 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 8 December 2018, ''Newsweek'' reported allegations that Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman and President Trump's son-in-law, [[Jared Kushner]], had \"maintained unofficial communications via a WhatsApp chat for the past two years and&nbsp;... continued to speak in the wake of Khashoggi's killing.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/kushner-defended-crown-prince-murder-text-messages-1250810|title=Jared Kushner defended Saudi Crown prince after Khashoggi's death, and kept chatting in text messages, report says|last=O'Connor|first=Tom|date=8 December 2018|website=Newsweek|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120221602/https://www.newsweek.com/kushner-defended-crown-prince-murder-text-messages-1250810|archive-date=20 November 2019|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other alleged abduction attempts==\nFollowing Jamal Khashoggi's killing and mutilation, several other exiled Saudi activists reported that the Saudi regime attempted to lure them into their embassies.<ref name=\"Other Exiles1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/saudi-dissidents-fear-long-arm-state-khashoggi-murder-114854780.html|title=Saudi dissidents fear 'long arm' of state after Khashoggi murder|work=AFP|access-date=2 November 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106184437/https://www.yahoo.com/news/saudi-dissidents-fear-long-arm-state-khashoggi-murder-114854780.html|archive-date=6 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Other Exiles2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.presstv.com/Detail/2018/10/22/577772/Saudi-exiles-Jamal-Khashoggi-Mohammed-bin-Salman-trap|title=Riyadh tried to 'trap' us in overseas embassies: Saudi dissidents|work=PressTV|access-date=22 October 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022212752/https://www.presstv.com/Detail/2018/10/22/577772/Saudi-exiles-Jamal-Khashoggi-Mohammed-bin-Salman-trap|archive-date=22 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Middle East Eye'' published claims from an unnamed source with knowledge of Saudi intelligence agencies that the murder is part of a larger operation of silently murdering critics of Saudi government by a death squad named \"[[Tiger Squad]]\", composed of the most trusted and skilled intelligence agents.<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\" /> According to the source, the Tiger Squad assassinates dissidents using varying methods such as planned car accidents, house fires, or poisoning clinics by injecting toxic substances into opponents when they attend regular health checkups. The alleged group members are recruited from different branches of the Saudi forces, directing several areas of expertise.<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\" /> According to ''Middle East Eye'', five members were part of the 15-member death squad who were sent to murder Khashoggi.<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\"/>\n\nExiled Saudi activist Omar Abdulaziz said he was approached earlier in 2018 by Saudi officials who urged him to visit the [[Embassy of Saudi Arabia, Ottawa|Saudi embassy in Ottawa]], Canada with them to collect a new passport. The Saudi activist stated that the officials from the Saudi regime, \"They were saying 'it will only take one hour, just come with us to the embassy.{{'\"}} After Omar Abdulaziz refused, Saudi authorities arrested two of his brothers and several of his friends in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"Other Exiles2\" /> Abdulaziz secretly recorded his conversations with those officials, which were several hours long, and provided them to ''The Washington Post''.<ref name=\"Other Exiles3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/saudi-dissidents-fear-long-arm-of-state-after-khashoggi-murder/article/535176|title=Saudi dissidents fear 'long arm' of state after Khashoggi murder|work=Digital Journal|access-date=22 October 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022160313/http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/saudi-dissidents-fear-long-arm-of-state-after-khashoggi-murder/article/535176|archive-date=22 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The source interviewed by ''Middle East Eye'' also said the team planned to kill Omar Abdelaziz and claimed prince [[Mansour bin Muqrin]] was assassinated by the squad by shooting down his personal aircraft as he was fleeing the country on 5 November 2017 and made to appear as an accidental crash.<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\" />\n\nOpposition Saudi scholar Abdullah Alaoudh (son of [[Salman al-Ouda]]) said he was subjected to a similar plot when he sent in a passport renewal application to the [[Embassy of Saudi Arabia in Washington, D.C.|Saudi Embassy in Washington]]. Alaoudh said, \"They offered me a 'temporary pass' that would allow me to return to Saudi Arabia.\" Alaoudh suspected a trap and just let his passport expire.<ref name=\"Other Exiles1\" /><ref name=\"Other Exiles2\" /> Prominent Saudi women's rights activist [[Manal al-Sharif]] also separately reported a similar event during her exile in Australia, having said: \"If it weren't for the kindness of God I would have been [another] victim.\"<ref name=\"Other Exiles1\" /><ref name=\"Other Exiles2\" />  The Tiger Squad also reportedly killed Suleiman Abdul Rahman al-Thuniyan, a Saudi court judge who was murdered by an injection of a deadly virus into his body when he had visited a hospital for a regular health checkup. \"One of the techniques the Tiger Squad uses to silence dissidents or opponents of the government is to 'kill them with [[HIV]], or other sorts of deadly viruses'\".<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\" />\n\n==Reactions==\n{{main|Reactions to the assassination of Jamal Khashoggi}}\nFor 18 days, Saudi Arabian officials denied Khashoggi had died in the consulate, before indicating a team of Saudi agents had overstepped their orders to capture him when a struggle ensued leading to his death.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fraser |first1=Suzan |last2=Deeb |first2=Sarah El |last3=Press |first3=Jon Gambrell Associated |last4=October 19 |first4=Updated |title=For 1st time, Saudis say Jamal Khashoggi killed in consulate \u2013 The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/world/2018/10/19/saudi-state-run-news-agency-quotes-prosecutors-saying-that-jamal-khashoggi-was-killed-saudi-consulate-fight/YUMIdTDF7KIac1zBlADi3O/story.html |work=BostonGlobe.com |access-date=9 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709080032/https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/world/2018/10/19/saudi-state-run-news-agency-quotes-prosecutors-saying-that-jamal-khashoggi-was-killed-saudi-consulate-fight/YUMIdTDF7KIac1zBlADi3O/story.html |archive-date=9 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Turkey's president, [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], said he believes the killing was premeditated and approved by the Saudi government, and sought extradition of the suspects.<ref name=\"CNNErdogan_body\">{{cite news |title=Erdogan demands Saudi Arabia reveal the location of Jamal Khashoggi's body |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/26/middleeast/saudi-turkey-khashoggi-investigation-intl/index.html |accessdate=26 October 2018 |publisher=CNN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026213849/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/26/middleeast/saudi-turkey-khashoggi-investigation-intl/index.html |archive-date=26 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The United States' president, [[Donald Trump]], expressed support for the Saudi government, reserving judgment about culpability.<ref name=\"wintour\"/> This created a bipartisan uproar in [[United States Congress|Congress]], and 22 senators petitioned Trump to consider investigating whether Saudi Arabia should be sanctioned for human rights violations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jamal-khashoggi-missing-saudi-arabia-turkey-istanbul-consulate-dismembered-lindsey-graham-us-a8578266.html|title=Jamal Khashoggi disappearance: 'Hell to pay' for Saudi Arabia if journalist was murdered, Lindsey Graham says|newspaper=The Independent|date=10 October 2018|access-date=22 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012043114/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jamal-khashoggi-missing-saudi-arabia-turkey-istanbul-consulate-dismembered-lindsey-graham-us-a8578266.html|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Several countries called for a transparent investigation and condemned the killing. Allied Arab countries characterized the aftermath as a media campaign against Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia's Arab Allies Come To Its Defense In The Khashoggi Murder Affair |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/saudi-arabias-arab-allies-come-its-defense-khashoggi-murder-affair |publisher=[[MEMRI]] |date=24 October 2018 |language=en |access-date=9 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709080042/https://www.memri.org/reports/saudi-arabias-arab-allies-come-its-defense-khashoggi-murder-affair |archive-date=9 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGermany, Norway and Denmark<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zeit.de/news/2018-11/22/daenemark-stoppt-waffenlieferungen-an-saudi-arabien-wegen-fall-khashoggi-20181122-doc-1b10bj|title=D\u00e4nemark stoppt Waffenlieferungen an Saudi-Arabien wegen Fall Khashoggi|date=22 November 2018|work=Die Zeit|access-date=22 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122143651/https://www.zeit.de/news/2018-11/22/daenemark-stoppt-waffenlieferungen-an-saudi-arabien-wegen-fall-khashoggi-20181122-doc-1b10bj|archive-date=22 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> stopped the sale of arms to Saudi Arabia over the incident. Canada considered freezing its $13 billion [[General Dynamics Land Systems \u2013 Canada]] arms deal,<ref name=\"MEE_NorwayArms\">{{cite news|url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/norway-suspends-future-arms-exports-saudi-arabia-829709770|title=Norway suspends future arms exports to Saudi Arabia|date=9 November 2018|accessdate=9 November 2018|website=Middle East Eye|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110120140/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/norway-suspends-future-arms-exports-saudi-arabia-829709770|archive-date=10 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> but so far has chosen to proceed with the deal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/03/04/700055559/canada-set-to-go-ahead-with-arms-deal-saudi-arabia-says|title=Canada Set To Go Ahead With Arms Deal, Saudi Arabia Says|last=Mortada|first=Dalia|date=4 March 2019|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=25 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724091437/https://www.npr.org/2019/03/04/700055559/canada-set-to-go-ahead-with-arms-deal-saudi-arabia-says|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.karenvecchiomp.ca/saudi_arms_export_deal_warning|title=Killing Saudi arms export deal would 'devastate' London region, says Tory MP Vecchio|last=Moss|first=Neil|date=9 January 2019|website=Hill Times, via Karen Vecchio MP|language=en|access-date=25 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725034348/https://www.karenvecchiomp.ca/saudi_arms_export_deal_warning|archive-date=25 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a U.S. senator, the [[Trump administration]] granted authorizations to US companies to share sensitive [[Nuclear proliferation|nuclear power information]] with Saudi Arabia shortly after the assassination of Jamal Khashoggi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL2N23B13V|title=U.S. shared nuclear power info with Saudi Arabia after Khashoggi killed|date=4 June 2019|agency=Reuters|access-date=21 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721152022/https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL2N23B13V|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2019, Trump vetoed three bipartisan Congressional resolutions that would have halted arms sales.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/saudi-arms-sale-resolutions-trump-veto/index.html|title=Trump vetoes 3 bills prohibiting arms sales to Saudi Arabia|last=Cohen|first=Zachary|last2=Klein|first2=Betsy|date=25 July 2019|website=CNN|access-date=25 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725034347/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/saudi-arms-sale-resolutions-trump-veto/index.html|archive-date=25 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 2018, Khashoggi was named as a [[Time Person of the Year|person of the year]] by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine for his work in journalism, along with other journalists who faced political persecution for their work. ''Time'' referred to Khashoggi, and the others, as a \"Guardian of the Truth\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/11/business/media/jamal-khashoggi-person-of-the-year-time.html|title=Time Names Person of the Year for 2018: Jamal Khashoggi and Other Journalists|first1=Matthew|last1=Haag|first2=Michael M.|last2=Grynbaum|date=11 December 2018|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=11 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211214442/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/11/business/media/jamal-khashoggi-person-of-the-year-time.html|archive-date=11 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/11/media/time-person-of-the-year-2018/index.html|title=Time Person of the Year: 'The Guardians and the War on Truth'|first=Jill Disis and Brian Stelter, CNN|last=Business|website=CNN|access-date=7 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211202747/https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/11/media/time-person-of-the-year-2018/index.html|archive-date=11 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2018/12/11/times-person-year-guardians-truth-including-slain-journalist-jamal-khashoggi/|title=Time's Person of the Year: 'Guardians' of the truth, including slain journalist Jamal Khashoggi|website=The Washington Post|access-date=11 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211200623/https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2018/12/11/times-person-year-guardians-truth-including-slain-journalist-jamal-khashoggi/|archive-date=11 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Politics|Saudi Arabia}}\n*[[The Dissident]] \u2013 a 2020 American documentary film about the assassination of Khashoggi, directed by [[Bryan Fogel]]\n*[[Freedom of the press]]\n*[[Pegasus (spyware)]]\n*[[Human rights in Saudi Arabia]]\n**[[Israa al-Ghomgham]] \u2013 Saudi human rights activist who documented the [[2017\u201318 Qatif unrest]] and faces execution by beheading\n**[[Nimr al-Nimr|Sheikh Baqir al-Nimr]] \u2013 dissident cleric executed for criticism of the Saudi regime\n**[[Ali Mohammed Baqir al-Nimr]], (Sheikh Baqir al-Nimr's nephew), participated in the [[2011\u201312 Saudi Arabian protests|protests]] during the [[Arab Spring]], arrested at the age of 17 and sentenced to death, to be carried out by beheading and crucifixion\n**[[Salman al-Ouda]] \u2013 cleric in the city of Riyadh, urged the Saudi monarchy to launch democratic reforms, sentenced to death in September 2018<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=[[Dexter Filkins]] |title=In the Aftermath of Jamal Khashoggi's Murder, Saudi Arabia Enters a Dangerous Period |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/in-the-aftermath-of-khashoggis-murder-saudi-arabia-enters-a-dangerous-period |date=2 November 2018 |magazine=The New Yorker |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103210338/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/in-the-aftermath-of-khashoggis-murder-saudi-arabia-enters-a-dangerous-period |archive-date=3 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n**[[Raif Badawi]] \u2013 imprisoned Saudi dissident, writer and activist\n**[[Hamza Kashgari]] \u2013 pro-democracy activist and columnist imprisoned for blasphemy\n**[[Dina Ali Lasloom]] \u2013 imprisoned Saudi asylum seeker\n**[[Samar Badawi]] \u2013 imprisoned Saudi activist\n**[[Fahad Albutairi|Fahad al-Butairi]] \u2013 abducted in Jordan and taken to be imprisoned in Saudi Arabia\n**[[Manal al-Sharif]] \u2013 Saudi human rights activist\n**[[Loujain al-Hathloul]] \u2013 imprisoned Saudi activist\n**[[Mishaal bint Fahd bin Mohammed Al Saud]] \u2013 Saudi princess executed for alleged adultery\n**[[Sara bint Talal bin Abdulaziz Al Saud]] \u2013 exiled Saudi princess and regime critic\n*[[2016 Saudi Arabia mass execution]]\n*[[2017 Lebanon\u2013Saudi Arabia dispute|2017 Saad Hariri affair]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|On Standing with Saudi Arabia|Statement from Donald J. Trump On Standing with Saudi Arabia}}\n* [https://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/RegularSessions/Session41/Documents/A_HRC_41_CRP.1.docx Annex to the Report of the Special Rapporteur on extrajudicial, summary or arbitrary executions: Investigation into the unlawful death of Mr. Jamal Khashoggi] (19 June 2019), [[United Nations Human Rights Council]], 41st Session (24 June \u2013 12 July 2019) \n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/people/jamal-khashoggi Khashoggi's columns for ''The Washington Post'']\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/12/how-jamal-khashoggi-disappeared-visual-guide Visual guide to Khashoggi's disappearance] on ''[[The Guardian]]''\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uJ44spUo8Uk Killing Jamal Khashoggi: How a Brutal Saudi Hit Job Unfolded \u2013 Visual Investigations], The New York Times (YouTube), 16 November 2018.\n{{Authority control}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xaeYMysnuvY  The Jamal Khashoggi murder reconstructed, Al Jazeera English (YouTube), 3 April 2019]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khashoggi, Jamal}}\n[[Category:2018 controversies]]\n[[Category:2018 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2018 in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:2018 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:2010s crimes in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:2010s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic incidents]]\n[[Category:Khashoggi family]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Murder in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:October 2018 crimes in Europe]]\n[[Category:October 2018 events in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabia\u2013Turkey relations]]\n[[Category:2018 murders in Asia]]\n[[Category:Assassinations in Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|assassination of a Saudi journalist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{outdated|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Assassination of Jamal Khashoggi\n| partof      =\n| image       = Jamal Khashoggi in March 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Jamal Khashoggi in March 2018\n| map         =\n{{Location map|Turkey Istanbul\n| alt     = Location of the Saudi consulate in Istanbul\n| lat_deg = 41.0860\n| lon_deg = 29.0121\n| caption = \n| border  = none\n| float = center\n}}\n| map_size    =\n| map_alt     =\n| map_caption = Location of the Saudi consulate in Istanbul, where the assassination took place<ref name=\"cia\"/>\n| location    = Saudi consulate in [[Istanbul]], Turkey\n| target      = \n| coordinates = {{coord|41.0860|N|29.0121|E|display=inline,title}}\n| date        = {{start date |df=yes|2018|10|02}}\n| time        = Some time after 1 p.m. ([[Time in Turkey|TRT]]), when Khashoggi entered the Saudi consulate<ref name=\"cia\"/><ref name=\"NDTV_Fiancee\">{{cite news |title=\"Where Is Jamal?\": Fiancee Of Missing Saudi Journalist Demands To Know |url=https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/where-is-jamal-fiancee-of-missing-saudi-journalist-demands-to-know-1928951 |accessdate=13 October 2018 |agency=The Washington Post |publisher=NDTV |date=9 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091308/https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/where-is-jamal-fiancee-of-missing-saudi-journalist-demands-to-know-1928951 |archive-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| timezone    =\n| injuries    = \n| victim      = [[Jamal Khashoggi]]\n| assailants = \n| weapons     = \n| numparts    = \n| dfens       = \n| motive      = Allegedly to remove a prominent dissident and critic of the Saudi leadership<ref name=\"cia\"/><ref name=\"Washington Post 6 October 2018\"/>\n| inquiry     = \n| coroner     =\n| accused     =\n| convicted   = For murder:<br>Fahad Shabib Albalawi<br>Turki Muserref Alshehri<br>Waleed Abdullah Alshehri<br>Maher Abdulaziz Mutreb<br>[[Salah Mohammed al-Tubaigy|Salah Mohammed Tubaigy]]\n| verdict     = [[Capital punishment in Saudi Arabia|Death sentence]] for murder: five persons<br>\n                Imprisonment for cover-up of the murder: three other persons\n| convictions = \n| charges     = \n| litigation  =\n| website     = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module      =\n}}\n\nThe '''assassination of Jamal Khashoggi'''\u2014a [[Saudi people|Saudi]] [[dissident]], journalist for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', and former general manager and editor-in-chief of the [[Al-Arab News Channel]]\u2014occurred on 2 October 2018 at the [[Saudis|Saudi]] [[Consul (representative)|consulate]] in [[Istanbul]], Turkey, and was perpetrated by agents of the [[Saudi government]].<ref name=\"nytasassination\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/12/world/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-killing-saudi-arabia.html |title='Tell Your Boss': Recording Is Seen to Link Saudi Crown Prince More Strongly to Khashoggi Killing |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=12 November 2018 |access-date=13 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112233122/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/12/world/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-killing-saudi-arabia.html |archive-date=12 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bbcsaudi\">{{cite news |title=Jamal Khashoggi: An unauthorized Turkey source says journalist was murdered in Saudi consulate |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45775819 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 October 2018 |access-date=12 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009004244/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45775819 |archive-date=9 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lured to the consulate building on the pretext of providing him papers for his upcoming wedding, [[Jamal Khashoggi|Khashoggi]] was ambushed, suffocated, and dismembered<ref name=Sakelaris/><ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce>David D. Kirkpatrick & Nick Cumming-Bruce, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/19/world/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-Mohammed-bin-Salman.html Saudis Called Khashoggi 'Sacrificial Animal' as They Waited to Kill Him], ''New York Times'' (19 June 2019).</ref> by a 15-member squad of Saudi assassins.<ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce/> Khashoggi's final moments are captured in audio recordings, transcripts of which were subsequently made public.<ref name=Sakelaris>Nicholas Sakelaris, [https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2019/09/26/Saudi-Prince-bin-Salman-accepts-responsibility-but-not-blame-for-Khashoggi-death/6231569504880/ Saudi Prince bin Salman accepts responsibility but not blame for Khashoggi death], United Press International (26 September 2019).</ref><ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/09/audio-jamal-khashoggi-gruesome-murder-revealed-190909163642769.html Audio transcripts of Jamal Khashoggi's murder revealed], Al Jazeera (10 September 2019).</ref> The Turkish investigation concluded that Khashoggi had been strangled as soon as he entered the consulate building, and that his body was dismembered and disposed of.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/khashoggi-choked-death-dismembered-turkey-prosecutor-181031145816813.html|title=Turkey: Khashoggi strangled immediately after entering consulate|website=Al Jazeera|first=Umut|last=Uras|date=31 October 2018|access-date=31 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031231027/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/khashoggi-choked-death-dismembered-turkey-prosecutor-181031145816813.html|archive-date=31 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Turkish investigators, as well as investigations by the ''New York Times'', concluded that some of the 15 members of the Saudi hit team were closely connected to [[Saudi Crown Prince]] [[Mohammed bin Salman]], and that the team had traveled to Istanbul specifically to commit the murder.<ref name=Hubbard>Ben Hubbard, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/03/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-khashoggi-death-penalty.html Saudi Arabia Seeks Death Penalty for 5 Suspects in Khashoggi Killing], ''New York Times'' (3 January 2019).</ref>\n\nThe Saudi government engaged in an extensive effort to [[cover-up]] the killing, including [[Destruction of evidence|destroying evidence]].<ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce/> After repeatedly shifting its account of what happened to Khashoggi in the days following the killing, the Saudi government admitted that Khashoggi had been killed in a [[premeditated murder]],<ref name=\"admission\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/saudi-arabia-now-admits-khashoggi-killing-was-premeditated-n924286|title=Saudis change Khashoggi story again, admit killing was 'premeditated'|website=NBC News|last=Smith|first=Saphora|date=25 October 2018|access-date=25 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025155511/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/saudi-arabia-now-admits-khashoggi-killing-was-premeditated-n924286|archive-date=25 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC_murder_fox\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45935823|title=Saudis now admit journalist was murdered|last=|first=|date=22 October 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=22 October 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021230750/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45935823|archive-date=21 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> but denied that the killing took place on the orders of bin Salman,<ref name=\"admission\"/><ref name=\"fivedeathsentence\"/><ref name=\"fiveexecute\"/> who said he accepted responsibility for the killing \"because it happened under my watch\" but asserted that he did not order it.<ref name=Sakelaris/> Turkish officials released an audio recording of Khashoggi's killing that they alleged contained evidence that Khashoggi had been assassinated on the orders of  Mohammed bin Salman.<ref name=\"nytasassination\"/> By November 2018, the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]], based on multiple sources of intelligence, had concluded that bin Salman had ordered Khashoggi's assassination.<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite news |title=CIA concludes Saudi crown prince ordered Jamal Khashoggi's assassination |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-concludes-saudi-crown-prince-ordered-jamal-khashoggis-assassination/2018/11/16/98c89fe6-e9b2-11e8-a939-9469f1166f9d_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=16 November 2018 |access-date=17 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203145827/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-concludes-saudi-crown-prince-ordered-jamal-khashoggis-assassination/2018/11/16/98c89fe6-e9b2-11e8-a939-9469f1166f9d_story.html |archive-date=3 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same month, the United States sanctioned 17 Saudi individuals under the [[Magnitsky Act]] over the Khashoggi murder, including former bin Salman advisor [[Saud Al-Qahtani]], but did not sanction bin Salman himself.<ref>Kim Hjelmgaard, [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2018/11/15/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-seek-death-penalty-writers-murder/2009827002/ US sanctions 17 Saudi nationals over Jamal Khashoggi's killing], ''USA Today'' (15 November 2018).</ref> U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] disputed the CIA assessment, expressed support for bin Salman, and stated that the investigation into Khashoggi's death had to continue.<ref name=\"nov20\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/unusual-statement-disputing-cia-filled-exclamation-points-trump-backs-saudi-n938526 |title=In unusual statement disputing the CIA and filled with exclamation points, Trump backs Saudi ruler after Khashoggi killing |website=NBC News |date= |access-date=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121024654/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/unusual-statement-disputing-cia-filled-exclamation-points-trump-backs-saudi-n938526 |archive-date=21 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe murder prompted intense global scrutiny and criticism of the Saudi government.<ref name=RashadHosenball>Marwa Rashad & Mark Hosenball, [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi/saudi-sentences-five-to-death-three-to-jail-over-khashoggi-murder-idUSKBN1YR0SY Saudi Arabia sentences five to death over Khashoggi murder, U.N. official decries 'mockery'], Reuters (23 December 2019).</ref> A June 2019 report issued by the [[United Nations special rapporteur]] on [[extrajudicial executions]] [[Agn\u00e8s Callamard]] concluded that Khashoggi's murder was \"a brutal and premeditated killing, planned and perpetrated.\"<ref name=RashadHosenball/> Callamard determined that responsibility for Khashoggi's killing, and the elaborate campaign to cover it up, rests with the highest officials of the [[House of Saud|Saudi royal court]] and that \"credible evidence\" called for the \"investigation of high-level Saudi officials' individual liability, including the crown prince's.\"<ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce/> Callamard's report also detailed the role of the Saudi consul general in Istanbul in coordinating the killing, undercutting the claim that the murder was an unauthorized act by rogue operatives.<ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce/> The special rapporteur called for a criminal investigation to be undertaken by the UN and, because Khashoggi was a resident of the United States, the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]].<ref name=KirkpatrickCumming-Bruce/>\n\nIn January 2019, the Saudi government began trials against 11 Saudis accused of involvement in Khashoggi's murder.<ref>Donna Abdulaziz, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-begins-trial-in-khashoggi-murder-11546533394 Saudi Arabia Begins Trial in Khashoggi Murder], ''Wall Street Journal'' (January 3, 2019).</ref><ref name=RashadHosenball/> In December 2019, following proceedings shrouded in secrecy, a Saudi court acquitted three defendants; sentenced five defendants to [[Capital punishment in Saudi Arabia|death]]; and sentenced three defendants to prison terms.<ref name=RashadHosenball/> The acquitted defendants, [[Saud al-Qahtani]] and [[Ahmad Asiri (general)|Ahmed al-Asiri]], were high-level Saudi security officials, while the five men sentenced to death were \"essentially foot soldiers in the killing.\"<ref name=RashadHosenball/> Saudi prosecutors rejected the findings of the UN investigation and asserted that the killing \"was not premeditated\" but was instead  \"taken at the spur of the moment.\"<ref name=RashadHosenball/> UN special rapporteur Callamard said the Saudi verdict was a \"mockery\" because \"the masterminds not only walk free, they have barely been touched by the investigation and the trial.\"<ref name=RashadHosenball/> Human rights group [[Amnesty International]] called the verdict a \"whitewash\" and the Turkish government said that the trials had fallen far short of \"justice being served and accountability.\"<ref name=RashadHosenball/>\n\n==Victim==\n{{main|Jamal Khashoggi}}\n[[File:P06409PS-0571 (3594694537).jpg|4 June 2009 \u2212 after his speech ''[[A New Beginning]]'' at [[Cairo University]], U.S. President [[Barack Obama|Obama]]  participates in a roundtable interview with, among others, Jamal Khashoggi, [[Bambang Harymurti]], and [[Nahum Barnea]].|thumb|right]]  \t \t\n\nKhashoggi was a Saudi journalist,<ref name=\"bbcsaudi\"/> author, and a former general manager and editor-in-chief of [[Al-Arab News Channel]].<ref name=\"speakers\">{{cite web|title=Speakers|url=http://www.prwcdubai.com/english/speaker_article.php?idsp=11|publisher=International Public Relations Association \u2013 Gulf Chapter (IPRA-GC)|accessdate=10 May 2012|year=2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511210004/http://www.prwcdubai.com/english/speaker_article.php?idsp=11|archive-date=11 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He also served as editor for the Saudi newspaper ''[[Al-Watan (Saudi Arabia)|Al Watan]]'', turning it into a platform for Saudi progressives.<ref name=\"afb\">{{cite news |last= Hendley |first= Paul |title= Saudi newspaper head resigns after run-in with conservatives |url= https://en.hdhod.com/Saudi-newspaper-head-resigns-after-run-in-with-conservatives_a3996.html |accessdate= 11 October 2018 |newspaper= Al Hdhod |date= 17 May 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181116112423/https://en.hdhod.com/Saudi-newspaper-head-resigns-after-run-in-with-conservatives_a3996.html |archive-date= 16 November 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nKhashoggi fled Saudi Arabia in June 2017 and went into self-imposed exile in the US. He became a frequent contributor to publications like the ''Washington Post''{{'}}s global opinions section and continued to criticize the Saudi government from afar. He had been sharply critical of Saudi Arabia's [[Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia|crown prince]], [[Mohammad bin Salman]], and the country's [[King of Saudi Arabia|king]], [[Salman of Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"bbcsaudi\"/> He also opposed the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey says journalist Khashoggi 'killed at Saudi consulate' |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20181007-turkish-police-journalist-jamal-khashoggi-killed-saudi-consulate-mbs-washington-post |work=France 24 |date=7 October 2018 |access-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009002148/https://www.france24.com/en/20181007-turkish-police-journalist-jamal-khashoggi-killed-saudi-consulate-mbs-washington-post |archive-date=9 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe said, \"The government banned me from Twitter when I cautioned against an overly enthusiastic embrace of then-President-elect [[Donald Trump]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2017/09/18/saudi-arabia-wasnt-always-this-repressive-now-its-unbearable/|title=Saudi Arabia wasn't always this repressive. Now it's unbearable|last=Khashoggi|first=Jamal|date=|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=7 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006173627/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2017/09/18/saudi-arabia-wasnt-always-this-repressive-now-its-unbearable/|archive-date=6 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2017, the ''Washington Post'' published its first column by Khashoggi, in which he criticized the prince and the kingdom's direction and advocated for reform in his country. Once Khashoggi's collaboration with the ''Washington Post'' started, he was [[harassment|harassed]] via Twitter from pro-regime bot accounts commonly known as \"the electronic flies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/23/jamal-khashoggi-a-victim-of-saudi-internet-trolls|title=Khashoggi was victim of Saudi internet trolls, friend tells Euronews|date=23 October 2018|publisher=|access-date=2 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103210221/https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/23/jamal-khashoggi-a-victim-of-saudi-internet-trolls|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The \"lord of the flies\", the man who ran social media for crown prince Mohammed, was [[Saud al-Qahtani]]. The crown prince Mohammed ordered a zero-tolerance campaign against dissents, spearheaded by Qahtani, who is implicated in the murder of Khashoggi.<ref name=\"reut22Oct\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-adviser-insight/how-the-man-behind-khashoggi-murder-ran-the-killing-via-skype-idUSKCN1MW2HA |title=How the man behind Khashoggi murder ran the killing via Skype |agency=Reuters |date=22 October 2018 |access-date=22 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115040933/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-adviser-insight/how-the-man-behind-khashoggi-murder-ran-the-killing-via-skype-idUSKCN1MW2HA |archive-date=15 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"nyt20Oct\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/20/us/politics/saudi-image-campaign-twitter.html |title=Saudis' Image Makers: A Troll Army and a Twitter Insider |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Katie |last=Benner |first2=Mark |last2=Mazzetti |first3=Ben |last3=Hubbard |first4=Mike |last4=Isaac |date=20 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115201738/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/20/us/politics/saudi-image-campaign-twitter.html |archive-date=15 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nJust before his assassination, Khashoggi was launching projects to combat online abuse in an attempt to consolidate the [[Opposition (politics)|opposition]] and accuse crown prince Mohammed of mismanaging the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia (KSA). Khashoggi collaborated with Omar Abdelaziz, one of most visible public critics of the Saudi regime abroad who had received asylum in Canada, on a range of projects. One project was named Geish al-Nahl \u062c\u064a\u0634 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u062d\u0644 (Army of the Bees or The Bees Army). They wanted to create a counterpoint to the regime's propaganda machine{{snd}} \"a network of pro-democracy activists who would post and amplify one another's messages about Saudi political issues\".<ref name=\"FoPo19Oct\" /> Abdulaziz said they wanted \"to talk about the dissidents, the political prisoners, freedom of speech, human rights\" and \"make people aware of what's really happening\".<ref name=\"FoPo19Oct\">{{cite web |last1=Elias Groll |title=The Kingdom's Hackers and Bots Saudi Arabia is using cutting-edge technology to track dissidents and stifle dissent. |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/10/19/the-kingdoms-hackers-and-bots-saudi-dissident-khashoggi/ |website=foreignpolicy.com |accessdate=19 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020015413/https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/10/19/the-kingdoms-hackers-and-bots-saudi-dissident-khashoggi/ |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> And the Bee Movement should also provide [[cybersecurity]] to \"people living in Saudi Arabia and other oppressive regimes in the Middle East\" in need of a safe way to express themselves.<ref name=\"Ind20Oct\">{{cite news |last1=Bel Trew |title=Bee stung: Was Jamal Khashoggi the first casualty in a Saudi cyberwar? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-cyberwar-trolls-bee-army-missing-journalist-turkey-us-a8591051.html |work=The Independent |date=20 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107064614/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-cyberwar-trolls-bee-army-missing-journalist-turkey-us-a8591051.html |archive-date=7 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> As Khashoggi wrote in his last, posthumously published, column, he was of the opinion that \"What the Arab world needs most is [[free expression]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jamal Khashoggi |title=What the Arab world needs most is free expression |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/global-opinions/jamal-khashoggi-what-the-arab-world-needs-most-is-free-expression/2018/10/17/adfc8c44-d21d-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html |website=The Washington Post |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020001008/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/global-opinions/jamal-khashoggi-what-the-arab-world-needs-most-is-free-expression/2018/10/17/adfc8c44-d21d-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-saudi-princes-crackdown-was-confidant-tied-to-khashoggi-killing-1541178150|title=Behind Saudi Prince's Crackdown Was Confidant Tied to Khashoggi Killing|first1=Margherita|last1=Stancati|first2=Summer|last2=Said|date=2 November 2018|publisher=|accessdate=7 February 2019|via=wsj.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190205161652/https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-saudi-princes-crackdown-was-confidant-tied-to-khashoggi-killing-1541178150|archive-date=5 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKhashoggi and Abdelaziz were also working on a short film, showing how the Saudi leadership was dividing the country, a website tracking human rights and the new [[Foundation (nonprofit)|foundation]] \"Democracy for the Arab World Now\" (DAWN) Khashoggi was forming. They tried to keep their work secret from Saudi persecution. In late September 2018, Khashoggi met with friends in London to discuss his various plans.<ref>{{cite web |last1=[[Joby Warrick]], Loveday Morris, [[Souad Mekhennet]] |title=In death, Saudi writer's mild calls for reform grew into a defiant shout |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-death-saudi-writers-mild-calls-for-reform-grew-into-a-defiant-shout/2018/10/20/8fa185cc-d48b-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=20 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107232542/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-death-saudi-writers-mild-calls-for-reform-grew-into-a-defiant-shout/2018/10/20/8fa185cc-d48b-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html |archive-date=7 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn summer 2018, Abdulaziz's [[cellphone]] was infected with a [[surveillance]] tool. This was first revealed on 1 October 2018 in a detailed forensic report by [[Citizen Lab]],<ref name=\"CiLab1Oct\">{{cite web |last1=By Bill Marczak, John Scott-Railton, Adam Senft, Bahr Abdul Razzak, Ron Deibert |title=The Kingdom Came to Canada How Saudi-Linked Digital Espionage Reached Canadian Soil |url=https://citizenlab.ca/2018/10/the-kingdom-came-to-canada-how-saudi-linked-digital-espionage-reached-canadian-soil/ |publisher=Citizen Lab |date=1 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108025746/https://citizenlab.ca/2018/10/the-kingdom-came-to-canada-how-saudi-linked-digital-espionage-reached-canadian-soil/ |archive-date=8 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> a [[University of Toronto]] project that investigates digital espionage against [[civil society]]. Citizen Lab concluded with a \"high degree of confidence\" that his cellphone was successfully targeted with [[NSO Group]]'s [[Pegasus (spyware)|Pegasus spyware]] and attributed this infection to an operator linked to \"Saudi Arabia's government and security services\".<ref name=\"CiLab1Oct\" /> NSO's Pegasus, of which KSA has emerged as one of its biggest operators, is one of the most advanced spyware tools available. It is designed to infect cell phones without being detected. Among other known cases, KSA is believed to have used NSO software to target London-based Saudi dissident [[Yahya Assiri]], a former Royal Saudi Air Force officer and founder the [[human rights organisation]] [[ALQST]] and an [[Amnesty International]] researcher.<ref>{{cite web |title=Amnesty International Among Targets of NSO-powered Campaign |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/research/2018/08/amnesty-international-among-targets-of-nso-powered-campaign/ |website=amnesty.org |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001225006/https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/research/2018/08/amnesty-international-among-targets-of-nso-powered-campaign/ |archive-date=1 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Loveday Morris and Zakaria Zakaria |title=Secret recordings give insight into Saudi attempt to silence critics |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/secret-recordings-give-insight-into-saudi-attempt-to-silence-critics/2018/10/17/fb333378-ce49-11e8-ad0a-0e01efba3cc1_story.html |website=The Washington Post |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107232559/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/secret-recordings-give-insight-into-saudi-attempt-to-silence-critics/2018/10/17/fb333378-ce49-11e8-ad0a-0e01efba3cc1_story.html |archive-date=7 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThrough their sophisticated spyware attack on Abdulaziz's phone, the Saudi regime would have had a direct line into Khashoggi's private thoughts, and access to hours of conversations between the two men. Abdulaziz recalled: \"Jamal was very polite in public, but in private, he spoke more freely{{snd}} he was very very critical of the crown prince.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Avi Asher-Schapiro |title=How the Saudis may have spied on Jamal Khashoggi |url=https://cpj.org/blog/2018/10/how-the-saudis-may-have-spied-on-jamal-khashoggi.php |website=[[Committee to Protect Journalists]] |date=31 October 2018 |access-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108030351/https://cpj.org/blog/2018/10/how-the-saudis-may-have-spied-on-jamal-khashoggi.php |archive-date=8 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 September, just eleven days before Khashoggi was murdered in the Saudi consulate, he made a declaration of support for the Bees Movement. Using the Bee Army's first [[hashtag]] \"what do you know about bees\" he tweeted \"They love their home country and defend it with truth and rights\".<ref name=\"Ind20Oct\" />\n\nOn 9 October, one week after his disappearance, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' published an article in which Hatice Cengiz, Khashoggi's fianc\u00e9, claimed that he had applied for [[U.S. citizenship]].<ref name=\"WaPoCengiz9-10-2018\">{{cite web |last1=Hatice Cengiz |title=Please, President Trump, shed light on my fiance's disappearance |website=The Washington Post |date=9 October 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/10/09/please-president-trump-shed-light-on-my-fiances-disappearance |access-date=29 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030035528/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/10/09/please-president-trump-shed-light-on-my-fiances-disappearance/ |archive-date=30 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 October, The [[Wilson Center]] issued a statement saying that they had offered him a [[fellow]]ship at the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]] (or Wilson Center), located in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/article/statement-jamal-khashoggi |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223223759/https://www.wilsoncenter.org/article/statement-jamal-khashoggi |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Yah15102018\">{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Nazaryan |title=Think tanks reconsider Saudi support amid Khashoggi controversy |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/think-tanks-reconsider-saudi-support-amid-khashoggi-controversy-193104698.html |publisher=Yahoo News |date=15 October 2018 |access-date=28 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028073900/https://www.yahoo.com/news/think-tanks-reconsider-saudi-support-amid-khashoggi-controversy-193104698.html |archive-date=28 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 October, Marc Owen Jones, an assistant professor at [[Hamad Bin Khalifa University]] in Doha who researched Arab propaganda and has monitored Saudi Twitter bots for two years, said he has seen a massive surge in pro-regime Twitter activity, and in the creation of troll accounts, since Khashoggi went missing: \"There was such a huge spike in October in bot accounts and the use of the hashtags praising the crown prince, it's absurd\".<ref name=\"Ind20Oct\" />\n\nAfter Khashoggi's assassination, the Saudi cyber-operations were the focus of global scrutiny. The [[Government of Canada]] started an investigation in to those malicious cyberattacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2018/11/21/exclusive-saudi-dissidents-hit-with-stealth-iphone-spyware-before-khashoggis-murder/|title=Exclusive: Saudi Dissidents Hit With Stealth iPhone Spyware Before Khashoggi's Murder|first=Thomas|last=Brewster|website=Forbes|accessdate=7 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128002753/https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomasbrewster/2018/11/21/exclusive-saudi-dissidents-hit-with-stealth-iphone-spyware-before-khashoggis-murder/|archive-date=28 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018 Omar Abdulaziz granted [[CNN]] access to his text messages with Jamal Khashoggi, where the two discussed their sharp criticism and political opposition to Mohammed bin Salman.<ref>{{cite web |title=Khashoggi messages reveal sharp criticism of MBS |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A03r8oGCe3M |website=Youtube |publisher=CNN |date=2 December 2018 |access-date=3 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203120739/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A03r8oGCe3M |archive-date=3 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Nina dos Santos and Michael Kaplan |title=Jamal Khashoggi's private WhatsApp messages may offer new clues to killing |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/12/02/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-whatsapp-messages-intl/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=3 December 2018 |access-date=3 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203074511/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/12/02/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-whatsapp-messages-intl/index.html |archive-date=3 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Abdulaziz filed a lawsuit against an Israeli company [[NSO Group|NSO Group Technologies]] that allowed his smartphone to be taken over and his communications to be spied on by the Saudi regime.<ref>{{cite web |last1=David D. Kirkpatrick |title=Israeli Software Helped Saudis Spy on Khashoggi, Lawsuit Says |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/02/world/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-spyware-israel.html |publisher=NYT |date=2 December 2018 |access-date=3 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203034630/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/02/world/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-spyware-israel.html |archive-date=3 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===US intelligence reports===\n''The Washington Post'' reported on 10 October 2018 that [[United States Intelligence Community|U.S. intelligence]] intercepted communications of Saudi officials discussing a plan ordered by the Crown Prince Bin Salman, to capture Khashoggi from his home in Virginia.<ref name=\"WaPo 10-10-2018\">{{cite web |title=Crown prince sought to lure Khashoggi back to Saudi Arabia and detain him, U.S. intercepts show |website=The Washington Post |date=10 October 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/crown-prince-sought-to-lure-khashoggi-back-to-saudi-arabia-and-detain-him-us-intercepts-show/2018/10/10/57bd7948-cc9a-11e8-920f-dd52e1ae4570_story.html |access-date=10 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011020534/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/crown-prince-sought-to-lure-khashoggi-back-to-saudi-arabia-and-detain-him-us-intercepts-show/2018/10/10/57bd7948-cc9a-11e8-920f-dd52e1ae4570_story.html |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"WaPo 2018\">{{cite web |title=Saudis are said to have lain in wait for Jamal Khashoggi |website=The Washington Post |date=10 October 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/saudis-lay-in-wait-for-jamal-khashoggi-and-left-turkey-quickly-sources-say/2018/10/09/0e283e2e-cbc5-11e8-ad0a-0e01efba3cc1_story.html |access-date=9 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010013836/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/saudis-lay-in-wait-for-jamal-khashoggi-and-left-turkey-quickly-sources-say/2018/10/09/0e283e2e-cbc5-11e8-ad0a-0e01efba3cc1_story.html |archive-date=10 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The intercepted communications were regarded as significant because Khashoggi had bought a home in [[McLean, Virginia]],<ref>{{cite news |title=For Khashoggi, a Tangled Mix of Royal Service and Islamist Sympathies |website=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/14/world/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia.html |date=14 October 2018 |access-date=23 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017155108/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/14/world/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia.html |archive-date=17 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> where he lived after fleeing the [[KSA]]. Khashoggi had obtained an [[O visa]]{{snd}} also known as the \"genius\" visa, that offers individuals of \"extraordinary ability and achievement\" in the sciences, arts, education, and other fields and are recognized internationally{{snd}} he had applied for permanent residency status, and three of his children were US citizens.<ref>{{cite news |title=Friends of Saudi dissident say he failed to return after visit to Istanbul consulate |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/03/saudi-dissident-jamal-khashoggi-worry-after-his-absence-in.html |accessdate=25 October 2018 |work=CNBC |agency=Reuters |date=2 October 2018 |quote=Khashoggi was in the United States on an O-visa |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025150231/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/10/03/saudi-dissident-jamal-khashoggi-worry-after-his-absence-in.html |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"qz25102018\">{{cite news |last1=Heather Timmons |title=What does the US owe Jamal Khashoggi? |url=https://qz.com/1428499/jamal-khashoggi-what-trump-owes-khashoggi-under-us-law-and-constitution/ |accessdate=25 October 2018 |work=Quartz |date=19 October 2018 |quote=Khashoggi was living in the United States on an 'O' visa ... Three of Khashoggi's children are US citizens. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025185924/https://qz.com/1428499/jamal-khashoggi-what-trump-owes-khashoggi-under-us-law-and-constitution/ |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> As a [[Resident of the united states|legal resident of the United States]] Khashoggi was entitled to protection. Under a directive adopted in 2015, the US intelligence community has a \"duty to warn\" people{{snd}} including those who are not US citizens{{snd}} who are at risk of being kidnapped or killed. This directive was a central aspect of the conversation about the US's response to Khashoggi's disappearance.\n\nAccording to the [[National Security Agency]] (NSA) officials, the [[White House]] was warned of this threat through official intelligence channels.<ref name=\"Obs\">{{cite web| title=NSA: White House Knew Jamal Khashoggi Was In Danger| website=Observer| url=https://observer.com/2018/10/nsa-source-white-house-knew-jamal-khashoggi-danger| date=10 October 2018| access-date=20 October 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013053921/https://observer.com/2018/10/nsa-source-white-house-knew-jamal-khashoggi-danger/| archive-date=13 October 2018| url-status=live}}</ref> The Office of the [[Director of National Intelligence]] (DNI) of [[Dan Coats]] declined to comment on why Khashoggi was not warned.<ref name=\"qz25102018\" /> 55 members of Congress demanded in a letter clarity from DNI Dan Coats on what the intelligence community knew about the risk Khashoggi faced before his disappearance and whether American officials attempted to notify him that his life was in danger. In the letter, they sought insight into everything the NSA knows about phone calls and emails from Saudi officials on the Khashoggi case.<ref>{{cite web |title=Au\u00dfenminister Saudi-Arabiens sieht T\u00f6tung Khashoggis als Fehler |website=Der Standard |date=21 October 2018 |url=https://derstandard.at/2000089809286/US-Praesident-Trump-in-Fall-Khashoggi-unter-Druck |language=de |access-date=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025193735/https://derstandard.at/2000089809286/US-Praesident-Trump-in-Fall-Khashoggi-unter-Druck |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Knight First Amendment Institute at [[Columbia University]] filed a lawsuit against five US intelligence services \"seeking immediate release of records concerning U.S. intelligence agencies' compliance or non-compliance with their 'duty to warn' reporter Jamal Khashoggi of threats to his life or liberty\". The [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] joined the legal effort.<ref>{{cite web |title=US intelligence being sued for failing to warn Khashoggi of threat |url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20181121-us-intelligence-being-sued-for-failing-to-warn-khashoggi-of-threat/ |publisher=The Middle East Monitor |date=21 November 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123004610/https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20181121-us-intelligence-being-sued-for-failing-to-warn-khashoggi-of-threat/ |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Knight Institute Sues to Learn Whether U.S. Intelligence Agencies Complied With \"Duty to Warn\" Reporter Jamal Khashoggi of Threats to His Life |url=https://knightcolumbia.org/news/knight-institute-sues-learn-whether-us-intelligence-agencies-complied-duty-warn-reporter-jamal |publisher=Knight First Amendment Institute |date=20 November 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716083047/https://knightcolumbia.org/news/knight-institute-sues-learn-whether-us-intelligence-agencies-complied-duty-warn-reporter-jamal |archive-date=16 July 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 November, [[Central Intelligence Agency]] members who internally analyzed multiple sources of intelligence concluded that Mohammed bin Salman ordered Khashoggi's assassination.<ref name=\"cia\"/> On 20 November, US President [[Donald Trump]] disputed the CIA assessment and stated that the investigation into Khashoggi's death had to continue.<ref name=\"nov20\"/>\n\n==Disappearance==\n[[File:Ghanem al-Dosari.jpg|Saudi Arabian activist [[Ghanem al-Dosari]] at a protest outside the [[Natural History Museum, London]], 11 October 2018, after the disappearance of Jamal Kashoggi. The Saudi embassy was holding a Saudi National Day celebration at the museum.|thumb|right]]\n[[File:Consulate General of Saudi Arabia in Istanbul.jpg|The Saudi consulate in Istanbul, 16 October 2018,  after Khashoggi's disappearance.|thumb|right]]\nOver the year 2017, the House of Saud appealed to Khashoggi to return to Riyadh and resume his services as a media advisor to the royal court. But he declined in fear that it was a ruse and that upon returning he would be imprisoned or worse. Khashoggi met with crown prince Mohammed's brother [[Khalid bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Khalid]] at the [[Embassy of Saudi Arabia in Washington, D.C.|Saudi embassy in Washington]], in \"early 2018 or late 2017.\"<ref name=\"LedermanOct22\">{{cite web |last1=Josh Lederman |title=Khashoggi met with crown prince's brother amid efforts to return him to Saudi Arabia |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/mideast/khashoggi-met-crown-prince-s-brother-amid-efforts-return-him-n923031 |date=22 October 2018 |access-date=2 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102080709/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/mideast/khashoggi-met-crown-prince-s-brother-amid-efforts-return-him-n923031 |archive-date=2 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2018 Khashoggi visited the Washington embassy again, to retrieve paperwork for his pending marriage to his Turkish fianc\u00e9e, Hatice Cengiz. He tried to complete everything in the U.S. but was instead lured to the Saudi Arabian consulate in Turkey, where his fianc\u00e9e lived.<ref>{{cite news |title=Did Embassy in DC send Khashoggi to Istanbul? |url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/09/did-embassy-in-dc-send-khashoggi-to-istanbul |agency=Reuters and NBC |publisher=Euronews |date=9 October 2018 |access-date=2 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010060724/https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/09/did-embassy-in-dc-send-khashoggi-to-istanbul |archive-date=10 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=[[Boris Johnson]] |title=The murder of Jamal Khashoggi was a barbaric act. We mustn't let Saudi Arabia off the hook |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/21/murder-jamal-khashoggi-barbaric-act-mustnt-let-saudi-arabia/ |quote=First there was the transparent ruse by which the Saudi-born Washington Post columnist was tricked into endangering himself by leaving the United States. |work=The Telegraph |date=21 October 2018 |access-date=2 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102123432/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/21/murder-jamal-khashoggi-barbaric-act-mustnt-let-saudi-arabia/ |archive-date=2 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKhashoggi's first visit to the Saudi consulate in Istanbul was on 28 September 2018{{snd}} where he showed up unannounced. Having divorced his wife, who had remained in Saudi Arabia, he went to the consulate to obtain a document certifying that he was no longer married so he could marry his Turkish fianc\u00e9e. Before that visit he \"sought assurances about his safety from friends in the US\" and instructed his fianc\u00e9e to contact Turkish authorities if he failed to emerge.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/08/jamal-khashoggi-turkey-search-black-van-carried-body-saudi-arabia|title=Jamal Khashoggi: Turkey hunts black van it believes carried body|first1=Martin|last1=Chulov|first2=Patrick|last2=Wintour|date=9 October 2018|website=the Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215220703/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/08/jamal-khashoggi-turkey-search-black-van-carried-body-saudi-arabia|archive-date=15 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He received a warm welcome from officials, and was told to return to the consulate on 2 October. \"He was very pleased with their nice treatment and hospitality\", she later said.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/khashoggi-lured-back-saudi-consulate-warm-greeting-time/story?id=58857344|title=Though Khashoggi didn't suspect he may be in danger, he was still apprehensive|first=A. B. C.|last=News|date=30 October 2018|website=ABC News|access-date=2 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102062814/https://abcnews.go.com/International/khashoggi-lured-back-saudi-consulate-warm-greeting-time/story?id=58857344|archive-date=2 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 September Khashoggi traveled to London and spoke at a conference. On 1 October Khashoggi returned to Istanbul, and he told a friend that he was worried about being kidnapped and sent back to KSA.<ref name=\"TNYT30102018\" />\n\nMeanwhile, at around 16:30, a three-person Saudi team arrived in Istanbul on a scheduled flight, checked in to their hotels then visited the consulate, according to President Erdogan. Another group of officials from the consulate traveled to a forest in Istanbul's outskirts and to the nearby city of Yalova on a \"reconnaissance\" trip. Erdogan said a \"road map\" to kill Khashoggi was devised in Saudi Arabia during this time. In the night of 2 October, a 15-member group arrived from Riyadh on two private Gulfstream jets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/10/23/world/europe/ap-saudi-arabia-writer-killed-timeline.html|title=Key Moments Surrounding the Killing of Jamal Khashoggi|publisher=|access-date=2 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103210118/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/10/23/world/europe/ap-saudi-arabia-writer-killed-timeline.html|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 October 2018 CCTV showed the suspected agents entering the consulate around noon. Khashoggi arrived about an hour later, accompanied by his fianc\u00e9e Cengiz, whom he entrusted with two [[cell phone]]s while she waited outside for him.<ref name=\"TNYT30102018\">{{cite news |title=What Happened to Jamal Khashoggi? |website=The New York Times |date=3 October 2018 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/03/world/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-journalist-istanbul.html |access-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020052554/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/03/world/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-journalist-istanbul.html |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"AlJa8Oct2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/erdogan-closely-case-saudi-critic-jamal-khashoggi-181007143237024.html|title=Erdogan on Khashoggi vanishing: Upsetting this happens in Turkey|date=8 October 2018|access-date=19 October 2018|website=Al Jazeera|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019041311/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/erdogan-closely-case-saudi-critic-jamal-khashoggi-181007143237024.html|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC_8Oct2018\">{{cite news |title= Saudi journalist Jamal Khashoggi disappears after entering Saudi Arabia's consulate in Istanbul |url= http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-07/turkish-authorities-investigate-disappearance-of-jamal-khashoggi/10348304 |agency= [[Reuters]] |publisher= [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date= 7 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181017115417/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-07/turkish-authorities-investigate-disappearance-of-jamal-khashoggi/10348304 |archive-date= 17 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> He entered the consulate, through main entrance, at around 1 pm.<ref name=\"NDTV_Fiancee\"/> As he had not come out by 4 pm, even though the working hours of the consulate were until 3:30 pm,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://time.com/5416396/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-journalist-missing/ |title=A Columnist Walked Into Saudi Arabia's Consulate. Then He Went Missing |access-date=11 October 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011020839/http://time.com/5416396/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-journalist-missing/ |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cengiz contacted the authorities, phoning Khashoggi's friend, Yasin Aktay, an adviser to President Erdogan,<ref>{{cite web | title=Seine Verlobte im Interview: Aus diesem Grund ging Khashoggi beim zweiten Mal unbesorgt in das Konsulat | website=[[Die Welt]] | date=26 October 2018 | url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article182794750/Seine-Verlobte-im-Interview-Aus-diesem-Grund-ging-Khashoggi-beim-zweiten-Mal-unbesorgt-in-das-Konsulat.html | language=de | access-date=30 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208163013/https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article182794750/Seine-Verlobte-im-Interview-Aus-diesem-Grund-ging-Khashoggi-beim-zweiten-Mal-unbesorgt-in-das-Konsulat.html | archive-date=8 December 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> reported him missing and the police then started an investigation.\n\nThe Saudi government said that he had left the consulate<ref name=\"SPA1\">{{cite news |url= https://www.spa.gov.sa/1822222 |title= News snippet |publisher= [[Saudi Press Agency]] |date= 4 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181006075206/https://www.spa.gov.sa/1822222 |archive-date= 6 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC1\">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45758096 |title= Jamal Khashoggi: Washington Post blanks out missing Saudi writer's column |publisher= BBC |date= 5 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181019093042/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45758096 |archive-date= 19 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\"NPR1\">{{cite news |first= Sasha |last= Ingber |url= https://www.npr.org/2018/10/04/654591662/saudi-critic-vanishes-after-visiting-consulate-prompting-fear-and-confusion |title= Saudi Critic Vanishes After Visiting Consulate, Prompting Fear And Confusion |publisher= [[NPR]] |date= 4 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181019010138/https://www.npr.org/2018/10/04/654591662/saudi-critic-vanishes-after-visiting-consulate-prompting-fear-and-confusion |archive-date= 19 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> via a back entrance.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/10/alleged-saudi-hit-squad-linked-to-jamal-khashoggi-disappearance |title=Jamal Khashoggi: details of alleged Saudi hit squad emerge |last=Chulov |first=Martin |date=10 October 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=11 October 2018 |last2=McKernan |first2=Bethan |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011021035/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/10/alleged-saudi-hit-squad-linked-to-jamal-khashoggi-disappearance |archive-date=11 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Cabinet Erdo\u011fan IV|Turkish government]] first said that he was still inside, and his fianc\u00e9e and friends said that he was missing.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/03/world/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-journalist-istanbul.html |title= What Happened to Jamal Khashoggi? Conflicting Reports Deepen a Mystery |first= Carlotta |last= Gall |date= 3 October 2018 |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181020052554/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/03/world/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-journalist-istanbul.html |archive-date= 20 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nTurkish authorities have claimed that security camera footage of the day of the incident was removed from the consulate and that Turkish consulate staff were abruptly told to take a holiday on the day Khashoggi disappeared while inside the building.<ref name=\"guardian2\">{{cite news|date=9 October 2018|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/09/khashoggi-case-cctv-disappears-from-saudi-consulate-in-turkey|title=Khashoggi case: CCTV disappears from Saudi consulate in Turkey|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020131856/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/09/khashoggi-case-cctv-disappears-from-saudi-consulate-in-turkey|archive-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[General Directorate of Security (Turkey)|Turkish police]] investigators told the media that the recordings from the security cameras did not show any evidence of Khashoggi leaving the consulate.<ref name=\"NH_Thriller\"/> A security camera was located outside the consulate's front which showed him entering but not leaving, while another camera installed at a preschool opposite the rear entrance of the consulate also did not show him leaving.<ref name=\"NH_Thriller\">{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Joan |title=Jamal Khashoggi Case: A contemporary thriller |url=https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/opinion/jamal-khashoggi-case-a-contemporary-thriller |accessdate=14 October 2018 |publisher=National Herald |date=13 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014053123/https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/opinion/jamal-khashoggi-case-a-contemporary-thriller |archive-date=14 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe disappearance presented Turkish officials with a sharp diplomatic challenge. [[Jamal Elshayyal]] reported Turkish authorities were trying to walk a fine line so as not to damage the Turkish-Saudi relationship: \"There is an attempt by the Turkish government to try to find a way out of this whereby there isn't a full collapse of diplomatic relations, at least a temporary freeze between Saudi Arabia and Turkey. Because, if indeed, Turkish authorities can prove unequivocally that Saudi agents essentially murdered a journalist inside the consulate in Istanbul, it would require some sort of strong reaction.\"<ref name=\"AlJa8Oct2018\" /> Analysts have suggested that Khashoggi may have been considered especially dangerous by the Saudi leadership not because he was a long-time dissident, but rather, a pillar of the Saudi establishment who had been close to its ruling circles for decades, had worked as an editor at Saudi news outlets and had been an adviser to a former Saudi intelligence chief [[Turki bin Faisal Al Saud]].<ref name=\"Washington Post 6 October 2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkey-concludes-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-killed-by-murder-team-sources-say/2018/10/06/31ee4f86-c8d9-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html|title=Saudi forensic expert is among 15 named by Turkey in disappearance of journalist Jamal Khashoggi|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=14 October 2018|date=6 October 2018|first=Kareem|last=Fahim|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181007000044/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkey-concludes-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-killed-by-murder-team-sources-say/2018/10/06/31ee4f86-c8d9-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html|archive-date=7 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Assassination==\nAccording to numerous anonymous police sources, the Turkish police believe that Khashoggi was tortured and killed inside the Saudi consulate in Istanbul<ref name=\"reuters\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident/exclusive-turkish-police-believe-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-was-killed-in-consulate-sources-idUSKCN1MG0HU |title= Exclusive: Turkish police believe Saudi journalist Khashoggi was killed in consulate \u2013 sources |last= Coskun |first= Orhan |agency= [[Reuters]] |date= 6 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181014224621/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident/exclusive-turkish-police-believe-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-was-killed-in-consulate-sources-idUSKCN1MG0HU |archive-date= 14 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\"MEE\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/turkish-police-suspect-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-was-killed-consulate-report-1250529206 |title= Turkish police suspect Saudi journalist Khashoggi was killed at consulate |work= [[Middle East Eye]] |date= 6 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181007073811/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/turkish-police-suspect-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-was-killed-consulate-report-1250529206 |archive-date= 7 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> by a 15-member team brought in from Saudi Arabia for the operation.<ref name=\"Fahim 2018\">{{cite web |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkey-concludes-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-killed-by-murder-team-sources-say/2018/10/06/31ee4f86-c8d9-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html |title= Turkey concludes Saudi journalist Jamal Khashoggi killed by 'murder' team, sources say |first= Kareem |last= Fahim |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |date= 6 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181007000044/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkey-concludes-saudi-journalist-khashoggi-killed-by-murder-team-sources-say/2018/10/06/31ee4f86-c8d9-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html |archive-date= 7 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\"guardian1\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/06/saudi-journalist-killed-inside-consulate-turkish-sources |title= Saudi journalist 'killed inside consulate' \u2013 Turkish sources |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 6 October 2018 |access-date= 20 October 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181020223151/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/06/saudi-journalist-killed-inside-consulate-turkish-sources |archive-date= 20 October 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> One anonymous police source claimed that the dead body was \"[[Dismemberment|cut into pieces]]\" and quietly moved out of the consulate, and that all of this was \"videotaped to prove the mission had been accomplished and the tape was taken out of the country\".<ref name=MEE/> ''[[Middle East Eye]]'' cited an anonymous Saudi who said the [[Tiger Squad]] brought Khashoggi's fingers to Mohammad bin Salman in Riyadh as other evidence that the mission was successful.<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\">{{cite news | last1= Abu Sneineh | first1= Mustafa | title= REVEALED: The Saudi death squad MBS uses to silence dissent | date= 22 October 2018 | website= Middle East Eye | url= https://www.middleeasteye.net/tiger-squad-saudi-hitmen-khashoggi-mbs | accessdate= 22 October 2018 | archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/73MnJ9BcG?url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/tiger-squad-saudi-hitmen-khashoggi-mbs | archivedate= 22 October 2018 | url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 7 October, Turkish officials pledged to release evidence showing that Khashoggi was killed.<ref name=guardian1/> Aktay initially said he believed Khashoggi had been killed in the consulate,<ref name=MEE/> but on 10 October he claimed that \"the Saudi state is not blamed here\", something that a journalist for ''[[The Guardian]]'' saw as Turkey trying not to harm lucrative trade ties and a delicate regional relationship with Saudi Arabia.<ref name = guardian2/> Turkey then claimed to have audio and video evidence of the killing occurring inside the consulate.<ref name=\"WaPo1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/turks-tell-us-officials-they-have-audio-and-video-recordings-that-support-conclusion-khashoggi-was-killed/2018/10/11/119a119e-cd88-11e8-920f-dd52e1ae4570_story.html |title=Turks tell U.S. officials they have audio and video recordings that support conclusion Khashoggi was killed |first1=Shane |last1=Harris |first2=Souad |last2=Mekhennet |first3=John |last3=Hudson |first4=Anne |last4=Gearan |date=11 October 2018 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020074357/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/turks-tell-us-officials-they-have-audio-and-video-recordings-that-support-conclusion-khashoggi-was-killed/2018/10/11/119a119e-cd88-11e8-920f-dd52e1ae4570_story.html |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> U.S. President Donald Trump said the United States had asked Turkey for the recordings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-europe-45893993/jamal-khashoggi-we-ve-asked-for-tape-evidence-trump|title=We've asked for Khashoggi tape evidence \u2013 Trump|website=BBC News|access-date=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019224754/https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-europe-45893993/jamal-khashoggi-we-ve-asked-for-tape-evidence-trump|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> According to \"people familiar with the matter\", the audio was shared with [[Central Intelligence Agency]] agents; a CIA spokeswoman declined to comment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/saudi-claims-that-khashoggi-died-in-a-brawl-draw-immediate-skepticism/2018/10/19/e10d4186-d3ef-11e8-83d6-291fcead2ab1_story.html|title=Saudi claims that Khashoggi died in a 'brawl' draw immediate skepticism|last=|first=|date=|website=The Washington Post|language=en|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022232500/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/saudi-claims-that-khashoggi-died-in-a-brawl-draw-immediate-skepticism/2018/10/19/e10d4186-d3ef-11e8-83d6-291fcead2ab1_story.html|archive-date=22 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[CNN]] reported on 15 October that Saudi Arabia was about to admit to the killing, but would claim that it was an \"interrogation gone bad\", as opposed to a targeted death squad killing.<ref name=prepadmit>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/15/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-death-turkey/index.html|title=Saudis preparing to admit Jamal Khashoggi died during interrogation, sources say|website=CNN|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015201630/https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/15/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-death-turkey/index.html|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"prepadmit\"/> This claim drew criticism from some, considering that Khashoggi was reportedly dismembered and that his killing was allegedly premeditated, and the circumstances, including the arrival and departure of a team of 15, included forensic specialists presumed to have been present to hide evidence of the crime, on the same day.<ref name=prepadmit/>\n\nThe next day, ''[[Middle East Eye]]'' reported that, according to an anonymous Turkish source, the killing took about seven minutes and forensic specialist [[Salah Muhammed al-Tubaigy]], who had brought along a [[bone cutter|bone saw]],<ref name=\"MEE_7minutes\" /> cut Khashoggi's body into pieces while Khashoggi was still alive, as he and his colleagues listened to music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inquisitr.com/5119410/jamal-khashoggi-dismembered-alive-saudi/|title=Jamal Khashoggi Dismembered Alive, Saudi Killer Listened To Music During Murder|website=Inquisitr|accessdate=16 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017033937/https://www.inquisitr.com/5119410/jamal-khashoggi-dismembered-alive-saudi/|archive-date=17 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The source further claimed that \"Khashoggi was dragged from consul general [[Mohammad al-Otaibi]]'s office at the Saudi consulate ... Tubaigy began to cut Khashoggi's body up on a table in the study while he was still alive,\" and \"There was no attempt to interrogate him. They had come to kill him.\"<ref name=\"MEE_7minutes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/exclusive-khashoggi-829291552|title=Jamal Khashoggi's killing took seven minutes, Turkish source tells MEE|website=Middle East Eye|accessdate=16 October 2018}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Turkish pro-government newspaper ''[[Daily Sabah]]'' reported on 18 October that neighbours to the consul's residence had observed an unusual barbecue party, which the paper suggested might have been to mask the smell from the incineration of the dismembered corpse: \"We have been living here for twelve years but I have never seen them having a barbecue party. That day, they had a barbecue party in the garden.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/columns/merve-sebnem-oruc/2018/10/18/a-rogue-state-behind-khashoggis-disappearance-not-rogue-killers|title=A 'rogue state' behind Khashoggi's disappearance, not 'rogue killers'|accessdate=19 October 2018|work=Daily Sabah|author=Merve \u015eebnem Oru\u00e7|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019122015/https://www.dailysabah.com/columns/merve-sebnem-oruc/2018/10/18/a-rogue-state-behind-khashoggis-disappearance-not-rogue-killers|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' published reports from anonymous sources that Khashoggi was tortured in front of top Saudi diplomat Mohammad al-Otaibi, Saudi Arabia's consul general.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/pompeo-seeks-answers-amid-crisis-over-missing-saudi-journalist-1539690270?mod=trending_now_3|title=Turkey Details Alleged Killing of Saudi Journalist|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017091557/https://www.wsj.com/articles/pompeo-seeks-answers-amid-crisis-over-missing-saudi-journalist-1539690270?mod=trending_now_3|archive-date=17 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/jamal-khashoggi-tortured-saudi-diplomat-reports_us_5bc736d8e4b0d38b5873dc98|title=Jamal Khashoggi Tortured In Front Of Top Saudi Diplomat: Reports|website=Huffington Post|accessdate=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018043214/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/jamal-khashoggi-tortured-saudi-diplomat-reports_us_5bc736d8e4b0d38b5873dc98|archive-date=18 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Reuters reported that al-Otaibi left Istanbul for [[Riyadh]] on 16 October. His departure came hours before his home was expected to be searched in relation to the journalist's disappearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident-consul/saudi-consul-general-leaves-turkey-for-riyadh-turkish-broadcasters-idUSKCN1MQ23T|title=Saudi consul general leaves Turkey for Riyadh: Turkish broadcasters|agency=Reuters|accessdate=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018044649/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident-consul/saudi-consul-general-leaves-turkey-for-riyadh-turkish-broadcasters-idUSKCN1MQ23T|archive-date=18 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 October, the Saudi Foreign Ministry reported that a preliminary investigation showed that Khashoggi had died at the consulate while engaged in a fight, the first Saudi acknowledgement of Khashoggi's death.<ref name=\"WaPoArrest19\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/world/wp/2018/10/19/saudi-government-acknowledges-journalist-jamal-khashaoggi-died-while-in-that-countrys-consulate-in-istanbul/ |title=Saudi Arabia fires 5 top officials, arrests 18 Saudis, saying Khashoggi was killed in fight at consulate |last=Sullivan |first=Kevin |date=19 October 2018 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=20 October 2018 |last2=Morris |first2=Loveday |language=en |last3=El-Ghobashy |first3=Tamer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020015713/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/world/wp/2018/10/19/saudi-government-acknowledges-journalist-jamal-khashaoggi-died-while-in-that-countrys-consulate-in-istanbul/ |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 20 October [[Saud al-Qahtani]] and [[Ahmad Asiri (general)|Ahmad Asiri]] were announced fired by Saudi Arabia for involvement in Khashoggi's killing according to the BBC.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Jamal Khashoggi case: Saudi Arabia says journalist killed in fight |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45923217 |work=BBC |date=20 October 2018 |access-date=23 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120201646/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45923217 |archive-date=20 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 October, an anonymous Saudi official said Khashoggi had been threatened with drugging and kidnapping by Maher Mutreb, had resisted and was restrained with a chokehold, which killed him.<ref name=\"Rashad\">{{cite news |agency=Reuters |last1=Rashad |first1=Marwa |title=Amid skepticism, Saudi official provides another version of... |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-official/amid-skepticism-saudi-official-provides-another-version-of-khashoggi-death-idUSKCN1MV04V |accessdate=21 October 2018 |date=21 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021091541/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-official/amid-skepticism-saudi-official-provides-another-version-of-khashoggi-death-idUSKCN1MV04V |archive-date=21 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 October, [[Reuters]] cited a Turkish intelligence source and a high-ranking Arab with access to intelligence and links to members of Saudi's royal court and reported that Saud al-Qahtani, the then-top aide for Mohammed bin Salman, had made a [[Skype]] call to the consulate while Khashoggi was held in the room. Qahtani reportedly insulted Khashoggi, who responded in kind. According to the Turkish source, Qahtani then asked the team to kill Khashoggi. Qahtani instructed: \"Bring me the head of the dog\". According to both sources, the audio of the Skype call is currently with Erdogan.<ref name=\"ReutersSkype\">{{cite news |title=How the man behind Khashoggi murder ran the killing via Skype |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-adviser-insight/how-the-man-behind-khashoggi-murder-ran-the-killing-via-skype-idUSKCN1MW2HA |accessdate=22 October 2018 |agency=Reuters |date=22 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115040933/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-adviser-insight/how-the-man-behind-khashoggi-murder-ran-the-killing-via-skype-idUSKCN1MW2HA |archive-date=15 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Nazif Karaman of the ''[[Daily Sabah]]'', the audio recording from inside the consulate revealed that Khashoggi's last words were: \"I'm suffocating... take this bag off my head, I'm claustrophobic.\"<ref name=\"DailySabah_Khashoggi_lastwords\">{{cite news | title= 'I'm suffocating': Khashoggi's last words, says Turkish reporter | publisher= [[Al Jazeera English]] | url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/suffocating-khashoggi-words-turkish-reporter-181111085534099.html |accessdate= 11 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111185950/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/suffocating-khashoggi-words-turkish-reporter-181111085534099.html  |archivedate= 11 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 December, the details of the transcript of the audio were described to [[CNN]] by an anonymous source.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/12/09/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-last-words-intl/index.html |title='I can't breathe.' Jamal Khashoggi's last words disclosed in transcript, source says |first=Nick |last=Robertson |date=9 December 2018 |work=[[CNN]] |access-date=12 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212045056/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/12/09/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-last-words-intl/index.html |archive-date=12 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 November, a ''H\u00fcrriyet'' columnist reported that Turkey has more evidence, including a second audio recording from the consulate, where the Saudi team reviews the plans on how to execute Khashoggi. He also reported that: \"Turkish officials also did not confirm [Saudi prosecutor's claim] that Khashoggi was killed after they gave him a fatal dose of drug. They say that he was strangulated with a rope or something like a plastic bag.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-has-second-audio-recording-on-khashoggi-killing-columnist-138915 |title=Turkey has second audio recording on Khashoggi killing: Columnist \u2013 Turkey News |publisher=Hurriyetdailynews.com |date=16 November 2018 |accessdate=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121230813/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-has-second-audio-recording-on-khashoggi-killing-columnist-138915 |archive-date=21 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Front of the Consulate General of Saudi Arabia in Istanbul.jpg|Police cordon, in front of the Saudi consulate in Istanbul, after Khashoggi's disappearance.|thumb|right]]\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Meets With King Salman (45309197352).jpg|thumb|right|U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] meets with King Salman on 16 October 2018.]]\nHatice Cengiz begged the US government to take action in helping to find her fianc\u00e9. In her ''Washington Post'' op-ed on 9 October, Cengiz wrote, \"At this time, I implore President [[Donald Trump|Trump]] and [[Melania Trump|first lady Melania Trump]] to help shed light on Jamal's disappearance. I also urge Saudi Arabia, especially King Salman and Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman, to show the same level of sensitivity and release CCTV footage from the consulate.\"<ref name=\"WaPoCengiz9-10-2018\"/>\n\n''[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]]'' reported on 11 October that Turkish officials were investigating whether Khashoggi's [[Apple Watch]] would reveal clues as to what happened to him inside the Saudi consulate, examining whether data from the smartwatch could have been transmitted to the [[Cloud computing|cloud]], or his personal phone, which was with Cengiz.<ref name=\"shockingevide\">{{cite news | last=Wilkinson | first=Bard | last2=Robertson | first2=Nic | last3=Smith-Spark | first3=Laura | title=Turkey has 'shocking' evidence of Saudi journalist's murder | website=CNN | date=12 October 2018 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/12/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-turkey-recordings-intl/index.html | access-date=12 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012074432/https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/12/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-turkey-recordings-intl/index.html | archive-date=12 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of 14 October, President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Erdo\u011fan]] and King Salman announced that a deal had been made for a \"jointing working group\" to examine the case.<ref name=\"wintour\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/15/turkey-jamal-khashoggi-granted-permission-search-saudi-arabia-consulate-istanbul|title=Donald Trump says 'rogue killers' may have murdered Khashoggi|first1=Patrick|last1=Wintour|first2=Martin|last2=Chulov|date=15 October 2018|website=The Guardian|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015113944/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/15/turkey-jamal-khashoggi-granted-permission-search-saudi-arabia-consulate-istanbul|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 15 October the Turkish Foreign Ministry announced that an \"inspection\" of the consulate, by both Turkish and Saudi officials, would take place that afternoon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/jamal-khashoggi-team-enters-saudi-consulate-ahead-of-joint-search-11526611|title=Jamal Khashoggi: Joint search team enters Saudi consulate|publisher=|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015231627/https://news.sky.com/story/jamal-khashoggi-team-enters-saudi-consulate-ahead-of-joint-search-11526611|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/jamal-khashoggi-latest-saudi-arabia-turkey-search-istanbul-death-missing-a8584361.html|title=Turkish authorities to search Saudi consulate two weeks after journalist vanished|publisher=news.sky.com|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015170040/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/jamal-khashoggi-latest-saudi-arabia-turkey-search-istanbul-death-missing-a8584361.html|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> According to an anonymous source from the Attorney General's office, Turkish officials found evidence of \"tampering\" during the inspection, and evidence that supports the belief Khashoggi was killed.<ref name=\"SearchEvidence\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/turkish-prosecutors-find-evidence-jamal-khashoggi-killing-181015205254636.html|title=Turkish prosecutors 'find evidence of Jamal Khashoggi killing'|website=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=15 October 2018|accessdate=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016203320/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/turkish-prosecutors-find-evidence-jamal-khashoggi-killing-181015205254636.html|archive-date=16 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> President Erdo\u011fan said that \"investigation is looking into many things such as toxic materials and those materials being removed by painting them over\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident-erdogan/turkeys-erdogan-says-some-material-at-saudi-consulate-painted-over-idUSKCN1MQ1CT|title=Turkey's Erdogan says some material at Saudi consulate painted over|agency=Reuters|accessdate=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016224604/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-politics-dissident-erdogan/turkeys-erdogan-says-some-material-at-saudi-consulate-painted-over-idUSKCN1MQ1CT|archive-date=16 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to anonymous sources, Turkish police have expanded the search, as Khashoggi's body may have been disposed of in nearby [[Belgrad Forest]] or on farmland in [[Yalova Province]], as indicated by the movement of the Saudi vehicles,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/18/search-for-khashoggis-remains-extends-to-saudi-consul-generals-residence|title=Search for Khashoggi's remains focuses on consul general's house|first1=Bethan|last1=McKernan|first2=Julian|last2=Borger|date=18 October 2018|website=the Guardian|access-date=27 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228180559/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/18/search-for-khashoggis-remains-extends-to-saudi-consul-generals-residence|archive-date=28 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[DNA profiling|DNA tests]] of samples from the Saudi consulate and the consul's residence are being conducted;<ref name=\"BBCJK\">{{cite web |title=Jamal Khashoggi case: Turkish police 'search forest' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45909732 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=19 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019015214/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45909732 |archive-date=19 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Al Jazeera'' reported that according to anonymous sources, fingerprints of one of the alleged perpetrators, Salah Muhammad al-Tubaigy, were found in the consulate.<ref name=\"AJ\">{{cite web |title=Jamal Khashoggi case: All the latest updates |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/jamal-khashoggi-case-latest-updates-181010133542286.html |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=19 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018230957/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/jamal-khashoggi-case-latest-updates-181010133542286.html |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Confirmation of death===\n\nOn 20 October, the Saudi Foreign Ministry reported that a preliminary investigation showed that Khashoggi had died at the consulate while engaged in a fight, the first Saudi acknowledgement of Khashoggi's death.<ref name=\"WaPoArrest19\"/>\n\nOn 22 October, six US and Western officials<ref name=\"haaretz2018-10-23\">{{cite web | title=CIA director Gina Haspel travels to Turkey for Khashoggi probe, sources say | website=haaretz.com | date=23 October 2018 | url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/cia-director-gina-haspel-travels-to-turkey-for-khashoggi-probe-source-says-1.6588337 | access-date=24 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023234114/https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/cia-director-gina-haspel-travels-to-turkey-for-khashoggi-probe-source-says-1.6588337 | archive-date=23 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> stated they believed that the crown prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]], because of his role overseeing the Saudi security apparatus, was ultimately responsible for Khashoggi's disappearance, and the [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA), [[Gina Haspel]], departed for Turkey to work on the investigation<ref>{{cite web | agency=Reuters | title=CIA director Haspel travels to Turkey for Khashoggi case: source | date=22 October 2018 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-cia/cia-director-haspel-travels-to-turkey-for-khashoggi-case-source-idUSKCN1MW2WN | access-date=24 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024112921/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-cia/cia-director-haspel-travels-to-turkey-for-khashoggi-case-source-idUSKCN1MW2WN | archive-date=24 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> \"amid a growing international uproar over Saudi's explanation of the killing\".<ref name=\"WaP20181022\">{{cite web |title=CIA director flies to Turkey amid growing controversy over Jamal Khashoggi killing |website=The Washington Post |date=22 October 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-director-flies-to-turkey-amid-growing-controversy-over-jamal-khashoggi-killing/2018/10/22/47d406d9-9f36-49fc-a187-a9a495b70a62_story.html |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024073637/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-director-flies-to-turkey-amid-growing-controversy-over-jamal-khashoggi-killing/2018/10/22/47d406d9-9f36-49fc-a187-a9a495b70a62_story.html |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Governor of \u0130stanbul]]'s office said that Khashoggi's fianc\u00e9e, Hatice Cengiz, had been given 24-hour [[police protection]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamal Khashoggi: Erdogan vows to reveal all that happened 'in all its nakedness' |website=Sky News |date=21 October 2018 |url=https://news.sky.com/story/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-vows-to-bring-journalists-killers-to-justice-11531766 |accessdate=22 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022002900/https://news.sky.com/story/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-vows-to-bring-journalists-killers-to-justice-11531766 |archive-date=22 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlso on 22 October, [[CNN]] aired [[CCTV]] law enforcement footage from the Turkish authorities, showing the Saudi agent Mustafa al-Madani, a member of the 15-man team, leaving the consulate by the back door.<ref name=\"body double\"/> He was dressed up in Khashoggi's clothes, except for the shoes. Madani had also put on a fake beard that resembled Khashoggi's facial hair, his glasses and his Apple Watch.<ref name=\"Tuysuz\" /><ref name=Rashad /><ref name=\"TheGMcKernan\" /> Madani, who was of similar age, height, and build to Khashoggi, left the consulate from its back door.<ref name=\"body double\"/> He was later seen at Istanbul's [[Blue Mosque (Istanbul)|Blue Mosque]], where he went to a public bathroom and changed back to his own clothes and discarded Khashoggi's clothes.<ref name=\"body double\"/> Later he was seen dining with another Saudi agent, and the footage shows him smiling and laughing.<ref name=\"ClarissaWard\" /> An anonymous Turkish official believes that Madani was brought to Istanbul to act as a [[body double]] and that \"You don't need a body double for a [[Extraordinary rendition|rendition]] or an interrogation. Our assessment has not changed since October 6. This was a [[premeditated]] murder, and the body was moved out of the consulate.\"<ref name=\"body double\">{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/22/middleeast/saudi-operative-jamal-khashoggi-clothes/index.html |title=Mustafa al-Madani identified as Saudi 'body double' in Khashoggi's clothes, Turkish source says |work=CNN |date=23 October 2018 |accessdate=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025145625/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/22/middleeast/saudi-operative-jamal-khashoggi-clothes/index.html |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The use of the body double might have been an attempt to lend credence to the Saudi government's first version of events: that Khashoggi walked out through the back not long after he arrived. But \"it was a flawed body double, so it never became an official part of the Saudi government's narrative\", a Turkish diplomat told ''The Washington Post''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/saudi-consulate-employees-talking-to-turkish-prosecutors-in-khashoggi-inquiry/2018/10/22/ba5980da-d3d2-11e8-a4db-184311d27129_story.html |title=Video appears to show Saudi body double in Jamal Khashoggi's clothes |work=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025032054/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/saudi-consulate-employees-talking-to-turkish-prosecutors-in-khashoggi-inquiry/2018/10/22/ba5980da-d3d2-11e8-a4db-184311d27129_story.html |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe body double footage bolstered Turkish claims that the Saudis always intended either to kill Khashoggi or move him back to Saudi Arabia. [[\u00d6mer \u00c7elik]], a spokesman for Turkey's ruling [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AKP]], stated: \"We are facing a situation that has been monstrously planned and later tried to be covered up. It is a complicated murder.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=The Khashoggi Body Double \u2013 and Mounting Evidence of a Premeditated Murder |website=The New Yorker |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-khashoggi-body-doubleand-mounting-evidence-of-a-premeditated-murder |date=22 October 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025031303/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-khashoggi-body-doubleand-mounting-evidence-of-a-premeditated-murder |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia has vowed it will conduct a thorough criminal investigation and deliver justice for Khashoggi, Turkish investigators have been faced with several delays from their Saudi counterparts. On 22 October, BBC reported that Turkish police had found a car with diplomatic number plates, abandoned in an underground car park in Istanbul. The car belonged to the Saudi consulate and permission was sought from the Saudi diplomats to search the car.<ref name=\"BBC_murder_fox\"/> Turkish media published a video from 3 October (day after the disappearance) that apparently showed the staff of the consulate burning documents.<ref name=BBC_murder_fox/>\n\n===Search of Saudi consul's residence===\nOn Sunday 7 October, the Turkish Ministry of Foreign Affairs summoned Saudi Arabian Ambassador [[Waleed A. M. Elkhereiji]] to demand for the second time permission to search the consulate building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/diplomacy/2018/10/08/turkey-demands-permission-to-search-saudi-consulate-after-journalist-khashoggis-disappearance|title=Turkey demands permission to search Saudi consulate after journalist Khashoggi's disappearance|work=[[Daily Sabah]]|quote=The Ministry of Foreign Affairs on Sunday summoned Saudi Arabian Ambassador [[Waleed A. M. Elkhereiji]] for the second time after journalist Jamal Khashoggi's disappearance and demanded permission to search the consulate building in Istanbul, October 8.|access-date=2 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119051646/https://www.dailysabah.com/diplomacy/2018/10/08/turkey-demands-permission-to-search-saudi-consulate-after-journalist-khashoggis-disappearance|archive-date=19 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Saudi officials continued to refuse that Turkish police could search the well in the Saudi consul's garden,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/todays-headlines/-saudis-did-not-let-turkey-search-well-at-consulate-/1291897 |title=Saudis did not let Turkey search well at consulate |work=[[Anadolu Agency]] |date=24 October 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024121708/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/todays-headlines/-saudis-did-not-let-turkey-search-well-at-consulate-/1291897 |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/saudi-khashoggi-consulate/saudi-officials-refuse-turkish-police-search-at-well-in-istanbul-consulate-anadolu-idUSA4N1UT02E |title=Saudi officials refuse Turkish police search at well in Istanbul consulate \u2013 Anadolu |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=24 October 2018 }}</ref> but granted permission on 24 October (22 days after the assassination).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ntv.com.tr/turkiye/konsolosluk-bahcesindeki-kuyuda-arama-yapilacak,9UXbI7aPaEWUk1k-7i9QPg |title=Konsolosluk bah\u00e7esindeki kuyuda arama yap\u0131lacak |language=Turkish |work=[[NTV (Turkey)]] |date=24 October 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-consulate/turkish-police-receive-permission-to-search-well-at-saudi-consulate-ntv-idUSKCN1MY1HF |title=Turkish police receive permission to search well at Saudi consulate: NTV |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=24 October 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024142119/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-consulate/turkish-police-receive-permission-to-search-well-at-saudi-consulate-ntv-idUSKCN1MY1HF |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"WaPoPreMeditated\">{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia again changes its story on Khashoggi killing |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/turkish-probe-of-khashoggi-killing-turns-to-garden-well/2018/10/25/a3aabb88-d837-11e8-8384-bcc5492fef49_story.html |accessdate=26 October 2018 |work=The Washington Post |date=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025115811/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/turkish-probe-of-khashoggi-killing-turns-to-garden-well/2018/10/25/a3aabb88-d837-11e8-8384-bcc5492fef49_story.html |archive-date=25 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Turkish newspaper ''[[H\u00fcrriyet]]'' reported on 26 October that police had found no DNA traces of Khashoggi in water samples taken from the well.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/incelemeden-once-araclara-oto-kuafor-40998828 |title=\u0130ncelemeden \u00f6nce ara\u00e7lara oto kuaf\u00f6r |language=Turkish |work=H\u00fcrriyet |date=26 October 2018 |quote=Yap\u0131lan kriminal incelemede, suda herhangi bir DNA \u00f6rne\u011fine rastlanmad\u0131 |access-date=26 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026182249/http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/incelemeden-once-araclara-oto-kuafor-40998828 |archive-date=26 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"SBS_NoDNA\">{{cite news |title=No Khashoggi DNA in Saudi consulate well |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/no-khashoggi-dna-in-saudi-consulate-well |accessdate=26 October 2018 |publisher=SBS News |date=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026143440/https://www.sbs.com.au/news/no-khashoggi-dna-in-saudi-consulate-well |archive-date=26 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCalling for an international investigation, at the [[Headquarters of the United Nations]] in [[New York City]] on 25 October, [[Agnes Callamard]], UN Special Rapporteur on Extrajudicial, Summary or Arbitrary Executions, explained the Saudi officials implicated in the death of Khashoggi \"are high enough to represent the state\".<ref name=\"NZZOct31\">{{cite web | title=Fall Khashoggi: Menschenrechtsexpertin fordert Uno-Untersuchung | website=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung | date=26 October 2018 | url=https://www.nzz.ch/international/fall-khashoggi-menschenrechtsexpertin-fordert-uno-untersuchung-ld.1431312 | language=de | access-date=31 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031174120/https://www.nzz.ch/international/fall-khashoggi-menschenrechtsexpertin-fordert-uno-untersuchung-ld.1431312 | archive-date=31 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> \"Even Saudi Arabia has admitted that the crime was premeditated ... From where I sit, this bears all the hallmarks of [[extrajudicial execution]]s. Until I am proven otherwise I must assume that this was the case. It is up to the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia to prove that it was not.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Khashoggi Killing Likely an Extrajudicial Execution \u2013 Press Conference (25 October 2018) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H5UGTUc06yU |website=Youtube |publisher=United Nations |date=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Saudi public prosecutors visit===\nSaudi public prosecutor Saud al-Mojeb arrived in Istanbul on 28 October, days after he contradicted weeks of official Saudi statements by saying that Khashoggi's murder was premeditated. His trip came amid Turkish suggestions of \"a lack of cooperation by the Saudi side\" and alleged \"attempts to spoil evidence\".<ref name=\"AlJ31Oct\">{{cite web | last=Koseoglu | first=Sinem | title=Turkey to present probe findings to Saudi, request new search | website=Al Jazeera | date=28 October 2018 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/turkey-present-saudi-probe-findings-request-consulate-search-181028145716739.html | access-date=31 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031133038/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/turkey-present-saudi-probe-findings-request-consulate-search-181028145716739.html | archive-date=31 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> Mojeb held talks on 29 October with Istanbul's chief prosecutor Irfan Fidan at the [[Istanbul \u00c7a\u011flayan Justice Palace|\u00c7a\u011flayan courthouse]]. During the meeting Saudi officials asked for the complete investigation folder, including evidence, statements and footage. The Turkish investigators presented the probe findings in a 150-page dossier, but refused to share all the evidence they have compiled in the murder. And they repeated the request for the extradition of the 18 suspects to Turkey, although the Saudi foreign minister [[Adel al-Jubeir]] insisted on 27 October that the men would be tried on Saudi soil. They also repeated requests for confirmation on the whereabouts of Khashoggi's body, the identity of the \"local cooperator\" that the Saudis claim disposed of the body, and an update on the progress of a Saudi investigation of the 15 Saudi operatives who visited the Istanbul consulate at the time of the murder. Due the lack of trust between the two countries the meeting lasted only 75 minutes. Turkish foreign minister [[Mevlut Cavusoglu]] stated that \"The whole truth must be revealed\" and the visit will help in that direction. He also asked Saudis to complete the investigation sooner.<ref name=\"Reuters_29Prosecutor\">{{cite news |title=Turkey demands truth over Khashoggi killing as Saudi prosecutor visits |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey-prosecutor/turkey-demands-truth-over-khashoggi-killing-as-saudi-prosecutor-visits-idUSKCN1N30K2 |accessdate=29 October 2018 |agency=Reuters |date=29 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029141615/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey-prosecutor/turkey-demands-truth-over-khashoggi-killing-as-saudi-prosecutor-visits-idUSKCN1N30K2 |archive-date=29 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"TheG_29Oct\">{{cite web | last=Wintour | first=Patrick | last2=McKernan | first2=Bethan | title=Turkey refuses to share all Khashoggi evidence with Saudis | website=the Guardian | date=29 October 2018 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/29/saudi-prosecutor-saud-al-mojeb-arrives-in-turkey-to-assist-with-jamal-khashoggi-inquiry | access-date=27 January 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204163743/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/29/saudi-prosecutor-saud-al-mojeb-arrives-in-turkey-to-assist-with-jamal-khashoggi-inquiry | archive-date=4 February 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMojeb held a second round of talks with Fidan on 30 October, before inspecting the Saudi consulate in the [[Levent]] neighbourhood, where he left after spending a little over an hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/saudi-prosecutor-visits-istanbul-court-house-in-khashoggi-probe-138396|title=Saudi prosecutor joins probe at Saudi consulate in Istanbul for Khashoggi investigation \u2013 Turkey News|website=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|accessdate=31 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030115127/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/saudi-prosecutor-visits-istanbul-court-house-in-khashoggi-probe-138396|archive-date=30 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"WaPo31Oct\" /> According to a source at the prosecutor's office, Fidan asked Mojeb to conduct another joint search at the consul-general's residence, because when Turkish investigators first entered the building in mid-October they were not allowed to search three locked rooms and were also not allowed to search a {{convert|20|m|adj=on}}-deep well. The Saudis did not let firefighters descend into the well, and the search ended with police only able to obtain some water samples.<ref name=\"AlJ31Oct\" />\n\nPresident Erdo\u011fan said the investigation needs to be completed swiftly: \"This needs to be solved now; there is no point in excuses\", and wants an extradition request for 18 suspects detained in KSA to be put on trial in Istanbul. High Commissioner for Human Rights, [[Michelle Bachelet]], also urged Saudi Arabia to reveal the location of Khashoggi's body: \"I urge the Saudi authorities to reveal the whereabouts of his body without further delay or prevarication.\"<ref name=\"WaPo31Oct\">{{cite web |title=Khashoggi's fiancee calls on Trump to prevent 'cover-up' |website=The Washington Post |date=31 October 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/khashoggis-fiancee-calls-on-trump-to-prevent-cover-up/2018/10/30/96cce4e0-dcb0-11e8-8bac-bfe01fcdc3a6_story.html |access-date=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031050424/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/khashoggis-fiancee-calls-on-trump-to-prevent-cover-up/2018/10/30/96cce4e0-dcb0-11e8-8bac-bfe01fcdc3a6_story.html |archive-date=31 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mojeb was accused by Erdo\u011fan of refusal to cooperate during his visit to discuss the investigation. Erdo\u011fan stated that, \"The prosecutor came to Turkey to make excuses, make things difficult.\" Mojeb had not shared any information to the Turkish investigators but wanted to take Khashoggi's mobile phone that was left outside the consulate with his fianc\u00e9e when he entered.<ref name=\"Reuters_Tapes_given\"/>\n\n===Disposing of the body===\nOn 31 October a senior Turkish official told ''The Washington Post'' that Turkish authorities were investigating the theory that Khashoggi's body was destroyed in acid on the grounds of the consulate or at the nearby residence of the Saudi consul general. The \"biological evidence\" discovered in the consulate garden supported the theory.<ref name=\"WaPo31Octacid\">{{cite web |title=Prosecutor says Khashoggi was strangled and dismembered, but fate of body still a mystery |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/saudi-arabia-not-fully-cooperating-with-khashoggi-investigation-turkish-official-says/2018/10/31/804bfc2a-dc78-11e8-8bac-bfe01fcdc3a6_story.html |website=The Washington Post |date=31 October 2018 |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103092637/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/saudi-arabia-not-fully-cooperating-with-khashoggi-investigation-turkish-official-says/2018/10/31/804bfc2a-dc78-11e8-8bac-bfe01fcdc3a6_story.html |archive-date=3 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Echoing the claim, Yasin Aktay, an adviser to Erdo\u011fan in his ruling [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]] and a friend of Khashoggi, hinted in an article in the Turkish newspaper ''H\u00fcrriyet'', published on 2 November, that the body was destroyed by dismembering and dissolving in acid: \"We now see that it wasn't just cut up, they got rid of the body by dissolving it\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/11/02/world/europe/02reuters-saudi-khashoggi-turkey.html|title=Turkey's Erdogan-Khashoggi Killing Ordered at Saudi 'Highest Levels'|publisher=|access-date=3 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103105151/https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/11/02/world/europe/02reuters-saudi-khashoggi-turkey.html|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trtworld.com/turkey/khashoggi-s-body-was-dissolved-after-murder-erdogan-advisor-21325|title=Khashoggi's body was 'dissolved' after murder \u2013 Erdogan advisor|website=Khashoggi's body was 'dissolved' after murder \u2013 Erdogan advisor|access-date=3 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103170538/https://www.trtworld.com/turkey/khashoggi-s-body-was-dissolved-after-murder-erdogan-advisor-21325|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey/erdogan-adviser-said-khashoggis-body-was-dismembered-and-dissolved-newspaper-idUSKCN1N7179|title=Erdogan adviser said Khashoggi's body was dismembered and...|agency=Reuters|access-date=3 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103123749/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey/erdogan-adviser-said-khashoggis-body-was-dismembered-and-dissolved-newspaper-idUSKCN1N7179|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March 2019, Al Jazeera Arabic released a documentary on the investigation of Khashoggi's murder and the subsequent coverup.  In its coverage, the network states that the body was likely disposed of by being burnt in an oven at the Saudi consulate general's residence.<ref name=\"burned-oven\">{{cite news |title=Jamal Khashoggi's body likely burned in large oven at Saudi home |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/jamal-khashoggi-body-burned-large-oven-saudi-home-190304011823218.html |website=Al Jazeera News |date=4 March 2019 |access-date=5 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305125107/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/jamal-khashoggi-body-burned-large-oven-saudi-home-190304011823218.html |archive-date=5 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  An interview with the oven's builder revealed that it was designed to be \"deep\", and capable of withstanding temperatures over {{convert|1000|C|F}}. The burning took three days and happened in parts.  Afterwards, a large quantity of [[barbecue]] meat was prepared to cover the evidence of cremation.\n\nIn a ''Washington Post'' op-ed Erdo\u011fan described the murder as \"inexplicable\" and as a \"clear violation and a blatant abuse of the [[Vienna Convention on Consular Relations]]\", arguing that not punishing the perpetrators \"could set a very dangerous precedent.\" He criticised Saudi inaction against the consul general [[Mohammad al-Otaibi]], who had misled the media and had fled the country shortly afterwards. He warned that no-one should dare commit \"such acts on the soil of a [[NATO]] ally again\" and wrote: \"As responsible members of the international community, we must reveal the identities of the puppet masters behind Khashoggi's killing and discover those in whom Saudi officials{{snd}} still trying to cover up the murder{{snd}} have placed their trust... We know that the order to kill Khashoggi came from the highest levels of the Saudi government.\" He urged the international community to uncover the whole truth.<ref name=\"Erdogan\">{{cite news |last1=Recep Tayyip Erdogan |title=Saudi Arabia still has many questions to answer about Jamal Khashoggi's killing |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/11/02/recep-tayyip-erdogan-saudi-arabia-still-has-many-questions-to-answer-about-jamal-khashoggis-killing |website=The Washington Post |date=2 November 2018 |access-date=15 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115152537/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/11/02/recep-tayyip-erdogan-saudi-arabia-still-has-many-questions-to-answer-about-jamal-khashoggis-killing/ |archive-date=15 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Tampering with evidence===\nOn 5 November, ''Daily Sabah'' quoted a Turkish official that an 11-member \"investigative team\" had been sent by Saudi Arabia to Istanbul on 11 October.<ref name=\"MEE_Compensation\">{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia to pay compensation to Khashoggi family, fiancee: Turkish official |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-arabia-pay-compensation-khashoggi-family-and-fiancee-says-turkish-official-2016567611 |accessdate=10 November 2018 |website=Middle East Eye |date=6 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111043945/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-arabia-pay-compensation-khashoggi-family-and-fiancee-says-turkish-official-2016567611 |archive-date=11 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Chemist Ahmad Abdulaziz Aljanobi and toxicology expert Khaled Yahya al-Zahrani were sent as a part of the investigative team to erase the evidence and cover up.<ref name=\"MEE_Saudi_CoverTeam\"/> This was mentioned by the Turkish official as a sign of awareness about the crime among the top Saudi officials.<ref name=\"Reuters_Tapes_given\"/> The Saudi team had visited the consulate everyday between 11 and 17 October.<ref name=\"MEE_Saudi_CoverTeam\"/> On 15 October, Turkish police were allowed for the first time to enter the consulate.<ref name=\"MEE_Saudi_CoverTeam\">{{cite news |title=audi team sent to Istanbul to 'cover up' Khashoggi murder: Turkish official |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/two-saudis-sent-istanbul-cover-khashoggi-murder-turkish-official-1558214130 |accessdate=10 November 2018 |website=Middle East Eye |date=5 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111044012/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/two-saudis-sent-istanbul-cover-khashoggi-murder-turkish-official-1558214130 |archive-date=11 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Audio tapes===\nSpeaking before his departure for Paris to attend the [[Armistice of 11 November 1918|World War I armistice]] centenary, Erdo\u011fan acknowledged the existence of audio recordings in a televised speech on 10 November to maintain the pressure from the international community on Saudi Arabia to reveal who ordered the murder of Khashoggi. He said: \"We gave the tapes. We gave them to Saudi Arabia, to the United States, Germans, French and British, all of them.\" It was the first time that he disclosed that the three European Union states had heard the recordings. [[Reuters]] reported that Turkey had multiple audio recordings of the Khashoggi incident.<ref name=\"Reuters_Tapes_given\" /> These recordings document Khashoggi's torture and death, as well as conversations from the days prior to the incident that Turkey had uncovered during its investigation. Based on these recordings, Turkey had concluded from an early stage that the killing was premeditated. [[Saud al-Qahtani]] was reported as having a major role throughout the recording.<ref name=\"Reuters_Tapes_given\">{{cite news |title=Turkey gave Khashoggi tapes to European nations, Erdogan says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey/turkey-gave-khashoggi-tapes-to-european-nations-erdogan-says-idUSKCN1NF0EQ |accessdate=10 November 2018 |agency=Reuters |date=10 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110171320/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-khashoggi-turkey/turkey-gave-khashoggi-tapes-to-european-nations-erdogan-says-idUSKCN1NF0EQ |archive-date=10 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><!-- <ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/tape-of-khashoggis-killing-has-been-given-to-us-saudi-europeans-erdogan-says/2018/11/10/bb21ab5e-e4e0-11e8-ab2c-b31dcd53ca6b_story.html</ref> -->\n\nWhile attending the [[World War I centennial]] commemorations in France, Erdo\u011fan discussed with President Donald Trump how to further respond to the killing. And a further closed-door meeting with Secretary-General [[Ant\u00f3nio Guterres]] of the [[United Nations]] took place.<ref>{{cite news |title=Erdo\u011fan, Trump meet over dinner in French capital |url=https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/erdogan-trump-meet-over-dinner-in-french-capital-3465965 |date=11 November 2018 |publisher=Yeni Safak |access-date=12 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112101403/https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/erdogan-trump-meet-over-dinner-in-french-capital-3465965 |archive-date=12 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> President Trump and French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] agreed that more details were needed from KSA on Khashoggi's murder. Accordingly, they also agreed that the case should not cause further destabilization in the Middle East; and fallout from the Khashoggi affair could create a way forward to find a resolution to the ongoing [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|War in Yemen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Will Saudi Arabia ever reveal who ordered the killing of Jamal Khashoggi? Luciano Zaccara (Assistant Professor of Gulf Politics at the Gulf Studies Center at Qatar University), Matthew Bryza (Former White House official, now a non-Resident Senior Fellow at the Atlantic Council), Selva Tor (Professor of Political Science and International Relations at Ko\u00e7 University)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uXbJ2RRw2Yk|website=Al Jazeera English|date=11 November 2018|access-date=12 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112183448/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uXbJ2RRw2Yk|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCanadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] gave public confirmation that Turkey had shared audio of the killing with world governments.<ref name=\"LeMon12Nov\">{{cite web |last1=Madjid Zerrouky |title=Le premier ministre canadien confirme l'existence d'enregistrements de l'assassinat du journaliste |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/proche-orient/article/2018/11/12/affaire-khashoggi-le-premier-ministre-canadien-confirme-l-existence-d-enregistrements_5382548_3218.html |quote=S'il y a un probl\u00e8me de communication entre les diff\u00e9rentes institutions au sein du gouvernement fran\u00e7ais, il appartient aux autorit\u00e9s fran\u00e7aises et non \u00e0 la Turquie de r\u00e9gler ce probl\u00e8me. |website=Le Monde |date=12 November 2018 |access-date=12 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112221849/https://www.lemonde.fr/proche-orient/article/2018/11/12/affaire-khashoggi-le-premier-ministre-canadien-confirme-l-existence-d-enregistrements_5382548_3218.html |archive-date=12 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Guard12Nov\">{{cite web |last1=Patrick |first1=Patrick |title=Trudeau says Canada received Turkish tape of Khashoggi murder |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/nov/12/trudeau-says-canada-has-received-turkish-tape-of-khashoggi |website=The Guardian |date=12 November 2018 |access-date=12 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112211149/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/nov/12/trudeau-says-canada-has-received-turkish-tape-of-khashoggi |archive-date=12 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The German government also confirmed it had received information from the Turkish authorities, but declined to elaborate.<ref>{{cite web |title=Geheimdienst-Kooperation Frankreich widerspricht T\u00fcrkei \u2013 offenbar keine Aufnahmen zu Khashoggi-Mord erhalten |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/frankreich-hat-die-aufnahmen-von-jamal-khashoggi-nicht-von-der-tuerkei-erhalten-a-1238012.html |website=Der Spiegel |publisher=dop/Reuters/AP/AFP |date=12 November 2018 |access-date=12 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112153727/http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/frankreich-hat-die-aufnahmen-von-jamal-khashoggi-nicht-von-der-tuerkei-erhalten-a-1238012.html |archive-date=12 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The British Foreign Secretary [[Jeremy Hunt]] paid an official visit to KSA and called for its cooperation with a \"credible\" investigation into Khashoggi's killing.<ref name=\"thetimes1\">{{cite news |last=Spencer |first=Richard |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jeremy-hunt-presses-saudi-arabia-over-yemen-and-khashoggi-t9tq9sjlz |title='Tell your boss' recording could link Saudi prince to Khashoggi's death |newspaper=The Times |date=13 November 2018 |accessdate=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121225415/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jeremy-hunt-presses-saudi-arabia-over-yemen-and-khashoggi-t9tq9sjlz |archive-date=21 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOne of the assassins was heard saying \"I know how to cut\" on the audio tape.<ref name=\"guard14dec\">{{cite news|agency=Reuters|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/dec/14/khashoggi-killer-heard-saying-i-know-how-to-cut-on-audio-erdogan|title=Khashoggi killer heard saying 'I know how to cut' on audio \u2013 Erdo\u011fan|newspaper=The Guardian|date=14 December 2018|accessdate=15 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214234246/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/dec/14/khashoggi-killer-heard-saying-i-know-how-to-cut-on-audio-erdogan|archive-date=14 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Charges===\n\nOn 15 November 2018, the Saudi Prosecutor's Office stated that 11 Saudi nationals had been indicted and charged with murdering Khashoggi and that five of the individuals who were indicted would face the [[Capital punishment in Saudi Arabia|death penalty]], since it had been determined they were directly involved in \"ordering and executing the crime\".  Prosecutors alleged that shortly after Khashoggi entered the Saudi Consulate in Istanbul he was bound and then injected with an overdose of a [[sedative]] that resulted in his death. The prosecutors also alleged that his body had been dismembered and removed from the consulate by five of those charged in the killing and given to a local collaborator for disposal. Saudi officials continued to deny that the Saudi Royal Family was involved in, ordered, or sanctioned the killing.<ref name=\"fivedeathsentence\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/15/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-prosecutor-death-penalty-intl/index.html|title=Saudis seek death penalty, details Khashoggi's death|first1=Sarah|last1=El Sirgany|first2=Nada|last2=Altaher|first3=Bianca|last3=Britton|publisher=CNN|access-date=15 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115215513/https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/15/middleeast/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-prosecutor-death-penalty-intl/index.html|archive-date=15 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"fiveexecute\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/11/15/668162272/khashoggi-case-update-saudi-prosecutor-says-5-suspects-should-be-executed|title=Khashoggi Case Update: Saudi Prosecutor Says 5 Suspects Should Be Executed|publisher=|access-date=15 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115164655/https://www.npr.org/2018/11/15/668162272/khashoggi-case-update-saudi-prosecutor-says-5-suspects-should-be-executed|archive-date=15 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 November 2018, several news organizations including ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''The Washington Post'' reported that CIA was unequivocal in assessing with \"high confidence\" that the crown prince Mohammad bin Salman ordered Khashoggi's assassination. The agency examined multiple sources of intelligence, including an [[intercepted]] phone call that the crown prince's brother [[Khalid bin Salman]]{{snd}} the then Saudi ambassador to the United States{{snd}} had with Khashoggi. A conclusion that contradicted previous Saudi government claims that the crown prince was not involved. A CIA spokesman and both the White House and the [[US State Department]] declined to comment. The Saudis issued a denial.<ref name=\"cia\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=CIA concludes Saudi prince ordered Khashoggi's killing (Interview with Fawaz A. Gerges, chair of Contemporary Middle East Studies at the LSE) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9zGx-AjbXmU |website=Youtube |publisher=CBC News |date=17 November 2018 |access-date=19 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118083243/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9zGx-AjbXmU |archive-date=18 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 November 2018, Trump issued the statement \"On Standing with Saudi Arabia\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Donald J. Trump|title=On Standing with Saudi Arabia|publisher=whitehouse.gov|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-president-donald-j-trump-standing-saudi-arabia|date=20 November 2018|access-date=24 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124130615/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-president-donald-j-trump-standing-saudi-arabia/|archive-date=24 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and without citing further evidence he denied the CIA's conclusion: \"Our intelligence agencies continue to assess all information, but it could very well be that the Crown Prince had knowledge of this tragic event{{snd}} maybe he did and maybe he didn't!\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=[[Michael Hirsh (journalist)|Michael Hirsh]] |title=What Happened to Trump's Khashoggi Report? |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/11/20/what-happened-to-the-khashoggi-report-trump-talked-about/ |magazine=Foreign Policy |date=20 November 2018 |quote=Indeed, in his extraordinary statement on Tuesday, Trump laid out one of the most naked and amoral declarations of American realpolitik \u2013 the idea that the United States is interested only in material and geopolitical benefit, and no longer cares to promulgate its values \u2013 of any president in U.S. history. |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124220251/https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/11/20/what-happened-to-the-khashoggi-report-trump-talked-about/ |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=nov20 /><ref>{{cite web |title=With Khashoggi decision, Trump places strategic interests above human rights |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZUw9i1qEPgg |website=Youtube |publisher=PBS NewsHour |date=20 November 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122060754/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZUw9i1qEPgg |archive-date=22 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a series of interviews President Trump said the crown prince denies his involvement \"vehemently\" and the CIA only has \"feelings\" and there is \"no smoking gun\" in the death.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trump contradicts CIA assessment on Khashoggi killing |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-contradicts-cia-assessment-on-khashoggi-killing |publisher=FoxNews.com |date=21 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124134126/https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-contradicts-cia-assessment-on-khashoggi-killing |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The next day ''H\u00fcrriyet'' columnist [[Abdulkadir Selvi]] wrote that the \"''CIA holds 'smoking gun phone call' of Saudi Crown Prince on Khashoggi murder''\"<ref>{{cite news |title=CIA holds 'smoking gun phone call' of Saudi Crown Prince on Khashoggi murder |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/cia-holds-smoking-gun-phone-call-of-saudi-crown-prince-on-khashoggi-murder-columnist-139079 |newspaper=H\u00fcrriyet |date=22 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124220121/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/cia-holds-smoking-gun-phone-call-of-saudi-crown-prince-on-khashoggi-murder-columnist-139079 |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and that the [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]] [[Gina Haspel]] has possession of an intercepted phone call in which crown prince [[Mohammad bin Salman|Mohammad]] gives an order to his brother [[Khalid bin Salman|Khalid]] \"''to silence Jamal Khashoggi as soon as possible''\". \"The subsequent murder is the ultimate confirmation of this instruction.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=CIA Has Recording of Saudi Crown Prince Ordering Khashoggi Silenced |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/report-cia-has-tape-of-saudi-crown-prince-giving-instructions-to-silence-khasoggi-1.6677571 |agency=Reuters |work=Haaretz |date=22 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124140644/https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/report-cia-has-tape-of-saudi-crown-prince-giving-instructions-to-silence-khasoggi-1.6677571 |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey says the CIA has a 'smoking gun' tape nailing the Saudi crown prince in the Khashoggi case |url=https://www.sfgate.com/technology/businessinsider/article/Turkey-says-the-CIA-has-a-smoking-gun-tape-13414259.php |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=22 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124162418/https://www.sfgate.com/technology/businessinsider/article/Turkey-says-the-CIA-has-a-smoking-gun-tape-13414259.php |archive-date=24 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Turkish media: CIA has recording of MBS ordering Khashoggi murder |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xkZYVjsRRig |website=Youtube |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=22 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123014639/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xkZYVjsRRig |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCiting the leaked CIA assessment, ''The Wall Street Journal'' reported that Mohammed bin Salman sent at least 11 text messages in the hours before and after the assassination on 2 October to his closest adviser [[Saud al-Qahtani]] who supervised the 15-man kill-team that was sent to Istanbul, and that Qahtani was in direct communication with the team's leader in Istanbul. The assessment also noted that Mohammed bin Salman had told his agents back in August 2017 that Khashoggi could be lured to a third country, if he could not be persuaded to return to the KSA.<ref>{{cite web |title=CIA Intercepts Underpin Assessment Saudi Crown Prince Targeted Khashoggi |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/cia-intercepts-underpin-assessment-saudi-crown-prince-targeted-khashoggi-1543640460 |website=The Wall Street Journal |date=1 December 2018 |access-date=2 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202053424/https://www.wsj.com/articles/cia-intercepts-underpin-assessment-saudi-crown-prince-targeted-khashoggi-1543640460 |archive-date=2 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, the message-exchange element of the report was contested by Saudi Arabia based on a confidential Saudi-commissioned investigation conducted by the private security firm [[Kroll Inc.|Kroll]]. The investigation, which focused on a forensic examination of a cellphone belonging to Saud al-Qahtani, found that none of the messages exchanged on the day of the murder between Prince Mohammed and Mr. Qahtani concerned the murder.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-commissioned-report-contests-u-s-finding-about-journalists-killing-11549498605 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |title=Saudis: Saudi-Commissioned Report Contests U.S. Finding About Khashoggi's Killing |date=7 February 2019 |access-date=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104164833/https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-commissioned-report-contests-u-s-finding-about-journalists-killing-11549498605 |archive-date=4 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman appeared in an interview with the CBS \"''[[60 Minutes]]''\" program that was aired on 29 September 2019, denying that he had ordered the killing of Jamal Khashoggi or that he had prior knowledge about it but said that he bears all responsibility for the killing of Jamal Khashoggi because the incident took place under his watch. He also said that \"once charges are proven against someone, regardless of their rank, it will be taken to court, no exception made.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mohammad-bin-salman-denies-ordering-khashoggi-murder-but-says-he-takes-responsibility-for-it-60-minutes-2019-09-29/|title=Mohammad bin Salman denies ordering Khashoggi murder, but says he takes responsibility for it|website=cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=30 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002062740/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mohammad-bin-salman-denies-ordering-khashoggi-murder-but-says-he-takes-responsibility-for-it-60-minutes-2019-09-29/|archive-date=2 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/29/middleeast/crown-prince-mohammed-bin-salman-interview/index.html|title=Mohammed bin Salman denies personal involvement in Khashoggi killing in '60 Minutes' interview but says it was carried out by Saudi officials|last=Maxouris|first=Christina|website=CNN|access-date=30 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001182811/https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/29/middleeast/crown-prince-mohammed-bin-salman-interview/index.html|archive-date=1 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March 2020, 20 Saudi nationals were reportedly indicted by Turkish prosecutors over the killing of Khashoggi.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/25/turkey-charges-20-saudis-over-jamal-khashoggi |title= Turkey charges 20 Saudis over Jamal Khashoggi murder. |}}</ref> According to the prosecutor's office in Istanbul, a royal court adviser Saud al-Qahtani, and Saudi's former deputy intelligence chief Ahmed al-Assiri were charged with inciting the murder; both had been investigated by Saudis in 2019 but acquitted or not charged.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/turkey-charges-20-saudis-over-khashoggi-murder/|title=Turkey charges 20 Saudis over Khashoggi murder|date=March 25, 2020|newspaper=Times of Israel}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.voanews.com/press-freedom/turkey-charges-20-khashoggi-killing |title= Turkey Charges 20 in Khashoggi Killing. |}}</ref> they were previously The suspects are believed to have fled Turkey, while Saudi Arabia has denied the Turkish claims for all the accused to be taken back to Turkey in order to answer for their crimes.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/turkish-prosecutors-file-indictment-khashoggi-killing-69785875 |title= Turkish prosecutors file indictment over Khashoggi killing. |}}</ref> According to Aljazeera, the charges were filed based on analysis of Khashoggi's accessories, witness testimonies, analysis of the suspects' phone records, including information on their whereabouts within and outside Turkey, as well as the consulate.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/istanbul-prosecutor-indicts-saudi-suspects-khashoggi-killing-200325083658411.html |title= Istanbul prosecutor indicts Saudi suspects for Khashoggi killing. |}}</ref> Even though arrest warrants have already been given out by the Turkish prosecutor for the accused, the office of the prosecutor however, did not disclose a specific date for the trial.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001365657/turkey-charges-20-saudis-over-khashoggi-murder |title= Turkey charges 20 Saudis over Khashoggi murder. |}}</ref>\n\n==Alleged perpetrators==\n[[File:Asiri and MbS.png|thumb|200px|[[Ahmad Asiri (general)|Ahmad Asiri]] (right)  and [[Mohammed bin Salman]] (left) in 2016]]  \nAl-Waqt news quoted informed sources as saying that [[Mohammad bin Salman]] had assigned [[Ahmad Asiri (general)|Ahmad Asiri]], the deputy head of the Saudi intelligence agency [[General Intelligence Presidency|Riasat Al-Mukhabarat Al-A'amah]]<ref name=\"saudigazette2013\">{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Gen. Asiri named deputy head of General Intelligence; Ibrahim Al-Omar is new SAGIA chairman|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/177105/Gen-Asiri-named-deputy-head-of-General-Intelligence-Ibrahim-Al-Omar-is-new-SAGIA-chairman|accessdate=13 October 2017|newspaper=Saudi Gazette|date=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113112753/http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/177105/Gen-Asiri-named-deputy-head-of-General-Intelligence-Ibrahim-Al-Omar-is-new-SAGIA-chairman|archive-date=13 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and the former spokesman for the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi-led coalition in Yemen]], with the mission to execute Khashoggi inside the Saudi consulate in Istanbul. Another military officer with a great deal of experience in dealing with dissidents was the second candidate for the mission.<ref name=\"perps\">{{cite web|url = http://en.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn=13970718000686|title = Arab Source: Khashoggi Murdered by Ex-Spokesman of Saudi-Led Coalition in War on Yemen|publisher = [[Fars News Agency]]|accessdate = 10 October 2018|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181011053539/http://en.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn=13970718000686|archive-date = 11 October 2018|url-status = live}}</ref> On the same day, Turkish media close to the President published images of what it described as a 15-member \"assassination squad\" allegedly sent to kill Khashoggi, and of a black van later traveling from the Saudi consulate to the consul's home.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/5420263/saudi-arabia-jamal-khashoggi-assassination-squad/|title=Photos Purport to Show Hit Squad Sent to Kill Saudi Writer|website=Time|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014055021/http://time.com/5420263/saudi-arabia-jamal-khashoggi-assassination-squad/|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 October the ''[[Daily Sabah]]'', a news outlet close to the Turkish president, published the names and pictures of the 15-member Saudi team apparently taken at passport control.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish police identify 5 suspects linked to Khashoggi murder: report |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/investigations/2018/10/10/15-member-saudi-intel-squad-sent-to-target-wps-khashoggi-identified |newspaper=Daily Sabah |accessdate=17 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017212018/https://www.dailysabah.com/investigations/2018/10/10/15-member-saudi-intel-squad-sent-to-target-wps-khashoggi-identified |archive-date=17 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Additional details about identities were also reported along with their aliases.<ref>{{cite news |title=15-member Saudi 'intel squad' sent to target WP's Khashoggi identified |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/investigations/2018/10/17/turkish-police-identify-5-suspects-linked-to-khashoggi-murder-report |newspaper=Daily Sabah |accessdate=10 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017092212/https://www.dailysabah.com/investigations/2018/10/17/turkish-police-identify-5-suspects-linked-to-khashoggi-murder-report |archive-date=17 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to one report, seven of the fifteen men suspected of killing Khashoggi are Mohammed bin Salman's personal bodyguards.<ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Hearst |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/khashoggi-mohammed-bin-salman-saudi-arabia-suspects-969185217 |title=Exclusive: Seven of bin Salman's bodyguards among Khashoggi suspects |work=Middle East Eye |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=10 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018003141/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/khashoggi-mohammed-bin-salman-saudi-arabia-suspects-969185217 |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ''Daily Sabah'' outlet named and detailed:\n\n* Maher Abdulaziz Mutreb ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0627\u0647\u0631 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0645\u0637\u0631\u0628|links=no}}) (born 1971): a former diplomat in London, was photographed with [[Mohammad bin Salman]] on trips to [[Madrid]], [[Paris]], [[Houston]], [[Boston]] and [[New York City|New York]].<ref>[https://archive.today/20181016232142/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/16/world/middleeast/khashoggi-saudi-prince.html Suspects in Khashoggi Case Had Ties to Saudi Crown Prince], by [[David D. Kirkpatrick]], Malachy Browne, Ben Hubbard and David Botti, 16 October 2018, [[The New York Times]]</ref><ref name=\"straitstimes\">{{cite news |title=Khashoggi case: Report links suspects to Saudi prince |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/middle-east/khashoggi-case-report-links-suspects-to-saudi-prince |work=[[The Straits Times]] |date=18 October 2018 |access-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020011536/https://www.straitstimes.com/world/middle-east/khashoggi-case-report-links-suspects-to-saudi-prince |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=One of the people believed to have been involved in Jamal Khashoggi's disappearance reportedly identified as frequent travel companion of Mohammed bin Salman |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jamal-khashoggi-disappearance-suspect-could-be-colleague-of-mohammed-bin-salman-2018-10 |work=Business Insider |date=17 October 2018 |access-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020053001/https://www.businessinsider.com/jamal-khashoggi-disappearance-suspect-could-be-colleague-of-mohammed-bin-salman-2018-10 |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> (convicted) Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* [[Salah Mohammed Tubaigy|Salah Mohammed al-Tubaigy]] ({{lang-ar|\u0635\u0644\u0627\u062d \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0628\u064a\u0642\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1971): the head of the Saudi Scientific Council of Forensics.<ref name=\"straitstimes\"/> (convicted) Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" /> \n* Abdulaziz Mohammed al-Hasawi ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0627\u0648\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1987): works as one of [[Mohammed bin Salman]]'s personal bodyguards.<ref name=\"straitstimes\"/>\n* Thaer Ghaleb al-Harbi ({{lang-ar|\u062b\u0627\u0626\u0631 \u063a\u0627\u0644\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0628\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1979): a member of the [[Saudi Royal Guard Regiment|Saudi Royal Guard]].<ref name=\"straitstimes\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" /> \n* Mohammed Saad al-Zahrani ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0633\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0632\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1988): a member of the [[Saudi Royal Guard Regiment|Saudi Royal Guard]].<ref name=\"straitstimes\"/><ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" /> \n* Meshal Saad al-Bostani ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0634\u0639\u0644 \u0633\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1987, died 2018): according to ''Al Jazeera'', a [[Lieutenant#Air force rank|lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Saudi Air Force|Saudi Air Force]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Matheson |first1=Rob |title=Who are the Saudi suspects in the Khashoggi case |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aGe1INeGhkU |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=17 October 2018}}</ref> According to Turkish media, he died in a car accident in Riyadh on return to Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite news |title=One of the men suspected of killing Jamal Khashoggi reportedly died in a car crash after returning to Saudi Arabia |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/khashoggi-suspect-mashal-saad-al-bostani-reportedly-dead-in-car-crash-2018-10 |accessdate=18 October 2018 |work=Business Insider |date=19 October 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018172317/https://www.businessinsider.com/khashoggi-suspect-mashal-saad-al-bostani-reportedly-dead-in-car-crash-2018-10 |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi who arrived in Turkey day of Khashoggi disappearance dies in 'traffic accident' |url=https://nypost.com/2018/10/18/saudi-who-arrived-in-turkey-day-of-khashoggi-disappearance-dies-in-traffic-accident/ |accessdate=18 October 2018 |work=New York Post |date=18 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018181319/https://nypost.com/2018/10/18/saudi-who-arrived-in-turkey-day-of-khashoggi-disappearance-dies-in-traffic-accident/ |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=One of 15 Saudis that targeted Khashoggi dies in suspicious car accident |url=https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/one-of-15-member-squad-that-targeted-khashoggi-dies-in-suspicious-car-accident-3463852 |accessdate=18 October 2018 |work=Yeni \u015eafak |language=tr-TR |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019040959/https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/one-of-15-member-squad-that-targeted-khashoggi-dies-in-suspicious-car-accident-3463852 |archive-date=19 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Naif Hassan al-Arefe ({{lang-ar|\u0646\u0627\u064a\u0641 \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u064a\u0641\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1986)<ref name=\"aljazeera 15 Saudis\">{{cite news |title=The 15 Saudis who flew to Turkey before Khashoggi's killing |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/15-saudis-flew-turkey-khashoggi-killing-181122144743650.html |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=aljazeera.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223162415/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/11/15-saudis-flew-turkey-khashoggi-killing-181122144743650.html |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n* Mustafa Mohammed al-Madani ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0635\u0637\u0641\u0649 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0646\u064a|links=no}})  (born 1961): Khashoggi's [[body double]] leaving the Saudi consulate by the back door, dressed in Khashoggi's clothes, a fake beard, and his glasses. The same man was seen at the [[Sultan Ahmed Mosque|Blue Mosque]], in an attempt to show that Khashoggi had left the consulate unharmed.<ref name=\"Tuysuz\">{{cite news |last1= Tuysuz |first1=Gul |last2=Abdelaziz |first2=Salma |last3=Balkiz |first3=Ghazi |last4=Formanek |first4=Ingrid |last5=Ward |first5=Clarissa |date=23 October 2018 |title=Surveillance footage shows Saudi 'body double' in Khashoggi's clothes after he was killed, Turkish source says |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/22/middleeast/saudi-operative-jamal-khashoggi-clothes/index.html |work=CNN |location=Istanbul |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023145023/https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/22/middleeast/saudi-operative-jamal-khashoggi-clothes/index.html |archive-date=23 October 2018 |access-date=23 October 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"ClarissaWard\">{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Clarissa |title=Who are the Saudi suspects in the Khashoggi case |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=41wj-5YKzkQ |publisher=CNN/Youtube |date=22 October 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024171328/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=41wj-5YKzkQ |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"TheGMcKernan\">{{cite web | last=Wintour | first=Patrick | last2=McKernan | first2=Bethan | title=CCTV footage appears to show Khashoggi body double in Istanbul | website=the Guardian | date=22 October 2018 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/22/cctv-footage-appears-to-show-jamal-khashoggi-body-double-in-istanbul | access-date=24 October 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023224357/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/22/cctv-footage-appears-to-show-jamal-khashoggi-body-double-in-istanbul | archive-date=23 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC23\"/>  Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Mansur Uthman Abahussein ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0646\u0635\u0648\u0631 \u0639\u062b\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0623\u0628\u0627\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646|links=no}}) (born 1972)<ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Waleed Abdullah al-Shehri ({{lang-ar|\u0648\u0644\u064a\u062f \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0647\u0631\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1980) (convicted),<ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Turki Musharraf al-Shehri ({{lang-ar|\u062a\u0631\u0643\u064a \u0645\u0634\u0631\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0647\u0631\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1982) (convicted)<ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Fahad Shabib al-Balawi ({{lang-ar|\u0641\u0647\u062f \u0634\u0628\u064a\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u0648\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1985) (convicted)<ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* Saif Saad al-Qahtani ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u064a\u0641 \u0633\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062d\u0637\u0627\u0646\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1973) Not charged and released.<ref name=\"BBC23\"/> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Middle 23 Dec\" />\n* Khalid Aedh al-Taibi ({{lang-ar|\u062e\u0627\u0644\u062f \u0639\u0627\u064a\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0628\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1988)<ref name=\"WaPo Oct 2018\" /> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\">{{cite web |title=Treasury Sanctions 17 Individuals for Their Roles in the Killing of Jamal Khashoggi {{!}} U.S. Department of the Treasury |url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm547 |website=home.treasury.gov |publisher=US Government |accessdate=23 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224073010/https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm547 |archive-date=24 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Badir Lafi al-Otaibi ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u062f\u0631 \u0644\u0627\u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062a\u064a\u0628\u064a|links=no}}) (born 1973)<ref name=\"WaPo Oct 2018\">{{cite news |title=What we know about the 15 Saudis said by Turkey to have played a role in Khashoggi's disappearance |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/investigations/khashoggi-saudi-suspects/ |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=The Washington Post |date=19 October 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223162413/https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/investigations/khashoggi-saudi-suspects/ |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Treasury Sanctions 17\" />\n* [[Ahmad Asiri (general)|Ahmad Asiri]], the deputy head of the Saudi intelligence agency [[General Intelligence Presidency|Riasat Al-Mukhabarat Al-A'amah]]. Sanctioned by US Treasury.<ref name=\"Middle 23 Dec\" />\n\n== Trial and convictions ==\nThe trial was conducted in secret with diplomats and Khashoggi family members permitted to attend but not speak. The court adhered to the official line that the killing was not premeditated.<ref name=\"Irish 23 Dec 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Jansen |first1=Michael |title=Khashoggi trial was an exercise in scapegoating and not justice |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/middle-east/khashoggi-trial-was-an-exercise-in-scapegoating-and-not-justice-1.4123789 |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=23 December 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223190308/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/middle-east/khashoggi-trial-was-an-exercise-in-scapegoating-and-not-justice-1.4123789 |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to the Saudi prosecutors, ten people were questioned and then released due to lack of evidence against them. A total of 11 people were put on trial by the court.<ref name=\"CNN 23 Dec 2019\">{{cite news |last1=Lister |first1=Tim |title=Saudi death sentence wipes MBS's fingerprints in Khashoggi killing |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/23/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-verdict-analysis-intl/index.html |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=CNN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223185112/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/23/middleeast/saudi-khashoggi-verdict-analysis-intl/index.html |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The court conducted ten hearings that were not open to the public. A few foreign diplomats were allowed to attend the hearings after swearing to secrecy. CNN reported that lack of public access made it impossible to understand how the court decided the verdict.<ref name=\"CNN 23 Dec 2019\" />\n\nOn 23 December 2019 five people were sentenced to death for carrying out Khashoggi's killing:\n\n* Fahad Shabib Albalawi\n* Turki Muserref Alshehri\n* Waleed Abdullah Alshehri\n* Maher Abdulaziz Mutreb, intelligence officer\n* Dr [[Salah Mohammed Tubaigy]], a forensic doctor from the Saudi interior ministry<ref name=\"BBC23\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-50890633|title=Jamal Khashoggi: Saudis sentence five to death for journalist's murder|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=23 December 2019|access-date=23 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223094357/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-50890633|archive-date=23 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN 23 Dec 2019\" />\n\nThree other defendants, unnamed {{As of|2019|12|23|lc=y}}, were sentenced to a combined total of 24 years in prison for \"covering up this crime and violating the law\".<ref name=\"BBC23\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/saudi-arabia-sentences-five-people-to-death-over-khashoggi-killing-11893950|title=Saudi Arabia sentences five people to death over Khashoggi killing|website=Sky News|access-date=23 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223114252/https://news.sky.com/story/saudi-arabia-sentences-five-people-to-death-over-khashoggi-killing-11893950|archive-date=23 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe following defendants were released:\n\n* [[Saud al-Qahtani]], released without charge\n* [[Ahmed al-Assiri (general)|Ahmed al-Assiri]], a former deputy intelligence chief, released due to a lack of evidence\n* [[Al-Otaibi|Mohammed al-Otaibi]], Saudi Arabia's consul-general in Istanbul, released due to a lack of evidence<ref name=\"Middle 23 Dec\">{{cite news |title=Khashoggi murder: Saudi Arabia sentences five to death, Qahtani not charged |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-arabia-sentences-five-death-over-jamal-khashoggi-murder |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=Middle East Eye |date=23 December 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223161215/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-arabia-sentences-five-death-over-jamal-khashoggi-murder |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe eight Saudis convicted in the verdict can appeal further. Clemency can be offered by Salah Khashoggi, the eldest son of Khashoggi.<ref name=\"Middle 23 Dec\" />\n\n===Response===\nCNN reported that the verdict was accepted by Khashoggi's sons. According to [[Amnesty International]]'s Middle East Research Director Lynn Maalouf, the verdict was a whitewash and the organisation released a statement saying: \"The verdict fails to address the Saudi authorities' involvement in this devastating crime or clarify the location of Jamal Khashoggi's remains&nbsp;... only an international, independent and impartial investigation can serve justice for Jamal Khashoggi.\"<ref name=\"CNN 23 Dec 2019\" />\n\nThe [[United Nations]] rapporteur on summary executions, [[Agn\u00e8s Callamard]], described the sentence as a \"mockery\" of justice, since, according to her, it was an \"[[extrajudicial killing|extrajudicial execution]] for which the state of Saudi Arabia is responsible\" and its masterminds walk free.<ref name=\"aljaz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/turkey-rights-groups-decry-saudi-verdict-khashoggi-murder-191223171239748.html|title=Turkey, rights groups decry Saudi verdict on Khashoggi murder|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=23 December 2019|access-date=23 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223210119/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/turkey-rights-groups-decry-saudi-verdict-khashoggi-murder-191223171239748.html|archive-date=23 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThree weeks to the day after the death of Khashoggi, on 22 October 2018, his son and brother were summoned to a [[photo op]] with King Salman and the heir to the throne, at the Palace of Yamamah, in Riyadh. Salah bin Jamal Khashoggi and his uncle Sahel were received by the royals. Pictures of the event went viral, amid reports that Salah, who lives in [[Jeddah]], has been banned from leaving the country since 2017. A family friend, [[Yehia Assiri]], described the event as \"a serious assault on the family\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Feis |first=Aaron |url=https://nypost.com/2018/10/23/khashoggis-son-meets-with-saudi-king-and-crown-prince/ |title=Khashoggi's son meets with Saudi king and crown prince |work=Nypost.com |accessdate=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024152548/https://nypost.com/2018/10/23/khashoggis-son-meets-with-saudi-king-and-crown-prince/ |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/twitter-storm-khashoggi-son-meets-saudi-crown-prince-181024011910161.html |title=Twitter storm after Khashoggi's son meets Saudi crown prince |work=Al Jazeera |date=24 October 2018 |accessdate=25 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024192201/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/10/twitter-storm-khashoggi-son-meets-saudi-crown-prince-181024011910161.html |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Nick Paton Walsh]], a senior international correspondent, described it as \"a remarkable display of the sustained and catastrophic disconnect between Riyadh and the outside world. As if PR is something you shoot yourself in the foot with.\"<ref name=\"Walsh2018\">{{cite news |last=Walsh |first=Nick Paton |title=Meeting Khashoggi's son could backfire for bin Salman |website=CNN |date=24 October 2018 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/24/opinions/bin-salman-khashoggi-saudi-brand-opinion-intl/index.html |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024203852/https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/24/opinions/bin-salman-khashoggi-saudi-brand-opinion-intl/index.html |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 24 October 2018, Salah Khashoggi, who holds dual Saudi-US citizenship, and his family left Saudi Arabia for the US.<ref>{{cite web |first=Bethan |last=McKernan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/25/jamal-khashoggi-killing-premeditated-says-saudi-prosecutor |title=Khashoggi's son leaves Saudi Arabia as prosecutor says killing was planned |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 October 2018 |accessdate=22 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121213456/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/25/jamal-khashoggi-killing-premeditated-says-saudi-prosecutor |archive-date=21 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 8 December 2018, ''Newsweek'' reported allegations that Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman and President Trump's son-in-law, [[Jared Kushner]], had \"maintained unofficial communications via a WhatsApp chat for the past two years and&nbsp;... continued to speak in the wake of Khashoggi's killing.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/kushner-defended-crown-prince-murder-text-messages-1250810|title=Jared Kushner defended Saudi Crown prince after Khashoggi's death, and kept chatting in text messages, report says|last=O'Connor|first=Tom|date=8 December 2018|website=Newsweek|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120221602/https://www.newsweek.com/kushner-defended-crown-prince-murder-text-messages-1250810|archive-date=20 November 2019|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other alleged abduction attempts==\nFollowing Jamal Khashoggi's killing and mutilation, several other exiled Saudi activists reported that the Saudi regime attempted to lure them into their embassies.<ref name=\"Other Exiles1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/saudi-dissidents-fear-long-arm-state-khashoggi-murder-114854780.html|title=Saudi dissidents fear 'long arm' of state after Khashoggi murder|work=AFP|access-date=2 November 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106184437/https://www.yahoo.com/news/saudi-dissidents-fear-long-arm-state-khashoggi-murder-114854780.html|archive-date=6 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Other Exiles2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.presstv.com/Detail/2018/10/22/577772/Saudi-exiles-Jamal-Khashoggi-Mohammed-bin-Salman-trap|title=Riyadh tried to 'trap' us in overseas embassies: Saudi dissidents|work=PressTV|access-date=22 October 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022212752/https://www.presstv.com/Detail/2018/10/22/577772/Saudi-exiles-Jamal-Khashoggi-Mohammed-bin-Salman-trap|archive-date=22 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Middle East Eye'' published claims from an unnamed source with knowledge of Saudi intelligence agencies that the murder is part of a larger operation of silently murdering critics of Saudi government by a death squad named \"[[Tiger Squad]]\", composed of the most trusted and skilled intelligence agents.<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\" /> According to the source, the Tiger Squad assassinates dissidents using varying methods such as planned car accidents, house fires, or poisoning clinics by injecting toxic substances into opponents when they attend regular health checkups. The alleged group members are recruited from different branches of the Saudi forces, directing several areas of expertise.<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\" /> According to ''Middle East Eye'', five members were part of the 15-member death squad who were sent to murder Khashoggi.<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\"/>\n\nExiled Saudi activist Omar Abdulaziz said he was approached earlier in 2018 by Saudi officials who urged him to visit the [[Embassy of Saudi Arabia, Ottawa|Saudi embassy in Ottawa]], Canada with them to collect a new passport. The Saudi activist stated that the officials from the Saudi regime, \"They were saying 'it will only take one hour, just come with us to the embassy.{{'\"}} After Omar Abdulaziz refused, Saudi authorities arrested two of his brothers and several of his friends in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"Other Exiles2\" /> Abdulaziz secretly recorded his conversations with those officials, which were several hours long, and provided them to ''The Washington Post''.<ref name=\"Other Exiles3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/saudi-dissidents-fear-long-arm-of-state-after-khashoggi-murder/article/535176|title=Saudi dissidents fear 'long arm' of state after Khashoggi murder|work=Digital Journal|access-date=22 October 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022160313/http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/saudi-dissidents-fear-long-arm-of-state-after-khashoggi-murder/article/535176|archive-date=22 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The source interviewed by ''Middle East Eye'' also said the team planned to kill Omar Abdelaziz and claimed prince [[Mansour bin Muqrin]] was assassinated by the squad by shooting down his personal aircraft as he was fleeing the country on 5 November 2017 and made to appear as an accidental crash.<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\" />\n\nOpposition Saudi scholar Abdullah Alaoudh (son of [[Salman al-Ouda]]) said he was subjected to a similar plot when he sent in a passport renewal application to the [[Embassy of Saudi Arabia in Washington, D.C.|Saudi Embassy in Washington]]. Alaoudh said, \"They offered me a 'temporary pass' that would allow me to return to Saudi Arabia.\" Alaoudh suspected a trap and just let his passport expire.<ref name=\"Other Exiles1\" /><ref name=\"Other Exiles2\" /> Prominent Saudi women's rights activist [[Manal al-Sharif]] also separately reported a similar event during her exile in Australia, having said: \"If it weren't for the kindness of God I would have been [another] victim.\"<ref name=\"Other Exiles1\" /><ref name=\"Other Exiles2\" />  The Tiger Squad also reportedly killed Suleiman Abdul Rahman al-Thuniyan, a Saudi court judge who was murdered by an injection of a deadly virus into his body when he had visited a hospital for a regular health checkup. \"One of the techniques the Tiger Squad uses to silence dissidents or opponents of the government is to 'kill them with [[HIV]], or other sorts of deadly viruses'\".<ref name=\"middleeasteye/22oct2018\" />\n\n==Reactions==\n{{main|Reactions to the assassination of Jamal Khashoggi}}\nFor 18 days, Saudi Arabian officials denied Khashoggi had died in the consulate, before indicating a team of Saudi agents had overstepped their orders to capture him when a struggle ensued leading to his death.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fraser |first1=Suzan |last2=Deeb |first2=Sarah El |last3=Press |first3=Jon Gambrell Associated |last4=October 19 |first4=Updated |title=For 1st time, Saudis say Jamal Khashoggi killed in consulate \u2013 The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/world/2018/10/19/saudi-state-run-news-agency-quotes-prosecutors-saying-that-jamal-khashoggi-was-killed-saudi-consulate-fight/YUMIdTDF7KIac1zBlADi3O/story.html |work=BostonGlobe.com |access-date=9 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709080032/https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/world/2018/10/19/saudi-state-run-news-agency-quotes-prosecutors-saying-that-jamal-khashoggi-was-killed-saudi-consulate-fight/YUMIdTDF7KIac1zBlADi3O/story.html |archive-date=9 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Turkey's president, [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], said he believes the killing was premeditated and approved by the Saudi government, and sought extradition of the suspects.<ref name=\"CNNErdogan_body\">{{cite news |title=Erdogan demands Saudi Arabia reveal the location of Jamal Khashoggi's body |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/26/middleeast/saudi-turkey-khashoggi-investigation-intl/index.html |accessdate=26 October 2018 |publisher=CNN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181026213849/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/26/middleeast/saudi-turkey-khashoggi-investigation-intl/index.html |archive-date=26 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The United States' president, [[Donald Trump]], expressed support for the Saudi government, reserving judgment about culpability.<ref name=\"wintour\"/> This created a bipartisan uproar in [[United States Congress|Congress]], and 22 senators petitioned Trump to consider investigating whether Saudi Arabia should be sanctioned for human rights violations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jamal-khashoggi-missing-saudi-arabia-turkey-istanbul-consulate-dismembered-lindsey-graham-us-a8578266.html|title=Jamal Khashoggi disappearance: 'Hell to pay' for Saudi Arabia if journalist was murdered, Lindsey Graham says|newspaper=The Independent|date=10 October 2018|access-date=22 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012043114/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jamal-khashoggi-missing-saudi-arabia-turkey-istanbul-consulate-dismembered-lindsey-graham-us-a8578266.html|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Several countries called for a transparent investigation and condemned the killing. Allied Arab countries characterized the aftermath as a media campaign against Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia's Arab Allies Come To Its Defense In The Khashoggi Murder Affair |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/saudi-arabias-arab-allies-come-its-defense-khashoggi-murder-affair |publisher=[[MEMRI]] |date=24 October 2018 |language=en |access-date=9 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709080042/https://www.memri.org/reports/saudi-arabias-arab-allies-come-its-defense-khashoggi-murder-affair |archive-date=9 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGermany, Norway and Denmark<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zeit.de/news/2018-11/22/daenemark-stoppt-waffenlieferungen-an-saudi-arabien-wegen-fall-khashoggi-20181122-doc-1b10bj|title=D\u00e4nemark stoppt Waffenlieferungen an Saudi-Arabien wegen Fall Khashoggi|date=22 November 2018|work=Die Zeit|access-date=22 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122143651/https://www.zeit.de/news/2018-11/22/daenemark-stoppt-waffenlieferungen-an-saudi-arabien-wegen-fall-khashoggi-20181122-doc-1b10bj|archive-date=22 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> stopped the sale of arms to Saudi Arabia over the incident. Canada considered freezing its $13 billion [[General Dynamics Land Systems \u2013 Canada]] arms deal,<ref name=\"MEE_NorwayArms\">{{cite news|url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/norway-suspends-future-arms-exports-saudi-arabia-829709770|title=Norway suspends future arms exports to Saudi Arabia|date=9 November 2018|accessdate=9 November 2018|website=Middle East Eye|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110120140/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/norway-suspends-future-arms-exports-saudi-arabia-829709770|archive-date=10 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> but so far has chosen to proceed with the deal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/03/04/700055559/canada-set-to-go-ahead-with-arms-deal-saudi-arabia-says|title=Canada Set To Go Ahead With Arms Deal, Saudi Arabia Says|last=Mortada|first=Dalia|date=4 March 2019|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=25 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724091437/https://www.npr.org/2019/03/04/700055559/canada-set-to-go-ahead-with-arms-deal-saudi-arabia-says|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.karenvecchiomp.ca/saudi_arms_export_deal_warning|title=Killing Saudi arms export deal would 'devastate' London region, says Tory MP Vecchio|last=Moss|first=Neil|date=9 January 2019|website=Hill Times, via Karen Vecchio MP|language=en|access-date=25 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725034348/https://www.karenvecchiomp.ca/saudi_arms_export_deal_warning|archive-date=25 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a U.S. senator, the [[Trump administration]] granted authorizations to US companies to share sensitive [[Nuclear proliferation|nuclear power information]] with Saudi Arabia shortly after the assassination of Jamal Khashoggi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL2N23B13V|title=U.S. shared nuclear power info with Saudi Arabia after Khashoggi killed|date=4 June 2019|agency=Reuters|access-date=21 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721152022/https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL2N23B13V|archive-date=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2019, Trump vetoed three bipartisan Congressional resolutions that would have halted arms sales.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/saudi-arms-sale-resolutions-trump-veto/index.html|title=Trump vetoes 3 bills prohibiting arms sales to Saudi Arabia|last=Cohen|first=Zachary|last2=Klein|first2=Betsy|date=25 July 2019|website=CNN|access-date=25 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725034347/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/saudi-arms-sale-resolutions-trump-veto/index.html|archive-date=25 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 2018, Khashoggi was named as a [[Time Person of the Year|person of the year]] by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine for his work in journalism, along with other journalists who faced political persecution for their work. ''Time'' referred to Khashoggi, and the others, as a \"Guardian of the Truth\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/11/business/media/jamal-khashoggi-person-of-the-year-time.html|title=Time Names Person of the Year for 2018: Jamal Khashoggi and Other Journalists|first1=Matthew|last1=Haag|first2=Michael M.|last2=Grynbaum|date=11 December 2018|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=11 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211214442/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/11/business/media/jamal-khashoggi-person-of-the-year-time.html|archive-date=11 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/11/media/time-person-of-the-year-2018/index.html|title=Time Person of the Year: 'The Guardians and the War on Truth'|first=Jill Disis and Brian Stelter, CNN|last=Business|website=CNN|access-date=7 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211202747/https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/11/media/time-person-of-the-year-2018/index.html|archive-date=11 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2018/12/11/times-person-year-guardians-truth-including-slain-journalist-jamal-khashoggi/|title=Time's Person of the Year: 'Guardians' of the truth, including slain journalist Jamal Khashoggi|website=The Washington Post|access-date=11 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211200623/https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2018/12/11/times-person-year-guardians-truth-including-slain-journalist-jamal-khashoggi/|archive-date=11 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Politics|Saudi Arabia}}\n*[[The Dissident]] \u2013 a 2020 American documentary film about the assassination of Khashoggi, directed by [[Bryan Fogel]]\n*[[Freedom of the press]]\n*[[Pegasus (spyware)]]\n*[[Human rights in Saudi Arabia]]\n**[[Israa al-Ghomgham]] \u2013 Saudi human rights activist who documented the [[2017\u201318 Qatif unrest]] and faces execution by beheading\n**[[Nimr al-Nimr|Sheikh Baqir al-Nimr]] \u2013 dissident cleric executed for criticism of the Saudi regime\n**[[Ali Mohammed Baqir al-Nimr]], (Sheikh Baqir al-Nimr's nephew), participated in the [[2011\u201312 Saudi Arabian protests|protests]] during the [[Arab Spring]], arrested at the age of 17 and sentenced to death, to be carried out by beheading and crucifixion\n**[[Salman al-Ouda]] \u2013 cleric in the city of Riyadh, urged the Saudi monarchy to launch democratic reforms, sentenced to death in September 2018<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=[[Dexter Filkins]] |title=In the Aftermath of Jamal Khashoggi's Murder, Saudi Arabia Enters a Dangerous Period |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/in-the-aftermath-of-khashoggis-murder-saudi-arabia-enters-a-dangerous-period |date=2 November 2018 |magazine=The New Yorker |access-date=3 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103210338/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/in-the-aftermath-of-khashoggis-murder-saudi-arabia-enters-a-dangerous-period |archive-date=3 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n**[[Raif Badawi]] \u2013 imprisoned Saudi dissident, writer and activist\n**[[Hamza Kashgari]] \u2013 pro-democracy activist and columnist imprisoned for blasphemy\n**[[Dina Ali Lasloom]] \u2013 imprisoned Saudi asylum seeker\n**[[Samar Badawi]] \u2013 imprisoned Saudi activist\n**[[Fahad Albutairi|Fahad al-Butairi]] \u2013 abducted in Jordan and taken to be imprisoned in Saudi Arabia\n**[[Manal al-Sharif]] \u2013 Saudi human rights activist\n**[[Loujain al-Hathloul]] \u2013 imprisoned Saudi activist\n**[[Mishaal bint Fahd bin Mohammed Al Saud]] \u2013 Saudi princess executed for alleged adultery\n**[[Sara bint Talal bin Abdulaziz Al Saud]] \u2013 exiled Saudi princess and regime critic\n*[[2016 Saudi Arabia mass execution]]\n*[[2017 Lebanon\u2013Saudi Arabia dispute|2017 Saad Hariri affair]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|On Standing with Saudi Arabia|Statement from Donald J. Trump On Standing with Saudi Arabia}}\n* [https://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/RegularSessions/Session41/Documents/A_HRC_41_CRP.1.docx Annex to the Report of the Special Rapporteur on extrajudicial, summary or arbitrary executions: Investigation into the unlawful death of Mr. Jamal Khashoggi] (19 June 2019), [[United Nations Human Rights Council]], 41st Session (24 June \u2013 12 July 2019) \n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/people/jamal-khashoggi Khashoggi's columns for ''The Washington Post'']\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/12/how-jamal-khashoggi-disappeared-visual-guide Visual guide to Khashoggi's disappearance] on ''[[The Guardian]]''\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uJ44spUo8Uk Killing Jamal Khashoggi: How a Brutal Saudi Hit Job Unfolded \u2013 Visual Investigations], The New York Times (YouTube), 16 November 2018.\n{{Authority control}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xaeYMysnuvY  The Jamal Khashoggi murder reconstructed, Al Jazeera English (YouTube), 3 April 2019]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khashoggi, Jamal}}\n[[Category:2018 controversies]]\n[[Category:2018 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2018 in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:2018 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:2010s crimes in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:2010s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic incidents]]\n[[Category:Khashoggi family]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Murder in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:October 2018 crimes in Europe]]\n[[Category:October 2018 events in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabia\u2013Turkey relations]]\n[[Category:2018 murders in Asia]]\n[[Category:Assassinations in Turkey]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:98be:e400:21d3:1cdc:ba44:d7cb", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assassination_of_Jamal_Khashoggi"}
{"title_page": "Youssef Boughanem", "text_new": "{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Youssef Boughanem\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| other_names     = Terminator \n| nationality     = {{flagicon|Belgium}} Belgian, {{flagicon|Morocco}} Moroccan \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1989|12|6}}\n| birth_place     = [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]\n| fighting_out_of = Thailand \n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| height_m        = 1.85\n| weight_kg       = 72.5 \n| weight_class    = [[Middleweight]]<br>[[Welterweight]] \n| reach           = \n| style           = [[Muay Thai]] \n| stance          =\n| team            = Petchsaman Gym \n| trainer         = \n| years_active    = 2008 \u2013 present\n| kickbox_win     = 183\n| kickbox_kowin   = \n| kickbox_loss    = 23\n| kickbox_koloss  = \n| kickbox_draw    = 4 \n| kickbox_nc      = 1\n| other           = \n| occupation      = \n| spouse          = \n| relatives       = \n| students        = \n| university      = \n| url             = \n| boxrec          =\n| sherdog         =\n| updated         = March 14, 2020 \n}}\n\n'''Youssef Boughanem''' (born December 6, 1989) is a Moroccan-Belgian [[Muay Thai]] [[kickboxer]] who is the reigning [[WBC Muay Thai]] World Middleweight Champion. He is a former [[Lumpinee Stadium]] and [[Rajadamnern Stadium]] [[Middleweight|160 lb]] Champion. Boughanem currently trains out of the Petchsaman Gym in [[Thailand]]. \n\nBoughanem is also a former THAI FIGHT tournament winner, having competed for the promotion from 2010 to 2017.\n\n==Muay Thai career== \nYoussef began practicing Muay Thai at the age of 12 and moved to Thailand with his brother, Yassine Boughanem, at the age of 17 to focus on training on a fulltime basis. Yassine is a Muay Thai fighter in the heavyweight division.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://asianmma.com/youssef-boughanem-muay-thais-enduring-belgian-star/|title=Youssef Boughanem: Muay Thai's enduring Belgian star|website=Asian MMA|date=2018-11-16|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> \n\nHe gained prominence when he competed in the first-ever THAI FIGHT event in 2010. On August 29, 2010, he defeated Australia's Jason Lea in the round-of-sixteen. He then defeated Ireland's Anthony Kane via extra-round decision in the quarter-finals on October 25, 2010. On December 6, 2010, Boughanem defeated Soichiro Miyakoshi to advance to the final round of the THAI FIGHT tournament. That same night, he lost to [[Fabio Pinca]] in the final, where he finished as the runner-up in the THAI FIGHT 67kg welterweight tournament.\n\nAfter his first THAI FIGHT outing, Boughanem fought for different programs around Thailand and France. He eventually returned in 2013 when THAI FIGHT unveiled their new format: THAI FIGHT Kard Chuek. This format saw fighters wearing rope bindings instead of gloves (Muay Kard Chuek) and would eventually become the defining characteristic for subsequent THAI FIGHT events. Youssef Boughanem would enter the inaugural THAI FIGHT Kard Chuek tournament. On June 1, 2013, he defeated Salahdine Ait Naceur by second-round knockout in the 1/16 finals. He then beat Sebastien Billard in the 1/8 finals by first-round knockout on June 15, 2013. On July 14, 2013, he defeated Burmese fighter Zaw Tum in the quarterfinals after a three-round decision. Za Tum is better known as [[Tun Tun Min]] and became went on to be [[Lethwei|Openweight Lethwei World Champion]]. On July 29, 2013, Boughanem was eliminated from the tournament when he lost in the semifinal round by decision to [[Saiyok Pumpanmuang]], who eventually finished as the THAI FIGHT Kard Chuek tournament runner-up.    \n\nOn August 15, 2015, Youssef Boughanem defeated Rungrawee P.K. Saenchaimuaythaigym by third-round knockout to capture the Omnoi Stadium middleweight title. He successfully defended the Omnoi Stadium title against Chanajon P.K. Saenchaimuaythaigym by five-round decision on September 26 of the same year.\n\nAfter an absence from the promotion in 2014, Youssef Boughanem made his return to THAI FIGHT in late 2015, appearing at THAI FIGHT Vietnam on October 24, 2015. There, he faced Russian fighter Yurik Davtyan and won by decision. Later on, he entered the 2015 THAI FIGHT 72.5kg tournament. In the tournament semifinals, Boughanem defeated Rungrawee P.K. Saenchaimuaythaigym at THAI FIGHT RPCA on November 21, 2015. On December 31, 2015, he defeated [[Sudsakorn Sor Klinmee]] at THAI FIGHT Count Down to win the 2015 THAI FIGHT 72.5kg tournament and capture his first THAI FIGHT title. \n\nOn June 24, 2016, Youssef Boughanem defeated [[Armen Petrosyan]] via three-decision in [[Monte Carlo]] to win the [[World Association of Kickboxing Organizations|WAKO]] Pro 71.8kg Championship.\n\nOn August 31, 2016, he defeated Kompetch Lookprabat by fourth-round knockout to capture the [[Rajadamnern Stadium]] middleweight championship. On February 26, 2018, Boughanem retained the Rajadamnern title against Noppakaw Siriluck Muaythai by third-round knockout at Phoenix 5 Bangkok, which also saw him winning the [[WBC Muay Thai]] Middleweight World Championship. On April 28, 2018, he defeated by Payakdam Extra Cole Film by third-round TKO to win the [[International Boxing Federation Muaythai|IBF Muaythai]] middleweight title. On May 22, 2018, Youssef Boughanem defeated Talaytong Sor. Thanaphet by fourth-round TKO to win the [[Lumpinee Stadium]] middleweight championship. He retained the WBC Muay Thai title against Kongjak Por. Pao In on October 13, 2018, where he also won the [[International Sport Karate Association|ISKA]] Muay Thai light middleweight title. He defended the WBC Muay Thai title a third time against Joe Craven on April 22, 2019, winning by fourth-round TKO. Boughanem successfully retained the WBC Muay Thai belt in his fourth title defense against Tobias Alexandersson on November 16, 2019, winning a five-round decision.\n\n==Titles and accomplishments==\n* 2019 [[WBC Muay Thai]] [[List of WBC Muaythai world champions|Middleweight Champion]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbcmuaythai.com/champions.php|title=WBC Muay Thai World Champions|website=WBC Muay Thai|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> \n* 2019 [[World Kickboxing Network|WKN]] Muay Thai World Super Welterweight Champion \n* 2018 [[International Sport Karate Association|ISKA]] Muay Thai Light Middleweight Champion \n* 2018 [[Lumpinee Stadium]] Middleweight 160 lb Champion \n* 2018 [[International Boxing Federation Muaythai|IBF Muaythai]] [[List of IBF Muaythai world champions|Middleweight Champion]]\n* 2017 Phoenix FC Middleweight Champion\n* 2016 [[Rajadamnern Stadium]] Middleweight 160 lb Champion \n* 2016 [[World Association of Kickboxing Organizations|WAKO]] Pro Kickboxing 71.8kg/158lbs Champion\n* 2015 THAI FIGHT 72.5kg Tournament Champion \n* 2015 Omnoi Stadium Middleweight 160 lb Champion\n* 2015 Venum Middleweight Champion \n* 2014 MAX Muay Thai Tournament Champion\n* 2010 WMA 71kg Tournament Champion \n* 2010 1-KING Tournament Champion\n* 2010 TCC Super Welterweight Tournament Champion \n* 2009 Thepprasit Stadium Champion\n* 2007 Belgium Muay Thai Champion\n\n==Muay Thai record==\n{| class=\"toccolours\"  style=\"width:100%; clear:both; margin:1.5em auto; font-size:85%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:darkGrey;\"| <span style=\"color:white;\">Kickboxing record</span>\n|- valign=\"top\" \n|<div class=\"NavFrame\">\n<div class=\"NavHead\" style=\"background:white; \"><span style=\"color:black;\">'''183 Wins ''' , '''23 Losses ''', '''4 Draws ''', '''1 No Contest '''</span></div>\n<div class=\"NavContent\" style=\"text-align:left; display:collapse;\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#ddd;\"\n| '''Date''' || '''Result''' || '''Opponent''' || '''Event''' || '''Location''' || '''Method''' || '''Round''' || '''Time'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center; background:#cfc;\"\n| 2020-01-29|| Win ||align=left|{{fla