ry of Holland'' (1999) 264 pp. [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0313306583 excerpt and text search]\n* [[Jonathan Israel|Israel, Jonathan]]. ''The Dutch Republic: Its Rise, Greatness, and Fall, 1477\u20131806'' (1995) a major synthesis; [https://www.questia.com/read/91981119 complete online edition]; also [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0198207344 excerpt and text search]\n* Kooi, Christine. \"The Reformation in the Netherlands: Some Historiographic Contributions in English.\" ''Archiv f\u00fcr Reformationsgeschichte'' 100.1 (2009): 293\u2013307.\n*  Koopmans, Joop W., and Arend H. Huussen Jr. ''Historical Dictionary of the Netherlands'' (2nd ed. 2007)[https://www.amazon.com/Historical-Dictionary-Netherlands-Dictionaries-Europe/dp/0810856271/ excerpt and text search]\n* Kossmann, E. H. ''The Low Countries 1780\u20131940'' (1978), detailed survey; [http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/koss002lage01_01/ full text online in Dutch (use CHROME browser for automatic translation to English)]\n* Kossmann-Putto, J. A. and E. H. Kossmann. ''The Low Countries: History of the Northern and Southern Netherlands'' (1987)\n* Milward, Alan S. and S. B. Saul. ''The Economic Development of Continental Europe 1780\u20131870'' (2nd ed. 1979), 552 pp.\n* Milward, Alan S. and S. B. Saul. ''The Development of the Economies of Continental Europe: 1850\u20131914'' (1977) pp.&nbsp;142\u2013214\n* Moore, Bob, and Henk Van Nierop. ''Twentieth-Century Mass Society in Britain and the Netherlands'' (Berg 2006) [https://www.questia.com/read/118217447/twentieth-century-mass-society-in-britain-and-the online edition]\n* van Oostrom, Frits, and Hubert Slings. ''A Key to Dutch History'' (2007)\n* Pirenne, Henri. ''Belgian Democracy, Its Early History'' (1910, 1915) 250 pp. history of towns in the Low Countries [https://www.questia.com/read/1276323 online free]\n* Rietbergen, P.J.A.N.  ''A Short History of the Netherlands. From Prehistory to the Present Day''. 5th ed. Amersfoort: Bekking, 2002. {{ISBN|90-6109-440-2}}\n*[[Simon Schama|Schama, Simon]], ''[[The Embarrassment of Riches: An Interpretation of Dutch Culture in the Golden Age]]'' (1991) [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0679781242 excerpt and text search], very well written broad survey\n* Schama, Simon. ''Patriots and Liberators: Revolution in the Netherlands, 1780\u2013 1813'' (London: Collins, 1977)\n* Treasure, Geoffrey. ''The Making of Modern Europe, 1648\u20131780'' (3rd ed. 2003). pp 463\u201393.\n* Vlekke, Bernard H. M. ''Evolution of the Dutch Nation'' (1945) 382 pp. [https://www.questia.com/read/82243176 online edition]\n* Wintle, Michael P. ''An Economic and Social History of the Netherlands, 1800\u20131920: Demographic, Economic, and Social Transition'' (Cambridge University Press, 2000) [https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=105016141 online edition]\n*Van Tuyll Van Serooskerken, Hubert P. '' The Netherlands and World War I: Espionage, Diplomacy and Survival'' (Brill 2001) [https://www.questia.com/read/118479769/the-netherlands-and-world-war-i-espionage-diplomacy online edition]\n* Vries, Jan de, and A. van der Woude. ''The First Modern Economy. Success, Failure, and Perseverance of the Dutch Economy, 1500\u20131815'' (Cambridge University Press, 1997)\n* Vries, Jan de. \"Benelux, 1920\u20131970,\" in C. M. Cipolla, ed. ''The Fontana Economic History of Europe: Contemporary Economics Part One'' (1976) pp.&nbsp;1\u201371\n* van Zanden, J. L. ''The Economic History of The Netherlands 1914\u20131995: A Small Open Economy in the 'Long' Twentieth Century'' (Routledge, 1997) [https://www.amazon.com/Economic-History-Netherlands-1914-1995-Contemporary/dp/0415150035/  excerpt and text search]\n* Vandenbosch, Amry. ''Dutch Foreign Policy since 1815'' (1959). [https://books.google.com/books?id=kgbsCAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=intitle:Dutch+intitle:Foreign+intitle:Policy+intitle:since+intitle:1815&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwih-are3KHZAhVCxWMKHXstDboQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false online]; [https://www.questia.com/library/3392771/dutch-foreign-policy-since-1815-a-study-in-small full text at Questia]\n* Vandenbosch, Amry. ''The neutrality of the Netherlands during the world war'' (1927).\n* Wielenga, Friso. ''A History of the Netherlands: From the Sixteenth Century to the Present Day'' (2015) 344 pp\n\n{{refend}}\n\n===Geography and environment===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Burke, Gerald L. ''The making of Dutch towns: A study in urban development from the 10th\u201317th centuries'' (1960)\n*  Lambert, Audrey M. ''The Making of the Dutch Landscape: An Historical Geography of the Netherlands'' (1985); focus on the history of land reclamation\n* Meijer, Henk. ''Compact geography of The Netherlands''  (1985)\n* Riley, R. C., and G. J. Ashworth. ''Benelux: An Economic Geography of Belgium, the Netherlands, and Luxembourg'' (1975) [https://www.questia.com/read/85882918/benelux-an-economic-geography-of-belgium-the-netherlands online]\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|History of the Netherlands}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041013072113/http://www.20eeuwennederland.nl/periodes Chronologisch overzicht van de Nederlandse geschiedenis (in Dutch)]\n* [http://dutchrevolt.leidenuniv.nl/Nederlands/default.htm De Tachtigjarige Oorlog (in Dutch)]\n* [http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/maney/dtc/ ''Dutch Crossing: Journal of Low Countries Studies''], a scholarly journal\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/14971 History of Holland, George Edmundson, 1922, Project Gutenberg EBook.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120926161214/http://www.innl.nl/page/14332/en History of the Netherlands from 50 BC to 2005]\n* [http://eudocs.lib.byu.edu/index.php/History_of_the_Netherlands:_Primary_Documents History of Netherlands: Primary Documents]\n* [http://www.niod.nl/ Netherlands Institute for War Documentation]\n* [http://www.infoplease.com/country/netherlands.html Netherlands: Maps, History, Geography, Government, Culture, Facts, Guide & Travel &#124; Infoplease.com]\n* [http://www.historical-novel.com/ Overview of historical novels about The Netherlands and Belgium]\n* [http://home.zonnet.nl/van.duijvenbode/en/geschnl-o.htm Short survey of the Dutch history]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090612225030/http://www.entoen.nu/default.aspx?lan=e The Canon of the Netherlands.]\n* [http://home.versatel.nl/postbus/index2.html The Netherlands in prehistory]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/1043528.stm Timeline from 1914]\n* [http://bbs.keyhole.com/ubb/showflat.php?Cat=&Board=EarthHistory&Number=701881&Searchpage=1&Main=701881&Words=dutch+history&topic=&Search=true#Post701881 Virtual Tour of Dutch History (101 Sites in Google Earth with Links)]\n* [http://nlgis.nl Netherlands Geographic Information System (1812\u20131997) ]\n\n{{Netherlands topics}}\n{{The Netherlands year nav}}\n{{History of Europe}}\n{{European history by country}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Netherlands}}\n[[Category:History of the Netherlands| ]]\n[[Category:Articles which contain graphical timelines]]\n", "name_user": "Caleb0719", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Netherlands"}
{"title_page": "Univa Grid Engine", "text_new": "{{short description|Batch-queuing system to schedule resources in a data center}}\n{{Infobox software\n| title                  = \n| name                   = Univa Grid Engine Software\n| logo                   = <!-- [[File: ]] -->\n| logo caption           = \n| screenshot             = <!-- [[File: ]] -->\n| caption                = \n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = \n| developer              = [[Univa]]\n| released               = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| discontinued           = \n| latest release version = 8.6.12\n| latest release date    = {{Start date and age|2020|04|15|df=yes/no}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = [[Cross-platform]]\n| platform               = \n| size                   = \n| language               = \n| genre                  = [[Grid computing]] [[Supercomputing]]\n| license                = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]] [[commercial software]]<ref>[http://www.univa.com/resources/licenses/univa-support-and-term-software Univa Support and Term Software license]</ref>\n| alexa                  = \n| website                = {{URL|www.univa.com/products}}\n}}\n'''[[Univa]] Grid Engine''' is a [[batch-queuing system]], forked from [[Sun Grid Engine]] (SGE).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hpcinthecloud.com/features/Grid-Engine-Finds-Safe-Harbor-in-Univa-114125534.html | title=Grid Engine Finds Safe Harbor at Univa | work=HPC in the Cloud | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Gentzsch, Wolfgang}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/01/18/univa_forks_oracle_grid_engine/ | title=Univa forks Oracle's Sun Grid Engine | work=The Register | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Morgan, Timothy Prickett}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hpcwire.com/features/Univa-Rescues-Grid-Engine-From-Oracle-114140804.html | title=Univa Rescues Grid Engine From Oracle | work=HPCwire | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Feldman, Michael | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110124052006/http://www.hpcwire.com/features/Univa-Rescues-Grid-Engine-From-Oracle-114140804.html | archive-date=January 24, 2011 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The software schedules resources in a [[data center]] applying user-configurable policies to help improve resource sharing and throughput by maximizing resource utilization. The product can be deployed to run on-premises, using IaaS [[cloud computing]] or in a hybrid cloud environment.\n\n== History ==\nThe roots of Grid Engine as a commercial product date back to 1993 (under the names CODINE and later, in a variation of the product, GRD). A more comprehensive genealogy of the product is described in [[Sun Grid Engine]]. Grid Engine was first distributed by Genias Software and from 1999, after a company merger, by Gridware, Inc. In 2000, [[Sun Microsystems]] acquired Gridware.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun.com/smi/Press/sunflash/2000-07/sunflash.20000724.3.xml|title=Gridware's resource management software increases efficiency and productivity in compute-intensive technical computing environments|date=2000-07-24|publisher=Sun Microsystems}}</ref>  Sun renamed CODINE/GRD as Sun Grid Engine later that year, and released it as [[open-source software|open-source]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun.com/smi/Press/sunflash/2001-07/sunflash.20010723.1.xml|title=Sun Microsystems makes SUN GRID ENGINE software available to open source community|date=2001-07-23|publisher=Sun Microsystems}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Oracle Corporation]] acquired Sun and subsequently renamed SGE to [[Oracle Grid Engine]]. Oracle Grid Engine (6.2u6) moved to a closed-source model providing binaries with the distribution but no source code. As a result, the project's open-source repository no longer reflected changes made by Oracle and users were prevented from contributing code changes. In response to this, the Grid Engine community started the Open Grid Scheduler and the Son of Grid Engine projects to continue to develop and maintain a free implementation of Grid Engine.<ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/gridscheduler/ Open Grid Scheduler]</ref><ref>[https://arc.liv.ac.uk/trac/SGE Son of Grid Engine]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linux-mag.com/id/7850|title=The State of Oracle/Sun Grid Engine|first=Douglas|last=Eadline, Ph.D.|date=September 1, 2010|accessdate=2011-01-18|publisher=Linux Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://markmail.org/message/hcxond5s4cywe5dv|title=Changes for a Bright Future at Oracle|first=Daniel|last=Templeton|date=2010-12-23|accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, [[Univa]] announced that it had hired the principal engineers from the Sun Grid Engine team.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/| title=Univa Acquires Grid Engine Expertise | publisher=Univa | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>  Univa Grid Engine development is led by CTO Fritz Ferstl, who founded the Grid Engine project and ran the business within Sun/Oracle for the past 10 years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.univa.com/about/| title=Biography of Fritz Ferstl | publisher=Univa | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2013 [[Univa]] announced that it had acquired Oracle Grid Engine assets and intellectual property making it the sole commercial provider of Grid Engine software.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/about/news/press_2013/10222013.php| title=Univa completes acquisition of Grid Engine assets | publisher=Univa | date=2013-10-22 | accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2011 and 2013 Univa added new capabilities to Univa Grid Engine including Univa Unisight<ref>{{cite press_release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20111004006175/en/Univa-Widens-Grid-Engine-Gap | title=Univa Widens Grid Engine Gap  | publisher=businesswire | date=2011-10-11 | accessdate=October 11, 2011}}</ref>, and Univa License Orchestrator.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130618005372/en/Univa-Releases-License-Orchestrator-Integrated-Univa-Grid| title=Univa Releases License Orchestrator Integrated with Univa Grid Engine to Reduce and Optimize Software License Expenses | publisher=businesswire | date=2013-06-18 | accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nUniva Unisight provided new reporting and analytics capabilities related to of Univa Grid Engine workloads and infrastructure. Univa License Orchestrator extended Univa Grid Engine scheduling policies to support allocation and optimization of commercial software licenses, an important capability in [[Electronic Design Automation]] (EDA) and other industries.\n\nOn June 24, 2018 [[Univa]] announced massive scalability operating a single cluster with over 1 million cores on [[Amazon Web Services|AWS]].<ref>{{cite blog | url=https://blogs.univa.com/2018/06/univa-demonstrates-extreme-scale-automation-by-deploying-more-than-one-million-cores-in-a-single-univa-grid-engine-cluster-using-aws/ | title=Univa Demonstrates Extreme Scale Automation by Deploying More Than One Million Cores in a Single Univa Grid Engine Cluster using AWS | publisher=Univa | date=2018-06-24 | accessdate=June 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Releases ==\nUniva Grid Engine 8.0 was Univa\u2019s first commercial release of Grid Engine, offered on April 12, 2011.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110412005977/en/Univa-Grid-Engine-8.0 | title=Univa Grid Engine 8.0 Now Available | publisher=Univa | date=2011-04-12 | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>  It was [[Fork (software development)|forked]] from SGE 6.2u5, the last open source release.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wheregridenginelives.com/content/rebirth-continuity-and-expansion-univa-grid-engine-v80 | title=Rebirth, Continuity and Expansion - Univa Grid Engine v8.0 | publisher=Univa | date=2011-04-12 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Ferstl, Fritz}}</ref> It added improved third party application integration, license and policy management, enhanced support for software and hardware platforms, and cloud management tools.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.0.1 was released on October 4, 2011.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/news/| title=Univa Widens Grid Engine Gap | publisher=Univa | date=2011-10-04 | accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref>  It adds improved support for multi-core hardware, integration with NVIDIA GPUs, new job submission verifier extensions, and additional bug fixes.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.1.0 was announced on May 2, 2011 and improvements and bug fixes were made in a series of 8.1.x releases through 8.1.3 announced on Nov 15, 2012. The 8.1.x releases delivered important new functionality such as Job Classes, PostgreSQL Spooling, Resource Maps, and improvements to Share Tree Policies. The releases also introduced a new Fair Urgency Policy, deterministic Wildcard PE Selection, improved Diagnostics, pre-configured MPI integrations, an improved Apache Hadoop Integration <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.univa.com/resources/| title=Univa Grid Engine Integration for Hadoop | publisher=Univa}}</ref> as well as many bug fixes and performance improvements.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.1.6 was announced on Oct 14, 2013. This update included improvements to the Univa Grid Engine scheduler aimed at larger clusters and Qmaster stability and scalability improvements.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.2.0 was released on Sept 02, 2014. Univa Grid Engine version 8.2.0 was the first release to provide native support for Microsoft\u00ae Windows\u00ae environments.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.3.0 was released on June 22, 2015. The new Preemption feature in Univa Grid Engine 8.3.0 allowed users to set priorities on different work so that, if a higher priority application needed to use resources allocated to a lower priority application, the lower priority application would be effectively be \u201cpaused\u201d\u2014not lost\u2014and work would automatically resume once the higher priority application completed. Among a handful of other new features added to Grid Engine 8.3.0 to improve overall reliability and efficiency was a new Run Time Modification of Resources feature. The Run Time Modification of Resources feature enabled cluster administrators to make configuration changes \u201con the fly\u201d improving cluster availability and improving overall efficiency.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.3.1 was released on August 28, 2015. This release contained additional fixes and enhancements identified since the release of 8.3.0.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.4.0 was released on May 31, 2016. This release supports [[Docker (software)|Docker]] containers containers and automatically dispatched and ran jobs within a user specified Docker Image.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.univa.com/about/news/press_2016/05312016.php|title=New Version of Univa Grid Engine|last=univa|website=www.univa.com|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref>\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.5.0 was released on March 7, 2017. This release of Univa Grid Engine provided on average ~2x faster scheduling than open source Grid Engine 6.2u5. Univa Grid Engine 8.5.0 also delivered significant improvements to Docker support including mobility of GPU apps within a cluster.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.0 was released on July 17, 2018. This release added support for NVIDIA Docker 2.0 providing more flexibility when running Docker containers in a Univa Grid Engine environment.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.1 was released on August 8, 2018, providing improved control over GPU devices, and new affinity features, allowing jobs to gravitate towards, or away from, certain compute nodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.univa.com/2018/08/introducing-univa-grid-engine-8-6-1-next-level-enterprise-grade-workload-management/|title=Introducing Univa Grid Engine 8.6.1: Next-Level Enterprise Grade Workload Management|website=blogs.univa.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref>\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.2 was released on August 16, 2018. This release improved Univa Grid Engine performance and scalability in several key areas including network communications, job submission, memory allocation, and scheduler optimizations. This update also improved Univa Grid Engine job dispatch information.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.3 was released on September 27, 2018. This update introduced bulk configuration changes for Univa Grid Engine hosts. Bulk configuration changes perform operations on many hosts simultaneously, making it easier to manage large Univa Grid Engine clusters.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.4 was released on November 23, 2018, providing new core binding strategies making it easier to specify how jobs are placed on nodes and cores while also providing more flexibility. A new affinity-based job placement policy was included in this update. Jobs submitted using affinity can be packed close together (\u201cpositive affinity\u201d) or spread across the cluster (\u201cnegative affinity\u201d) based on resources requested. New Univa Grid Engine Resource Maps syntax provides more granular control over application access to host devices such as NVIDIA GPUs. This allows jobs to request GPUs and ensure that GPUs are exclusively assigned to the specific job. Univa Grid Engine was also enhanced to directly communicate with NVIDIA Data Center GPU Manager (DCGM) in this release to collect GPU metrics for scheduling and accounting.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.5 was released on May 6, 2019. Key new features were:\n\n* Support for IBM Power 9 on Linux\n* Improvements to Docker support on Univa Grid Engine\n* Very large cluster hostname management where the IP address for each host is contained in the hostname\n* Integration with Linux Out of Memory (OOM) Notification API ensuring that Univa Grid Engine is automatically notified of jobs that are terminated by the Linux kernel\n* Improved responsiveness in heavily loaded cluster for Grid Engine administrator commands\n* Performance improvements to Univa Grid Engine automatic job rescheduling\n* Thread deadlock detection for Univa Grid Engine Qmaster\n* Updated support for NVIDIA DCGM versions up to 1.6.3\n* Ability to specify GPU/CPU affinity as hard or soft requests\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.7 was released on August 5, 2019offering Red Hat Enterprise Linux 8 (RHEL8) support and NVIDIA GPU DCGM job usage features.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.8 was released on December 12, 2019, providing new parameters to fine-tine scheduling wildcard requests, support for Linux mount namespaces and GPU usage reporting.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.9 was released on February 10, 2020, providing enhancements to the qconf command and improved information and messaging collection.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.11 was released on March 17, 2020 delivering improved Docker compatibility, job reporting and monitoring and increased support for the latest version of DCGM.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Job scheduler#Batch queuing for HPC clusters|Job Scheduler and Batch Queuing for Clusters]]\n<!-- sort alphabetically: -->\n* [[Beowulf cluster]]\n* [[Maui Cluster Scheduler]]\n* [[Open Source Cluster Application Resources]] (OSCAR)\n* [[Slurm Workload Manager]]\n* [[TORQUE]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.univa.com/products/}}\n* [http://linuxappfinder.com/package/gridengine pointer to repository for old Debian and Ubuntu packages]\n\n[[Category:Grid computing]]\n[[Category:Supercomputers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Batch-queuing system to schedule resources in a data center}}\n{{Infobox software\n| title                  = \n| name                   = Univa Grid Engine Software\n| logo                   = <!-- [[File: ]] -->\n| logo caption           = \n| screenshot             = <!-- [[File: ]] -->\n| caption                = \n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = \n| developer              = [[Univa]]\n| released               = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| discontinued           = \n| latest release version = 8.6.12\n| latest release date    = {{Start date and age|2020|04|15|df=yes/no}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = [[Cross-platform]]\n| platform               = \n| size                   = \n| language               = \n| genre                  = [[Grid computing]] [[Supercomputing]]\n| license                = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]] [[commercial software]]<ref>[http://www.univa.com/resources/licenses/univa-support-and-term-software Univa Support and Term Software license]</ref>\n| alexa                  = \n| website                = {{URL|www.univa.com/products}}\n}}\n'''[[Univa]] Grid Engine''' is a [[batch-queuing system]], forked from [[Sun Grid Engine]] (SGE).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hpcinthecloud.com/features/Grid-Engine-Finds-Safe-Harbor-in-Univa-114125534.html | title=Grid Engine Finds Safe Harbor at Univa | work=HPC in the Cloud | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Gentzsch, Wolfgang}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/01/18/univa_forks_oracle_grid_engine/ | title=Univa forks Oracle's Sun Grid Engine | work=The Register | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Morgan, Timothy Prickett}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hpcwire.com/features/Univa-Rescues-Grid-Engine-From-Oracle-114140804.html | title=Univa Rescues Grid Engine From Oracle | work=HPCwire | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Feldman, Michael | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110124052006/http://www.hpcwire.com/features/Univa-Rescues-Grid-Engine-From-Oracle-114140804.html | archive-date=January 24, 2011 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The software schedules resources in a [[data center]] applying user-configurable policies to help improve resource sharing and throughput by maximizing resource utilization. The product can be deployed to run on-premises, using IaaS [[cloud computing]] or in a hybrid cloud environment.\n\n== History ==\nThe roots of Grid Engine as a commercial product date back to 1993 (under the names CODINE and later, in a variation of the product, GRD). A more comprehensive genealogy of the product is described in [[Sun Grid Engine]]. Grid Engine was first distributed by Genias Software and from 1999, after a company merger, by Gridware, Inc. In 2000, [[Sun Microsystems]] acquired Gridware.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun.com/smi/Press/sunflash/2000-07/sunflash.20000724.3.xml|title=Gridware's resource management software increases efficiency and productivity in compute-intensive technical computing environments|date=2000-07-24|publisher=Sun Microsystems}}</ref>  Sun renamed CODINE/GRD as Sun Grid Engine later that year, and released it as [[open-source software|open-source]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun.com/smi/Press/sunflash/2001-07/sunflash.20010723.1.xml|title=Sun Microsystems makes SUN GRID ENGINE software available to open source community|date=2001-07-23|publisher=Sun Microsystems}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Oracle Corporation]] acquired Sun and subsequently renamed SGE to [[Oracle Grid Engine]]. Oracle Grid Engine (6.2u6) moved to a closed-source model providing binaries with the distribution but no source code. As a result, the project's open-source repository no longer reflected changes made by Oracle and users were prevented from contributing code changes. In response to this, the Grid Engine community started the Open Grid Scheduler and the Son of Grid Engine projects to continue to develop and maintain a free implementation of Grid Engine.<ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/gridscheduler/ Open Grid Scheduler]</ref><ref>[https://arc.liv.ac.uk/trac/SGE Son of Grid Engine]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linux-mag.com/id/7850|title=The State of Oracle/Sun Grid Engine|first=Douglas|last=Eadline, Ph.D.|date=September 1, 2010|accessdate=2011-01-18|publisher=Linux Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://markmail.org/message/hcxond5s4cywe5dv|title=Changes for a Bright Future at Oracle|first=Daniel|last=Templeton|date=2010-12-23|accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, [[Univa]] announced that it had hired the principal engineers from the Sun Grid Engine team.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/| title=Univa Acquires Grid Engine Expertise | publisher=Univa | date=2011-01-18 | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>  Univa Grid Engine development is led by CTO Fritz Ferstl, who founded the Grid Engine project and ran the business within Sun/Oracle for the past 10 years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.univa.com/about/| title=Biography of Fritz Ferstl | publisher=Univa | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2013 [[Univa]] announced that it had acquired Oracle Grid Engine assets and intellectual property making it the sole commercial provider of Grid Engine software.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/about/news/press_2013/10222013.php| title=Univa completes acquisition of Grid Engine assets | publisher=Univa | date=2013-10-22 | accessdate=October 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2011 and 2013 Univa added new capabilities to Univa Grid Engine including Univa Unisight<ref>{{cite press_release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20111004006175/en/Univa-Widens-Grid-Engine-Gap | title=Univa Widens Grid Engine Gap  | publisher=businesswire | date=2011-10-11 | accessdate=October 11, 2011}}</ref>, and Univa License Orchestrator.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130618005372/en/Univa-Releases-License-Orchestrator-Integrated-Univa-Grid| title=Univa Releases License Orchestrator Integrated with Univa Grid Engine to Reduce and Optimize Software License Expenses | publisher=businesswire | date=2013-06-18 | accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nUniva Unisight provided new reporting and analytics capabilities related to of Univa Grid Engine workloads and infrastructure. Univa License Orchestrator extended Univa Grid Engine scheduling policies to support allocation and optimization of commercial software licenses, an important capability in [[Electronic Design Automation]] (EDA) and other industries.\n\nOn June 24, 2018 [[Univa]] announced massive scalability operating a single cluster with over 1 million cores on [[Amazon Web Services|AWS]].<ref>{{cite blog | url=https://blogs.univa.com/2018/06/univa-demonstrates-extreme-scale-automation-by-deploying-more-than-one-million-cores-in-a-single-univa-grid-engine-cluster-using-aws/ | title=Univa Demonstrates Extreme Scale Automation by Deploying More Than One Million Cores in a Single Univa Grid Engine Cluster using AWS | publisher=Univa | date=2018-06-24 | accessdate=June 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Releases ==\nUniva Grid Engine 8.0 was Univa\u2019s first commercial release of Grid Engine, offered on April 12, 2011.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110412005977/en/Univa-Grid-Engine-8.0 | title=Univa Grid Engine 8.0 Now Available | publisher=Univa | date=2011-04-12 | accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>  It was [[Fork (software development)|forked]] from SGE 6.2u5, the last open source release.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wheregridenginelives.com/content/rebirth-continuity-and-expansion-univa-grid-engine-v80 | title=Rebirth, Continuity and Expansion - Univa Grid Engine v8.0 | publisher=Univa | date=2011-04-12 | accessdate=April 17, 2011 | author=Ferstl, Fritz}}</ref> It added improved third party application integration, license and policy management, enhanced support for software and hardware platforms, and cloud management tools.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.0.1 was released on October 4, 2011.<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.univa.com/news/| title=Univa Widens Grid Engine Gap | publisher=Univa | date=2011-10-04 | accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref>  It adds improved support for multi-core hardware, integration with NVIDIA GPUs, new job submission verifier extensions, and additional bug fixes.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.1.0 was announced on May 2, 2011 and improvements and bug fixes were made in a series of 8.1.x releases through 8.1.3 announced on Nov 15, 2012. The 8.1.x releases delivered important new functionality such as Job Classes, PostgreSQL Spooling, Resource Maps, and improvements to Share Tree Policies. The releases also introduced a new Fair Urgency Policy, deterministic Wildcard PE Selection, improved Diagnostics, pre-configured MPI integrations, an improved Apache Hadoop Integration <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.univa.com/resources/| title=Univa Grid Engine Integration for Hadoop | publisher=Univa}}</ref> as well as many bug fixes and performance improvements.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.1.6 was announced on Oct 14, 2013. This update included improvements to the Univa Grid Engine scheduler aimed at larger clusters and Qmaster stability and scalability improvements.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.2.0 was released on Sept 02, 2014. Univa Grid Engine version 8.2.0 was the first release to provide native support for Microsoft\u00ae Windows\u00ae environments.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.3.0 was released on June 22, 2015. The new Preemption feature in Univa Grid Engine 8.3.0 allowed users to set priorities on different work so that, if a higher priority application needed to use resources allocated to a lower priority application, the lower priority application would be effectively be \u201cpaused\u201d\u2014not lost\u2014and work would automatically resume once the higher priority application completed. Among a handful of other new features added to Grid Engine 8.3.0 to improve overall reliability and efficiency was a new Run Time Modification of Resources feature. The Run Time Modification of Resources feature enabled cluster administrators to make configuration changes \u201con the fly\u201d improving cluster availability and improving overall efficiency.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.3.1 was released on August 28, 2015. This release contained additional fixes and enhancements identified since the release of 8.3.0.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.4.0 was released on May 31, 2016. This release supports [[Docker (software)|Docker]] containers and will automatically dispatch and run jobs with a user specified Docker Image.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.univa.com/about/news/press_2016/05312016.php|title=New Version of Univa Grid Engine|last=univa|website=www.univa.com|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref>\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.5.0 was released on March 7, 2017. This release of Univa Grid Engine is 2x faster than open source Grid Engine 6.2u5. Grid Engine 8.5.0 also includes significant improvement to Docker support including mobility of GPU apps within the cluster.\n\n8.6.0 was released on July 17, 2018. Univa Grid Engine now supports NVIDIA Docker 2.0. The new Univa Grid Engine Docker integration allows for more flexibility when running Docker containers in a Univa Grid Engine environment.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.1 was released on August 8, 2018, providing improved control over GPU devices, and new affinity features, allowing jobs to gravitate towards, or away from, certain compute nodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.univa.com/2018/08/introducing-univa-grid-engine-8-6-1-next-level-enterprise-grade-workload-management/|title=Introducing Univa Grid Engine 8.6.1: Next-Level Enterprise Grade Workload Management|website=blogs.univa.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref>\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.2 was released on August 16, 2018. This release improved Univa Grid Engine performance and scalability in several key areas including network communications, job submission, memory allocation, and scheduler optimizations. This update also improved Univa Grid Engine job dispatch information.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.3 was released on September 27, 2018. This update introduced bulk configuration changes for Univa Grid Engine hosts. Bulk configuration changes perform operations on many hosts simultaneously, making it easier to manage large Univa Grid Engine clusters.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.4 was released on November 23, 2018, providing new core binding strategies making it easier to specify how jobs are placed on nodes and cores while also providing more flexibility. A new affinity-based job placement policy was included in this update. Jobs submitted using affinity can be packed close together (\u201cpositive affinity\u201d) or spread across the cluster (\u201cnegative affinity\u201d) based on resources requested. New Univa Grid Engine Resource Maps syntax provides more granular control over application access to host devices such as NVIDIA GPUs. This allows jobs to request GPUs and ensure that GPUs are exclusively assigned to the specific job. Univa Grid Engine was also enhanced to directly communicate with NVIDIA Data Center GPU Manager (DCGM) in this release to collect GPU metrics for scheduling and accounting.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.5 was released on May 6, 2019. Key new features were:\n\n* Support for IBM Power 9 on Linux\n* Improvements to Docker support on Univa Grid Engine\n* Very large cluster hostname management where the IP address for each host is contained in the hostname\n* Integration with Linux Out of Memory (OOM) Notification API ensuring that Univa Grid Engine is automatically notified of jobs that are terminated by the Linux kernel\n* Improved responsiveness in heavily loaded cluster for Grid Engine administrator commands\n* Performance improvements to Univa Grid Engine automatic job rescheduling\n* Thread deadlock detection for Univa Grid Engine Qmaster\n* Updated support for NVIDIA DCGM versions up to 1.6.3\n* Ability to specify GPU/CPU affinity as hard or soft requests\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.7 was released on August 5, 2019offering Red Hat Enterprise Linux 8 (RHEL8) support and NVIDIA GPU DCGM job usage features.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.8 was released on December 12, 2019, providing new parameters to fine-tine scheduling wildcard requests, support for Linux mount namespaces and GPU usage reporting.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.9 was released on February 10, 2020, providing enhancements to the qconf command and improved information and messaging collection.\n\nUniva Grid Engine 8.6.11 was released on March 17, 2020 delivering improved Docker compatibility, job reporting and monitoring and increased support for the latest version of DCGM.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Job scheduler#Batch queuing for HPC clusters|Job Scheduler and Batch Queuing for Clusters]]\n<!-- sort alphabetically: -->\n* [[Beowulf cluster]]\n* [[Maui Cluster Scheduler]]\n* [[Open Source Cluster Application Resources]] (OSCAR)\n* [[Slurm Workload Manager]]\n* [[TORQUE]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.univa.com/products/}}\n* [http://linuxappfinder.com/package/gridengine pointer to repository for old Debian and Ubuntu packages]\n\n[[Category:Grid computing]]\n[[Category:Supercomputers]]\n", "name_user": "Nbendov", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReleases:updating version details", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Univa_Grid_Engine"}
{"title_page": "Laura Serrant", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Laura Serrant\n| image         = Prof Laura Serrant.jpg\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = 1963\n| birth_place   = [[Nottingham]], [[United Kingdom]]  \n| nationality   = British\n| other_names   = \n| occupation   = Professor in Nursing \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n\n'''Laura Serrant''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} is a British nurse and academic. She has been [[Professor (highest academic rank)|Professor]] of Nursing and Head of the Nursing department at [[Manchester Metropolitan University]] since 2018.\n\n==Early Life & Career==\nSerrant was born in Nottingham in 1963, the daughter of John Serrant and his wife, born Eudora Toussaint.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=1qFs0NclFlyJ06wzWrSkIA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=24 April 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> She was not only the first in her family to attend university <ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Steve |title=Nursing professor named among UK\u2019s most influential black people |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/research-and-innovation/nursing-professor-named-among-uks-most-influential-black-people-25-10-2019/ |website=Nursing Times |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>, but also one of the first nurses to qualify through a degree, graduating in 1986 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) [[degree in nursing]] from [[Sheffield City Polytechnic]].<ref name=\"bio SHU\">{{cite web|title=Professor Laura Serrant|url=https://www.shu.ac.uk/about-us/our-people/staff-profiles/laura-serrant|website=Sheffield Hallam University|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Focus\">{{cite web|title=Focus on Professor Laura Serrant|url=https://www.shu.ac.uk/research/specialisms/centre-for-health-and-social-care-research/news/focus-on-professor-laura-serrant|website=Sheffield Hallam University|accessdate=24 October 2017|date=20 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Academy\">{{cite web|title=Laura Serrant - Health|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/academy/articles/art20170410160026638|website=BBC Academy|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"RCU\">{{cite web|title=Professor Laura Serrant PhD, MA, BA, RGN, PGCE, Queens Nurse|url=https://www.ecu.ac.uk/profiles/professor-laura-serrant-phd-ma-ba-rgn-pgce-queens-nurse/|website=Equality Challenge Unit|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSerrants work specialises in sexual and reproductive health, including research into working with sex workers, alcohol and drug dependent individuals and tackling attitudes towards HIV and AIDS alongside policy development nationally and internationally with an emphasis on racial inequalities and cultural safety. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Nanrah |first1=Gurjeet |title=Nursing professor from Nottingham named among UK\u2019s most influential black people |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/news/nottingham-news/nursing-professor-nottingham-named-among-3483580 |website=Nottingham Post |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=31 October 2019}}</ref> In 2016, Serrant appeared in [[BBC Four]] documentary ''Black Nurses: The Women Who Saved the NHS'', discussing the contribution and celebrating the influence of Black nurses in the NHS.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Four - Black Nurses: The Women Who Saved the NHS |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b083dgtb |website=BBC |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, then Chief Nursing Officer [[Jane Cummings]] appointed Serrant as Chair of the BME Strategic Advisory Group for NHS England. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Steve |title=CNO assesses five challenges now facing nursing as well as looking back at past five years |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/policies-and-guidance/cno-sets-out-five-main-challenges-lessons-and-achievements-20-03-2017/ |website=Nursing Times |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=20 March 2017}}</ref> Serrant has held a number of posts, having previously been Professor of Community and Public Health Nursing the [[University of Wolverhampton]] and Head of Evidence and Strategy in the Nursing Directorate of [[NHS England]].<ref name=\"bio SHU\" /> She was also [[non executive director]] of [[Sheffield Health & Social Care NHS Foundation Trust|Sheffield Health & Social Care NHS Foundation Trust]] from April 2018 to August 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/prof-laura-serrant-obe-11585341/?originalSubdomain=uk |title=Prof. Laura Serrant OBE \u2014 Global Diversity and Inclusion specialist at lauraserrant.com |work=[[LinkedIn]].com |date=2 December 2019 |accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref> From May 2016 to November 2018 she also served as [[Professor (highest academic rank)|Professor]] of Nursing at [[Sheffield Hallam University]].<ref name=\"bio SHU\" /> \n\nIn 2018 Serrant was appointed as the Head of the School of Nursing at [[Manchester Metropolitan University]] becoming the only black head of nursing in UK Universities.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Steve |title=Nursing professor named among UK\u2019s most influential black people |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/research-and-innovation/nursing-professor-named-among-uks-most-influential-black-people-25-10-2019/ |website=Nursing Times |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOutside of her work in Nursing, Serrant has appeared on [[BBC Radio 4]] programme ''[[Great Lives]]'' where she nominated poet and activist [[Audre Lorde]] as deserving of the title of having lived a 'Great Life'. <ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Radio 4 - Great Lives, Series 45, Laura Serrant on Audre Lorde |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09zxl90 |website=BBC |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> Furthermore, her relationship with poetry continued with the inclusion of a poem written by Serrant in a theatre production titled 'Windrush' which toured the UK in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Zoe |title=Windrush: Movement of the People is both timely and heartfelt |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/windrush-movement-of-the-people-peacock-theatre-dance-review-phoenix-sharon-watson-a8329081.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=30 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Roy |first1=Sanjoy |title=Windrush review \u2013 upbeat tribute to a generation who transformed Britain |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/mar/09/windrush-review-phoenix-dance-theatre |website=The Guardian |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=9 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2014, the [[Health Service Journal]] compiled a list of the 50 people from Black & Minority ethnicities working within the NHS that are inspiring and making a difference and included Serrant for her work in community and public health nursing at the University of Wolverhampton. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Steve |title=List recognises work of leading nurses from BME backgrounds |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/archive/list-recognises-work-of-leading-nurses-from-bme-backgrounds-11-11-2014/ |website=Nursing Times |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 it was announced that Serrant was recognised in the 2018 [[Powerlist]] as the eighth most influential black person in the United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web|title=UK's most influential black person named|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41734289|website=BBC News|accessdate=24 October 2017|date=24 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Professor Laura Serrant|url=http://www.powerlist.co.uk/eight|website=Power List|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>, and in the same year she was awarded an [[honorary doctorate]] by [[Abertay University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Honorary graduates announced |url=https://www.abertay.ac.uk/news/2017/honorary-graduates-announced |website=Abertay University |accessdate=12 June 2018 |date=30 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn the [[2018 Queen's Birthday Honours]], she was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for services to health policy.<ref name=\"LG\">{{London Gazette |issue= 62310 |date= 9 June 2018 |pages= B10\u2013B13 |supp= y }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Knighthood and OBEs for Hallam VC and staff |url=https://www4.shu.ac.uk/mediacentre/knighthood-and-obes-hallam-vc-and-staff |website=Sheffield Hallam University |accessdate=12 June 2018 |date=8 June 2018}}</ref>. Serrant has also been included on the [[Powerlist 2019|2019]] and 2020 Powerlist of the 100 most influential Britons from African/African Carribean decent.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Steve |title=Nursing professor named among UK\u2019s most influential black people |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/research-and-innovation/nursing-professor-named-among-uks-most-influential-black-people-25-10-2019/ |website=Nursing Times |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* {{cite journal |last1=Serrant-Green |first1=L. |title=Inequality in provision of sexual health information |journal=Professional Nurse |date=January 2001 |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=1038\u201342 |pmid=12029731}} \n* {{cite journal |last1=Serrant-Green |first1=Laura |title=Transcultural nursing education: a view from within |journal=Nurse Education Today |date=November 2001 |volume=21 |issue=8 |pages=670\u2013678 |doi=10.1054/nedt.2001.0663|pmid=11884181 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Serrant-Green |first1=Laura |title=Black on black: methodological issues for black researchers working in minority ethnic communities |journal=[[Nurse Researcher]] |date=July 2002 |volume=9 |issue=4 |pages=30\u201344 |doi=10.7748/nr2002.07.9.4.30.c6196}}\n* {{cite journal|authorlink1=Gina Higginbottom |last1=Higginbottom |first1=Gina Marie |last2=Serrant-Green |first2=Laura |title=Developing Culturally Sensitive Skills in Health and Social Care with a Focus on Conducting Research with African Caribbean Communities in England |journal=The Qualitative Report |date=2005 |volume=10 |issue=4 |pages=662\u2013686 |url=http://nsuworks.nova.edu/tqr/vol10/iss4/2/ |accessdate=24 October 2017 |issn=1052-0147}} \n* {{cite journal |last1=Higginbottom |first1=G. M. A. |last2=Mathers |first2=N. |last3=Marsh |first3=P. |last4=Kirkham |first4=M. |last5=Owen |first5=J. M. |last6=Serrant-Green |first6=L. |title=Young people of minority ethnic origin in England and early parenthood: views from young parents and service providers |journal=[[Social Science & Medicine]] |date=August 2006 |volume=63 |issue=4 |pages=858\u2013870 |doi=10.1016/j.socscimed.2006.03.011}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Serrant-Green |first1=Laura |title=Ethnographic research |journal=[[Nurse Researcher]] |date=April 2007 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=4\u20136 |doi=10.7748/nr2007.04.14.3.4.c6027}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Serrant-Green |first1=Laura |title=The sound of 'silence': a framework for researching sensitive issues or marginalised perspectives in health |journal=[[Journal of Research in Nursing]] |date=16 November 2010 |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=347\u2013360 |doi=10.1177/1744987110387741}}\n== External links ==\n* [[https://www.england.nhs.uk/author/professor-laura-serrant/]] NHS Profile\n* [[https://www2.mmu.ac.uk/hpsc/our-staff/browse/department-of-nursing/profile/index.php?id=4035]] Manchester Metropolitan University Profile\n* [[https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=MsKRkL4AAAAJ&hl=en]] Publications at Google Schollar\n* {{IMDb name|id=10530297|name=Laura Serrant}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}{{UK-med-bio-stub}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Serrant, Laura}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:English nurses]]\n[[Category:Nursing researchers]]\n[[Category:British women nurses]]\n[[Category:Academics of Sheffield Hallam University]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Wolverhampton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sheffield Hallam University]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Laura Serrant\n| image         = Prof Laura Serrant.jpg\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = 1963\n| birth_place   = [[Nottingham]], [[United Kingdom]]  \n| nationality   = British\n| other_names   = \n| occupation   = Professor in Nursing \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n\n'''Laura Serrant''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} is a British nurse and academic. She has been [[Professor (highest academic rank)|Professor]] of Nursing and Head of the Nursing department at [[Manchester Metropolitan University]] since 2018.\n\n==Early Life & Career==\nSerrant was born in Nottingham in 1963, the daughter of John Serrant and his wife, born Eudora Toussaint.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=1qFs0NclFlyJ06wzWrSkIA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=24 April 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> She was not only the first in her family to attend university <ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Steve |title=Nursing professor named among UK\u2019s most influential black people |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/research-and-innovation/nursing-professor-named-among-uks-most-influential-black-people-25-10-2019/ |website=Nursing Times |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>, but also one of the first nurses to qualify through a degree, graduating in 1986 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) [[degree in nursing]] from [[Sheffield City Polytechnic]].<ref name=\"bio SHU\">{{cite web|title=Professor Laura Serrant|url=https://www.shu.ac.uk/about-us/our-people/staff-profiles/laura-serrant|website=Sheffield Hallam University|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Focus\">{{cite web|title=Focus on Professor Laura Serrant|url=https://www.shu.ac.uk/research/specialisms/centre-for-health-and-social-care-research/news/focus-on-professor-laura-serrant|website=Sheffield Hallam University|accessdate=24 October 2017|date=20 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Academy\">{{cite web|title=Laura Serrant - Health|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/academy/articles/art20170410160026638|website=BBC Academy|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"RCU\">{{cite web|title=Professor Laura Serrant PhD, MA, BA, RGN, PGCE, Queens Nurse|url=https://www.ecu.ac.uk/profiles/professor-laura-serrant-phd-ma-ba-rgn-pgce-queens-nurse/|website=Equality Challenge Unit|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSerrants work specialises in sexual and reproductive health, including research into working with sex workers, alcohol and drug dependent individuals and tackling attitudes towards HIV and AIDS alongside policy development nationally and internationally with an emphasis on racial inequalities and cultural safety. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Nanrah |first1=Gurjeet |title=Nursing professor from Nottingham named among UK\u2019s most influential black people |url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/news/nottingham-news/nursing-professor-nottingham-named-among-3483580 |website=Nottingham Post |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=31 October 2019}}</ref> In 2016, Serrant appeared in [[BBC Four]] documentary ''Black Nurses: The Women Who Saved the NHS'', discussing the contribution and celebrating the influence of Black nurses in the NHS.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Four - Black Nurses: The Women Who Saved the NHS |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b083dgtb |website=BBC |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, then Chief Nursing Officer [[Jane Cummings]] appointed Serrant as Chair of the BME Strategic Advisory Group for NHS England. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Steve |title=CNO assesses five challenges now facing nursing as well as looking back at past five years |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/policies-and-guidance/cno-sets-out-five-main-challenges-lessons-and-achievements-20-03-2017/ |website=Nursing Times |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=20 March 2017}}</ref> Serrant has held a number of posts, having previously been Professor of Community and Public Health Nursing the [[University of Wolverhampton]] and Head of Evidence and Strategy in the Nursing Directorate of [[NHS England]].<ref name=\"bio SHU\" /> She was also [[non executive director]] of [[Sheffield Health & Social Care NHS Foundation Trust|Sheffield Health & Social Care NHS Foundation Trust]] from April 2018 to August 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/prof-laura-serrant-obe-11585341/?originalSubdomain=uk |title=Prof. Laura Serrant OBE \u2014 Global Diversity and Inclusion specialist at lauraserrant.com |work=[[LinkedIn]].com |date=2 December 2019 |accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref> From May 2016 to November 2018 she also served as [[Professor (highest academic rank)|Professor]] of Nursing at [[Sheffield Hallam University]].<ref name=\"bio SHU\" /> \n\nIn 2018 Serrant was appointed as the Head of the School of Nursing at [[Manchester Metropolitan University]] becoming the only black head of nursing in UK Universities.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Steve |title=Nursing professor named among UK\u2019s most influential black people |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/research-and-innovation/nursing-professor-named-among-uks-most-influential-black-people-25-10-2019/ |website=Nursing Times |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOutside of her work in Nursing, Serrant has appeared on [[BBC Radio 4]] programme ''[[Great Lives]]'' where she nominated poet and activist [[Audre Lorde]] as deserving of the title of having lived a 'Great Life'. <ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Radio 4 - Great Lives, Series 45, Laura Serrant on Audre Lorde |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09zxl90 |website=BBC |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> Furthermore, her relationship with poetry continued with the inclusion of a poem written by Serrant in in a theatre production titled 'Windrush' which toured the UK in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Zoe |title=Windrush: Movement of the People is both timely and heartfelt |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/windrush-movement-of-the-people-peacock-theatre-dance-review-phoenix-sharon-watson-a8329081.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=30 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Roy |first1=Sanjoy |title=Windrush review \u2013 upbeat tribute to a generation who transformed Britain |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/mar/09/windrush-review-phoenix-dance-theatre |website=The Guardian |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=9 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2014, the [[Health Service Journal]] compiled a list of the 50 people from Black & Minority ethnicities working within the NHS that are inspiring and making a difference and included Serrant for her work in community and public health nursing at the University of Wolverhampton. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Steve |title=List recognises work of leading nurses from BME backgrounds |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/archive/list-recognises-work-of-leading-nurses-from-bme-backgrounds-11-11-2014/ |website=Nursing Times |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 it was announced that Serrant was recognised in the 2018 [[Powerlist]] as the eighth most influential black person in the United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web|title=UK's most influential black person named|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41734289|website=BBC News|accessdate=24 October 2017|date=24 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Professor Laura Serrant|url=http://www.powerlist.co.uk/eight|website=Power List|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>, and in the same year she was awarded an [[honorary doctorate]] by [[Abertay University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Honorary graduates announced |url=https://www.abertay.ac.uk/news/2017/honorary-graduates-announced |website=Abertay University |accessdate=12 June 2018 |date=30 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn the [[2018 Queen's Birthday Honours]], she was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for services to health policy.<ref name=\"LG\">{{London Gazette |issue= 62310 |date= 9 June 2018 |pages= B10\u2013B13 |supp= y }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Knighthood and OBEs for Hallam VC and staff |url=https://www4.shu.ac.uk/mediacentre/knighthood-and-obes-hallam-vc-and-staff |website=Sheffield Hallam University |accessdate=12 June 2018 |date=8 June 2018}}</ref>. Serrant has also been included on the [[Powerlist 2019|2019]] and 2020 Powerlist of the 100 most influential Britons from African/African Carribean decent.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ford |first1=Steve |title=Nursing professor named among UK\u2019s most influential black people |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/research-and-innovation/nursing-professor-named-among-uks-most-influential-black-people-25-10-2019/ |website=Nursing Times |accessdate=21 April 2020 |language=en |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* {{cite journal |last1=Serrant-Green |first1=L. |title=Inequality in provision of sexual health information |journal=Professional Nurse |date=January 2001 |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=1038\u201342 |pmid=12029731}} \n* {{cite journal |last1=Serrant-Green |first1=Laura |title=Transcultural nursing education: a view from within |journal=Nurse Education Today |date=November 2001 |volume=21 |issue=8 |pages=670\u2013678 |doi=10.1054/nedt.2001.0663|pmid=11884181 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Serrant-Green |first1=Laura |title=Black on black: methodological issues for black researchers working in minority ethnic communities |journal=[[Nurse Researcher]] |date=July 2002 |volume=9 |issue=4 |pages=30\u201344 |doi=10.7748/nr2002.07.9.4.30.c6196}}\n* {{cite journal|authorlink1=Gina Higginbottom |last1=Higginbottom |first1=Gina Marie |last2=Serrant-Green |first2=Laura |title=Developing Culturally Sensitive Skills in Health and Social Care with a Focus on Conducting Research with African Caribbean Communities in England |journal=The Qualitative Report |date=2005 |volume=10 |issue=4 |pages=662\u2013686 |url=http://nsuworks.nova.edu/tqr/vol10/iss4/2/ |accessdate=24 October 2017 |issn=1052-0147}} \n* {{cite journal |last1=Higginbottom |first1=G. M. A. |last2=Mathers |first2=N. |last3=Marsh |first3=P. |last4=Kirkham |first4=M. |last5=Owen |first5=J. M. |last6=Serrant-Green |first6=L. |title=Young people of minority ethnic origin in England and early parenthood: views from young parents and service providers |journal=[[Social Science & Medicine]] |date=August 2006 |volume=63 |issue=4 |pages=858\u2013870 |doi=10.1016/j.socscimed.2006.03.011}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Serrant-Green |first1=Laura |title=Ethnographic research |journal=[[Nurse Researcher]] |date=April 2007 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=4\u20136 |doi=10.7748/nr2007.04.14.3.4.c6027}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Serrant-Green |first1=Laura |title=The sound of 'silence': a framework for researching sensitive issues or marginalised perspectives in health |journal=[[Journal of Research in Nursing]] |date=16 November 2010 |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=347\u2013360 |doi=10.1177/1744987110387741}}\n== External links ==\n* [[https://www.england.nhs.uk/author/professor-laura-serrant/]] NHS Profile\n* [[https://www2.mmu.ac.uk/hpsc/our-staff/browse/department-of-nursing/profile/index.php?id=4035]] Manchester Metropolitan University Profile\n* [[https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=MsKRkL4AAAAJ&hl=en]] Publications at Google Schollar\n* {{IMDb name|id=10530297|name=Laura Serrant}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}{{UK-med-bio-stub}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Serrant, Laura}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:English nurses]]\n[[Category:Nursing researchers]]\n[[Category:British women nurses]]\n[[Category:Academics of Sheffield Hallam University]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Wolverh